        The biggest issue was cultural interaction, which was limited by ease
 of contact.  If the Europeans had not been sufficently motivated to emabrk
 on the Crusades, the hardships involved in making contact would have
 continued to allow uneven technology growth.  However, once the gap had been
 bridged, then trade allowed ideas to flow both ways.

        Same problem in the Imperium.  Until two neighbouring cultures/ worlds
 have a reason to regularly bridge the gap between them, they can be vastly
 different in TL and conceptualization of tech.

        I am running a TL10 game with Earth as the centre of Terran Sphere.
 There are two other spacefaring cultures within about 200ly of Earth, and
 all three are blissfully unawares of each other, simply because of scale
 distance involved.  When they finally *do* bump into each other, it will be
 *decades* before enough interchange has occured for one side to influence
 the TL of the other.

