    'body' => 'Aaron DaMommio wrote:
>What is harder to explain is how the Imperium has lagged at TL15 for so long,
>after earlier climbs. I guess a basic Traveller premise is that technological
>change is not steady-and-upward, but that it can level off.

Actually, technological advancement in the Imperium has been roughly one TL
per 300 years (_very_ roughly). Except for the TL 16 to TL 17 jump of the
last 80 years.

>I don\'t really have trouble believing in a universe that is stagnating. It\'s
>just that it seems like the Imperium is a culture that would be continuing to
>progress technologically, and I don\'t see why it has hovered so long at and
>near 15.

It\'s one of those reverse game reasons. _If_ technological developement in
the game progressed like it does in real life then Refs wouldn\'t be able
to envisage the society and players wouldn\'t be able to relate to it
(except for a few gifted individuals who would be too busy writing hugely
succesful SF books). Hence society has to resemble the one we know to some
degree. A plasma handgun may be higher tech than we have today, but it\'s
still basically a gun. you point it and pull the trigger. A "nanocyte
assault weapon" that seek out the target and tries to penetrate his nano-
cyte shield is a bit too weird for me to relate to ("Let\'s see. Your NAW
is TL 54 and his NAS is TL 53. Right. You kill him!") Let alone the gun
that will really exist exist in the year 5600 which I can\'t even begin to
imagine.

So obviously there are some fiendishly difficult research barrierers to
further tech developement waiting just ahead of present-day Terran TL.


Stefan Matthias Aust wrote some very interesting things about tech levels.
However, for Traveller purposes he makes the same mistake that GDW made of
linking TLs to specific time periods in the history of one single planet.
That some things appeared at a particular point in Earth history is simply
a matter of historical chance. Some things could have appeared much earlier
or much later.

My favourite example is the medical technology of surgery. All you really
need to make surgery work is a sharp knife _and the knowledge to keep the
wound sterile_. On Earth germs weren\'t discovered until the microscope, a
TL 4 device, was invented. Hence GDW and Matthias classifies surgery as a
level 4 technology. But if you knew about germs - if someone from another
planet had told you (or if some stone age genius had deduced the way germs
_work_ even if he didn\'t have a clue why it worked that way) - all you
really needed would be a knife and boiling water. Hence _I_ classify
surgery as a level 1 technology.

The mixup comes from confusing discovery TLs and implementation TLs. I
remember a piece I saw on TV where a scientist from our Atomic Research
Station told of a new discovery they had made a couple of years ago (TL 8,
right?) He mentioned that this _could_ have been implemented with the
technology they had had when they started in the 1930ties, only, of course,
they hadn\'t known about it then. So is that TL 8 or TL 6? IMO it\'s TL 6.

>TECH LEVELS
>
>TL0 - Stone Age (-3000 TT)

Egypt was flourishing in 3000 BC.

>Sentient being who discovered fire (or other power), religion (or have other
>explanation), farming and animal handling, who have knowledge of pottery and
>cloth-making and can measure time.
>
>Power: Muscles, human or ox.
>Transportation: Primitive carts.

And dug-out canoes.

>Communication: Story telling.

Wouldn\'t "word of mouth" or "verbal" be more apt?

>Weapon Tech: Stone melee weapons, throwing weapons, bows.
>Medical Science: Not existant.

Curative herbs is available at the lowest tech level.

>Mathematics: Not existant.

All you need for mathematics is a stick and some dirt. (Hides and charcoal
is a sophisticated variant ;-)

>TL1 - Age of Early Civilization (-3000- -400 TT)
>
>Signs of TL1 are primitive forms of civilization: (fortified) cities, laws,
>service occupations, calendar, writing, literature. The being build nations.
>
>Power: Muscles, slaves; watercraft.

What\'s the difference between human muscles and slave muscles?

>Transportation: Horses, costal ships or boats.

Horses can\'t be used at TL 0?

>Communication: Writing, signal fire.

Writing is another one of those crafts that only need a stick and dirt (Or
stone and chisel or wood and knife or...)

>Weapon Tech: Bronze and iron weapons, siege engines.
>Medical Science: Primitive knowledge of body.

In the Traveller universe you can have a copy of Grey\'s anatomy (donated
by an off-worlder) and still be TL 0. Come to that, if some stone age
genius was motivated to acquire a sound knowledge of anatomy then he
could easily do it with only an obsidian knife (And a steady supply of
bodies, of course, but there are no shortage of that at any TL).

>Mathematics: Basic geometry, astronomy

See above.

>TL2 - Era of the Roman Empire (-400-500 TT)
>
>Empire building is the key event to classify a civilization as TL2.

So Egypt was TL 2?

>Advances in military tech, art and architecture.

>Coinage,

Coinage needs metal-working - TL 1.

>written history,

TL 0. And not even just in theory. Remember the Babylonian clay tablets.

>glass

Glass needs fire and sand - TL 0.

>Transporation: Horses with saddle and stirrups, ships.

Stirrups needs metal-working - TL 1.

>Communication: Paper.

As opposed to papyrus? Vellum? What does it take to make paper in quantity?
I\'ll have to look that up.

>Weapon Tech: Iron weapons and armor, siege engines, catapults, greek fire.

Didn\'t we have iron weapons and siege weapons on TL 1?

>Medical Science: Basic knowlege about inner organs, drugs.

See above.

>Mathematics: Geometry, algebra, advanced astronomy.

What is advanced astronomy? Anything like what the Mayans had?

>TL3 - Dark Ages (500-1500 TT)
>
>The name of this era is misleading. This was the high of the Arabian
>culture. This is the beginning of new religions.

I hesitate to tie religions to technology.

>Inventions are porcelain,

Now there\'s something I don\'t know too much about. I thought porcelain was
just a fancy type of pottery.

>optical laws, archs (architecture), compass, spectacles, mirrors, clocks.

Archs were used by the Romans, optical laws, spectacles and mirrors only
need glass to work (Well, mirrors only need smooth metal), clocks are
highly complex devices that need fine metalworking. Is fine metalworking
a higher TL than ordinary metalworking? I\'m inclined to say so, but I can\'t
really back it up.

>Power: Windcraft.

If you can build a watermill you can build a windmill. These two ought to
be on the same level.

>Transportation: horseshoes; ocean ships, sailing and rowing.

Horseshoes: metalworking - TL 1.

>Communication: as TL2.
>Weapon Tech: Crossbow, steel weapons, knights, black powder, cannons.

Gunpowder itself is TL 0, of course, but cannon needs some good knowledge
of metalworking.

>Medical Science: Diagnostics, understanding of body, healing drugs.
>Mathematics: Decimal system, Zero.

See above.

>TL4 - Age of Discoveries (1500-1800 TT)
>
>Signs of TL4 are black powder weapons, exploration and discoveries. Mind of
>people changed.

"Mind of people changed\'? Not really a TL issue, is it?

>Power: as TL3.

Somewhere in there you\'ve missed one of the most significant discoveries:
The horse collar. That made a horse more effective than human beings for
driving pumps etc. Of course, for implementation purposes it\'s still only
TL 0 (Leather work).

>Communication: Printing, signal stations.

Printing type needs metalwork. Carving letters in a piece of wood and
printing is TL 0. Signal stations are TL 0 (The telescope makes signal
stations more effective, though).

>TL5 - Era of Colonialism and Imperialism (1800-1900 TT)

>Transportation: Steam ships, railways, bicycle.

I would think that a bicycle would be possible with fairly crude metalwork,
but I may be mistaken.



>TL13 - The Long Night (-1500-200 IC)

TL 13 didn\'t arise until after the Long Night.



