    'body' => '
This topic has sparked some great contributions. Recent comments seem to
prove pretty convincingly that the Imperium has never been stagnating -- looks
like it\'s my ignorance of tech level changes that is at fault.

With the information folks have provided, I now have a much better picture of
the Imperium\'s historical growth.

Hans makes some great points about problems with the concept of tech level,
The distinction between implementation TL and discovery TL is a good one.

Another way to improve a TL description of a world would be to list different
levels for different areas of technology-- Medical TL 10, Military TL 13, and
Transportation TL 11, for example. Or you could write anywhere from a
paragraph to a page describing the technologies available to a culture. If you
use the TL concept, it\'s got to be recognized as a shortcut.

Another thing to approach here that might be more relevant would be
economics. Given that it is pretty expensive to move about in Traveller,
(although much cheaper than any real method of interstellar travel we can
currently extrapolate), I would think that local availablility of resources
would drive the availability of certain technologies more than knowledge.
Knowledge would be the cheapest thing to transport.

Actually, it\'s hard to understand how interstellar trade makes much sense.
Much of the CT material has things like wine and exotic meats being traded
around (I\'m specifically thinking of The Traveller Adventure) and that doesn\'t
make much sense to me. However, in play I don\'t think I\'d much want to call
that into question. If anyone wants to rattle off a justification for this,
I\'d be interested to read it. I think a universe in which few goods but lots
of info are moved around makes more sense as an actual extrapolation of our
present, but when it comes to a game milieu, I\'d hate to give up Free Traders
and the adventuring opportunities they provide.

--Aaron
