  {
    'topic' => 'Vilani v Terran TL',
    'body' => 'Hi there

 Phillip McGregor suggested that the Vilani Empire would have been
better off after it was conquered due to the "untrammelled Terran
techno" advance.  This assumes that technological progress is good,
absolutely regardless of its effects.  The Vilani Empire wasn\'t
suffering from the control of technological development as such, but
the stagnation, and the perception that technological progress was
bad, regardless of its effects.  This is where the essential
difference between Solomani and Vilani thinking effects technology;
the former forges on, even when technology is damaging the environment
and needlesly killing people, while the latter holds back, even when
technology could save people\'s lives and increase their standard of
living.

In MT, it was suggested that the success of the Imperium was due in
part to a synthesis or symbiosis of the Vilani and Solomani heritage
in the empire.  The Solomani urge to make changes and "advance" was
balanced by the Vilani wish to stick to what was known and be "careful
of change".  I don\'t know if this a correct sociological analysis of
the Third Imperium, but it\'ll do.

The Imperium went from about TL 12 to TL 15 in about 1000 years; is
that really a slow progress (as some seem to think).  How long did it
take Europe to go from TL 0 to TL 4?  In the twentieth century, we
have probably advanced from TL 4 to TL 8(ish), but perhaps we are not
typical.  Trying to come up with a theory of technological development
rates for an 11,000 world empire (and all the surrounding worlds) from
the experiences of a single world in a single century is v dodgy!
Social and political effects are probably stronger than we think.
There was a good book called the something or other Rose (sorry, can\'t
remember the title or the author) which posulated a Europe which never
underwent technological advances due to various fundamental
sociopolitical events going different ways.  The Catholic Church
remained in its Inquisition phase (that is certainly an historical
bogusity on my part), and technolgy was severely circumscribed.  This
was perfectly plausible, and showed a possible way in which social and
political differences can effect technological development.

