    'topic' => ' Tech Levels',
    'body' => 'Hans Rancke-Madsen wrote:

>Stefan Matthias Aust wrote some very interesting things about tech levels.

Thanks :-)

>However, for Traveller purposes he makes the same mistake that GDW made of
>linking TLs to specific time periods in the history of one single planet.

Well, defining TLs only based on describing available technology seemed more
difficult than referencing an example -- earth. Unfortunately, that\'s the
only example we (or at least I) know of. When using this example, we have to
assume, that developing technology isn\'t only a random invention process but
some technology is based on other technology and that there\'s a causal chain
of inventions.

Perhaps you could explain the earth-TL reference with the idea that TLs were
introduced during the Rule of Man and later adopted by the Imperium.

>That some things appeared at a particular point in Earth history is simply
>a matter of historical chance. Some things could have appeared much earlier
>or much later.

But they haven\'t. Technological advancements aren\'t independent of political
or social events. As I understand, sometimes the "time is ripe" for an
invention. Sometimes, nobody has the right idea. For what reason ever.
Perhaps there\'re other cheaper solutions. Perhaps free thought is forbidden.
Perhaps society is following the wrong ideas (earth is flate).

>[surgery is TL1 if you\'re told how to do it]

The turing maschine (a theoretical computer) could have been invented with
Greek mathematics. However, nobody did it. Probably, the Greeks could have
built primitive calculation maschines if somebody told them how.

>The mixup comes from confusing discovery TLs and implementation TLs.

Yes, a good point. I thought about this and decided to classify the TL based
on the time, when the technology was broadly used. on earth, steam power was
discovered about 50 AD, but nobody realized for what to use it. Time wasn\'t
ripe.

>I remember a piece I saw on TV where a scientist from our Atomic Research
>Station told of a new discovery they had made a couple of years ago (TL 8,
>right?) He mentioned that this _could_ have been implemented with the
>technology they had had when they started in the 1930ties, only, of course,
>they hadn\'t known about it then. So is that TL 8 or TL 6? IMO it\'s TL 6.

That\'s the point. I would classify this TL8 because at TL6 nobody did it. I
didn\'t want theoretical TLs but real (that is on-earth) TLs.

>>TL0 - Stone Age (-3000 TT)
>
>Egypt was flourishing in 3000 BC.

You\'re right. I would classify Egypt as TL1. But most of the remaining world
was still TL0.

>>Transportation: Primitive carts.
>
>And dug-out canoes.

Yes!

>>Communication: Story telling.
>
>Wouldn\'t "word of mouth" or "verbal" be more apt?

Yes! I\'ve to excuse my too basic English vocabulary :-)

>>Medical Science: Not existant.
>
>Curative herbs is available at the lowest tech level.

As I understand, they aren\'t used in a scientific manner but only random. So
I woudn\'t call this use "science."

>>Mathematics: Not existant.
>
>All you need for mathematics is a stick and some dirt. (Hides and charcoal
>is a sophisticated variant ;-)

All you need to invent the zero is copying the "O" and nevertheless it took
centuries to realize that a zero is needed and how to define it.
Mathematics is a science, not only counting.

>>TL1 - Age of Early Civilization (-3000- -400 TT)

>>Power: Muscles, slaves; watercraft.

>What\'s the difference between human muscles and slave muscles?

Slave muscles don\'t work voluntarily :-) Okay, it\'s more a social than a
technical difference.

>>Transportation: Horses, costal ships or boats.
>
>Horses can\'t be used at TL 0?

Well no. Ridding horses are used from about 2000 BC, Asimov\'s Chronology of
Science and Discovery says. That\'s TL1.

>>Communication: Writing, signal fire.
>
>Writing is another one of those crafts that only need a stick and dirt (Or
>stone and chisel or wood and knife or...)

I\'ve to contradict. You\'ve to invent some symbols and define their meaning.
You have to learn this, to teach it and to establish this technology. And I
would call a symbol language only a writing if the symbols are abstract
entities and not concrete pictures.

>In the Traveller universe you can have a copy of Grey\'s anatomy (donated
>by an off-worlder) and still be TL 0.

I feel, you can\'t try to cover off-world contacts with TLs. With my
definition of TL, this off-worlder would raise the local TL to at least 1.

>>TL2 - Era of the Roman Empire (-400-500 TT)

>>written history,
>
>TL 0. And not even just in theory. Remember the Babylonian clay tablets.

To record the own history, you need writing, so I would say TL1. But I
realize, recorded history isn\'t a good sight for TL2. Discard it.

>>glass
>
>Glass needs fire and sand - TL 0.

You need the idea to melt a special kind of sand and the idea what to do
with that hot liquid. But we\'re repeating our arguments.

>>Weapon Tech: Iron weapons and armor, siege engines, catapults, greek fire.
>
>Didn\'t we have iron weapons and siege weapons on TL 1?

No heavy armored soldiers, no siege engines as the Romans built. Precursors
might have exists on TL1 but broadly use was at TL2.

>>TL3 - Dark Ages (500-1500 TT)

>I hesitate to tie religions to technology.

Well, it\'s a way to see the world which is a way how to invent.
But in generally, I would agree with you.

>Archs were used by the Romans.

That were only Roman archs (they couldn\'t bridge more than a few metres).
Here I meant Gothic and Renaissance archs as used when building churches.

>If you can build a watermill you can build a windmill. These two ought to
>be on the same level.

Tell this our ancestors and ask them why no one who used a watermill
invented a windmill :-) Perhaps because slave power was cheaper?

>Somewhere in there you\'ve missed one of the most significant discoveries:
>The horse collar.

Do you know, when on earth this device was invented?

>>TL13 - The Long Night (-1500-200 IC)
>
>TL 13 didn\'t arise until after the Long Night.

>From TL9, my history slightly changed, so my Long Night might not be
comparable to the GDW Long Night. However, I liked the analogy between
TL1-Tl5 and TL11-TL15. As at TL3 the Arabin world made great discoveries, I
assumes that during the Long Night some enclaves of high tech still exists.

Thank you for your comments. I would like to know, what kind of technology
you would classifiy as TL10-TL15 besides jump drives and weapons.

PS: Would you agree with me to classify computers as TL0? Logic gates are
TL0. The needed tubes to implement the gates are TL0 because glass and
copper wire are TL0. Vaccum is probably also TL0. Electricity is TL0 because
lightnings are older than humankind. Punch cards to supply input are easy, a
punch card writer (for output) shouldn\'t be that complicated. An extern
clock to operate the ALU built from tube-gates could be supplied manually.
So with some endurance and some help it should be possible? :-)

bye
--
Stefan Matthias Aust  //  But it\'s gonna be really happening to ya

