The transistor was patented around 1900! Only they didn\'t know *why* it
worked. So they couldn\'t follow up on it. And tubes took over.

> >>TL0 - Stone Age (-3000 TT)
> >
> >Egypt was flourishing in 3000 BC.
>
> You\'re right. I would classify Egypt as TL1. But most of the remaining world
> was still TL0.

Actually, if you are going to go by Earth\'s history, then TL 0 is
actually more like 20,000 to 40,000 BC! That\'s the "Paleolithic" era.
TL 1 is the "Neolilthic" era. (note that the names essentially Latin
for "old stone age" and "new stone age").

The Paleolithic (as I recall) has crude stone tools and hunter/gatherer
cultures. The Neolithic has much more refined tools, domesticated
animals, and agriculture.

The next stages occured at different times in different places, but
only occured in a very few places on Earth. In *all* of them, the key
factor seems to have been *organized* agriculture. In Mesopotamia,
Egypt, China, India, SouthEast Asia, and some locations in the Americas
the pattern was discovering irrigation, which led to the *requirement*
for supervised labor to maintain the irrigation systems. This led to a
ruling class, which led to temples and cities, as well as arithmetic
and writing.

We have *multiple* cases that are considered to be *independent*
inventions of "civilization". Mespototamia (Assyria, Babylon). Egypt.
China. The Indus valley. Cambodia (Angkor Wat). The Maya. The Inca.
Note that the last two are interesting in that they did *not* involve
rivers. The Aztecs were *heavily* influenced by the Maya.

> >>Transportation: Primitive carts.
> >
> >And dug-out canoes.
>
> Yes!

Carts seem to be *late* Neolithic or even early "civilization". Canoes
are late Paleolithic to mid Neolithic technology (check out the
cultures that *used* canoes). Carts require a *lot* more work. And more
to the point, they require *roads*!

> >>Medical Science: Not existant.
> >
> >Curative herbs is available at the lowest tech level.
>
> As I understand, they aren\'t used in a scientific manner but only random. So
> I woudn\'t call this use "science."

Better re-check the historical and anthropological records. Medicine
actually starts in *paleolithic* cultures! Primitive does *not* mean
"dumb". They may not have the scientific method, but they can still
notice cause and effect. They will have *quite* a variety of drugs,
and even some surgical skills.

> >>TL1 - Age of Early Civilization (-3000- -400 TT)

Try 5000 BC!

> >>TL2 - Era of the Roman Empire (-400-500 TT)
>
> >>written history,
> >
