    'topic' => 'Tech levels: When or how?',
    'body' => 'Thor Christensen writes:
>I think it is a real mistake to assume that because components of a thing
>exist at a certain tech level, products that require a combination of those
>same things should be available at that same level.

I\'m mot. I\'m claiming that if the components of some technology is available
at some TL then that technology COULD exist at that TL _given the proper
knowledge_. Why? Because it dosen\'t make sense to rank TLs in the Traveller
universe according to the historical accidents of one single planet, not
even if that planet is Earth. In the Traveller Universe the Ancients spread
humans around on about a 100 worlds, and on about half of these the humans
survived. That gives us 50 histories right there and if even one of them
duplicated Earth\'s tech developements exactly I\'d be very surprised. Then
there\'s litterally hundreds of alien races each with their own histories (I
once calculated that there\'s a minor indigenous race per subsector on the
average (though I confess that I forget just what I based that estimate
on)).

>>>Communication: Writing, signal fire.
>>
>>Writing is another one of those crafts that only need a stick and dirt (Or
>>stone and chisel or wood and knife or...)
>
>Sticks, dirt are available at any tech level.  However, writing, requires
>someone to have an interest in preserving knowledge past tomorrow and
>coming up with a writing convention.  This argues for writing to be available
>in an age where the inmediate concern is not simply surviving past today.

It didn\'t happen at TL 0 on Earth (At least not if you don\'t accept Babylonia
and Egypt as TL 0 societies - which is OK by me). But postulate a world with
some more fertile areas where, say 4 people could gather enough food to keep
5 people alive (4:1 was the proportion of peasants to city-dwellers in the
Middle Ages). Right away you have a leisure class at TL 0. Remember the
"orchards" of Darrien? In that environment the Darrians could easily have
invented writing at a very early stage.

>The same with surgery.  The argument that surgery could occur as soon as
>sentients can wield a knife is a simplistic one.  One can open a body up with
>something as crude as a rock, a sharpened stick or something as advanced
>as a chainsaw. The point is that the person doing the cutting has to have
>developed the idea that cutting into the sentient under the saw will produce
>the effect of curing the patient.

But the idea is not tied to a particular TL. (Indeed, as someone else pointed
out in another message, skulls have been found of people who have had holes
punched into heads and survived.) In the Traveller Universe you have 1000s
of non-interdicted worlds that has nevertheless very low TLs, some of them
even TL 0. How to explain that when they have access to the highest learning
in Charted space? The only explanation that makes sense to me is that
Traveller TLs are not what ideas you have, but what ideas you use. In
other words, what technology has been _implemented_.

>>>Transporation: Horses with saddle and stirrups, ships.
>>
>>Stirrups needs metal-working - TL 1.
>
>They also need some understanding of tanning, horse training and the abilty
>to put the three together...

None of which is beyond the ability of anyone once they get the idea. And I
postulate that the ideas are freely available.

>We understand in a theoretical manner what superconductors can do for us,
>we have the materials knowledge somewhere to put them together, we know
>about transmission of power and the essentials of physics to make it happen,
>but we have not because we have not hit on the right combination.  That might
>take something else htat helps us bring the entire package together.

But if someone came and told us how to do it, could we implement it quickly?
If we could then superconductors are TL 8; if not, they aren\'t.

