Lorenz E. Pogue writes:
>I think your rebuttal is viable but misguided.  Statements like,
>[paraphrasing] "it only takes a stick and dirt to write, TL 0,";  "stirrups
>require metallurgy, TL1";  or "it only takes a copy of Gray\'s anatomy to be
>given to someone...".  All of these type of statements violate a basic rule
>of technological advancement, stepwise increase.  A common language and
>symbol system must be agreed upon before a stick and dirt will suffice.

Yes, but there\'s no reason why someone couldn\'t introduce the idea of writing
into a TL 0 society without further ado. The tools are all there for the
making: Sticks and clay tablets, ink and papyrus, hard stone and softer
stone, flint and wood - all are available at TL 0. You don\'t need steel pens
and paper to write. Oh, and there\'s the Inka system of knots in string.

>Metallurgy (beyond copper which is too soft for stirrups),

Copper and iron are the same TL in Traveller (which may be wrong, but it is).

>Animal husbandry/training (ie "horse" riding), and an advanced concept of
>animal control (more than hopping on an animal to get from A to B, ie
>saddle, bridle, etc) all of these items are prerequisites to the stirrup
>concept.

Sure, but saddles (leatherwork) is surely not a higher TL than ironworking?

>The  suggestion of any introduction of advanced tech level, Gray\'s Anatomy
>is at least TL 5, is an automatic bias. Any person in any previous time
>period who has access to advanced TL would be considered that TL in that
>area.  In other words, a TL0 society with one individual (or culture)
>possesing TL5 medicine.

By that token every Traveller society except those on interdicted worlds
would be TL 15. My point is that the knowledge is available. So TL is _not_
(except for the top "cutting edge" TL) a matter of discoveries, it\'s a
matter of wether or not those discoveries are being used on this or that
particular world.



