    'body' => 'Stefan Matthias Aust writes:
>Hans Rancke-Madsen wrote:
>>However, for Traveller purposes he makes the same mistake that GDW made of
>>linking TLs to specific time periods in the history of one single planet.
>
>Well, defining TLs only based on describing available technology seemed more
>difficult than referencing an example -- earth. Unfortunately, that\'s the
>only example we (or at least I) know of.

Sure, that\'s why GDW did it the same way, I presume. But it\'s still a mistake.
What\'s the point of having 11.000 worlds to stomp around in if they\'re all
going to be copies of Earth? Yet by making the Earth history some kind of
tech developement template, you make it that much more difficult to
introduce worlds with interesting variations.

>When using this example, we have to assume, that developing technology isn\'t
>only a random invention process

Why? There are ample examples of things that are just the result of random
invention processes.

>but some technology is based on other technology and that there\'s a causal
>chain of inventions.

Of course there is. That\'s the whole essense of the concept of TLs, IMO. You
can\'t have TL 5 without some TL 4 foundations, etc. I agree. But the
inventions are already done. We don\'t have to wait for someone to invent
the microscope so that we can discover germs, because in the year 5600 AD
the microscope has been invented scores of times on scores of worlds and
we already know about germs and know how to deal with them.

>>[surgery is TL1 if you\'re told how to do it]
>
>The turing maschine (a theoretical computer) could have been invented with
>Greek mathematics. However, nobody did it. Probably, the Greeks could have
>built primitive calculation maschines if somebody told them how.

But if you are a Referee preparing an adventure on Chaosheo (E87A788-1 in
1117) you couldn\'t care less about what the ancient Greeks did or didn\'t
do. What\'s interesting is wether the Chaosheans can have a turing machine
or not. Can they? Why not? If the ancient Greeks _could_ have invented it
then who\'s to say the Chaoseans didn\'t?

>>The mixup comes from confusing discovery TLs and implementation TLs.
>
>Yes, a good point. I thought about this and decided to classify the TL based
>on the time, when the technology was broadly used. on earth, steam power was
>discovered about 50 AD, but nobody realized for what to use it. Time wasn\'t
>ripe.

But was that because they didn\'t realize what they could have done with it
or because they _couldn\'t_ build steam engins of a useful size with their
metallurgy. If the first, then steam powewr IS possible on a TL 1 world;
if the second the it isn\'t. I think the difference is rather crucial.

>>I remember a piece I saw on TV where a scientist from our Atomic Research
>>Station told of a new discovery they had made a couple of years ago (TL 8,
>>right?) He mentioned that this _could_ have been implemented with the
>>technology they had had when they started in the 1930ties, only, of course,
>>they hadn\'t known about it then. So is that TL 8 or TL 6? IMO it\'s TL 6.
>
>That\'s the point. I would classify this TL8 because at TL6 nobody did it. I
>didn\'t want theoretical TLs but real (that is on-earth) TLs.

But the useful knowledge is wether the natives of Rabwhar/Five Sisters could
have it in 5600 AD or not, not wether the natives of Terra had it in 1930 AD
or not.

>>>Medical Science: Not existant.
>>
>>Curative herbs is available at the lowest tech level.
>
>As I understand, they aren\'t used in a scientific manner but only random. So
>I woudn\'t call this use "science."

They aren\'t? Not on any world in Charted space? Are you sure? Why in the
world(s) not?

>All you need to invent the zero is copying the "O" and nevertheless it took
>centuries to realize that a zero is needed and how to define it.
>Mathematics is a science, not only counting.

But it\'s been done. We\'ve got it now. And we (propably) won\'t ever loose it
again, even if we get bombed back to the stone age.

>>>Transportation: Horses, costal ships or boats.
>>
>>Horses can\'t be used at TL 0?
>
>Well no. Ridding horses are used from about 2000 BC, Asimov\'s Chronology of
>Science and Discovery says. That\'s TL1.

The Plains Indians rode horses using only a blanket and a rope halter. That\'s
1800 AD, but it\'s also TL 0.

>>If you can build a watermill you can build a windmill. These two ought to
>>be on the same level.
>
>Tell this our ancestors and ask them why no one who used a watermill
>invented a windmill :-) Perhaps because slave power was cheaper?

Propably for the same reason why it took centuries from the time lenses
were being ground for glasses before that German chap thought of putting
two of them in front of each other and invented the telescope: Nobody
happened to think of it.

>Thank you for your comments. I would like to know, what kind of technology
>you would classifiy as TL10-TL15 besides jump drives and weapons.

TL 9+ is something GDW defines and is thus less open to debate than the
historical stuff. I do have the notion that Terra today is propably of a
fairly high Computer TL - higher than TL 8, anyway.

>PS: Would you agree with me to classify computers as TL0? Logic gates are
>TL0.

I\'ll grant you that.

>The needed tubes to implement the gates are TL0 because glass and
>copper wire are TL0.

Metalworking is TL 1, isn\'t it? And I did suggest that there might well be
a difference between early metalworking and fine metalworking - possibly
more than one. And there\'s a difference between making glass drinking
vessels and vaccum tubes.

>Vaccum is probably also TL0.

What makes you say that? Could you create a vacuum using only TL 0 tools?

>Electricity is TL0 because lightnings are older than humankind.

Ho ho.

>Punch cards to supply input are easy, a
>punch card writer (for output) shouldn\'t be that complicated. An extern
>clock to operate the ALU built from tube-gates could be supplied manually.
>So with some endurance and some help it should be possible? :-)

A very crude, low-capacity calculator might be possible. In fact, it is.
It\'s called an abacus (and not so crude, either).



