Get the old "Secret of the Ancients" adventure. According to it, the
Ancients were Droyne.

If you don\'t wish to go along with at least *part* of that, then feel
free to make the Ancients one species or many. And describe them as you
see fit.

For what it is worth, Traveller owes a *lot* to Andre Norton\'s books.
And the "Ancients" are clearly based on her "Forerunners". The
Forerunners were\'nt even one *culture* much less one species. It was a
catch-all term for all civilizations that had gone extinct before the
recorded history of any of the *current* civilizations.


"Christopher Weuve" <caw@intercon.com> writes:

> If the company closes down (rather than being shut down by the creditors), an
> the games are not picked up, at what point do they fall into the public
> domain?

All (or at least *most*) of the stuff is copyright by a *company*. That
means they get a straight 50 (or is it 75?) years form copyright date.

CT came out in 1980. So it won\'t be PD until at least 2030.

Anything copyright by the *author* is good for 50( ort is it 75?) years
AFTER THE AUTHOR DIES. Since nnone of them are dead, the clock hasn\'t
even started ticking yet.

Basicly, if it is copyrighted, forget about it becoming PD in your
lifetime.

Simon.Harding@vuw.ac.nz writes:

> I have often considered it a major playability failing of Imperium Traveller
> that there existed worlds that had interstellar contact (in the sense that
> they had a starport of a reasonable rating) yet had very low tech levels. I
> found it difficult to beleive that the technology involved in the starport
> could be kept hidden from the surrounding world. The question always
> followed that if they were able to hide the technology, why would they do
> so? what possible purpose would it serve, for either the starport operators
> or the travellers?

Who says it is hidden? Take a good look around at Earth. We\'ve got
international airport in just about every country, yet aside from the
surrounding "airtown" there are many countries where the tech level
drops *drastically* once you get outside.

It\'s not just a matter of manufacturing capability. It\'s also a matter
of *money*. Many places, there\'s little money to *spend* on high tech
stuff.

And even in "resource rich" areas, what makes you think that the
*natives* are getting the profits from the resources? In some cases,
the *government* is getting a cut, but often that\'s as far as it goes.
The ruler and his cronies have money, and buy high tech stuff (often
things that the country really *doesn\'t* need). The people don\'t see a
lot of it except for the few cheap consumer goods that they can afford
(not even much of that).

You have to consider that much of the "high tech" stuff doesn\'t really
have much *appeal* to the average native. Again, look at things here on
earth. Medicine is wanted, because it solves a problem. Radios are
popular, because they bring useful info, and some entertainment (trust
me, that *is* the order of priorities involved). This in spite if the
*huge* cost of batteries (a reason why radios with solar panels are
popular!)

But laptop computers? What would they use them *for*?

To put it another way, why would *you* want a TL15 neutrino detector?
Unless you are a physicist, it\'s not of any use to you.

> No doubt this is way many of you also referee your games. I still have
> problems with justifying it sometimes. One would expect the gap in TL
> between the world and the imperial norm to close very quickly once contact
> had been made, especially for resource rich worlds.

No more so than it has on earth. It takes *money* to build the
factories, and takes training to staff them. Take a good look at most
third world countries, and even at a lot of countries not usually
considered as such.

Lock of money and training will *always* slow down upgrading the tech
level. And at the lower tech levels, there\'s another factor, not often
considered. Few people in developed countries really *understand* what
terms like "subsistence agriculture" *mean*. It means that you *cannot*
take any significant fraction of the population away from food
production without causing mass starvation. That condition is common to
most TLs up until the equivalent of the 1600s or so.

