    'year' => 1996,
    'from' => 'Ulrikke Ekelund UEkelund@pc.ibt.dk',
    'body' => '6 jan 1996 Marc Miller wrote:

>The industry news about GDW going out of business after 23 years mentions the
>reversion of Harpoon, Johnny Reb, and certain other titles, but their press
>release is not specific about Traveller. The Traveller systems (including
>Classic Traveller, MegaTraveller, and New Era)have reverted, or will revert
>to myself (Marc Miller).
>
>Rest easy, I am working hard at setting the agenda for the coming years. Wish
>me luck, and send me your ideas.

Dear mr. Miller

Okay, here are some ideas that are only in my very humble opinion:

As someone mentioned, it\'d be a good idea to get Thomas Peters back with
Traveller, as he is a great artist and generally influenced the look of the
game in a way I like very much. I can only second that motion. Other great
artists is Michael Vilardi and Blair Reynolds. Rob Caswell also did great
technical drawings.

I don\'t know how many of the original DGP staff is left at that company, but
I think that they all did a great job with the game. Noone mentioned, noone
forgotten, but I think it\'d be a benefit for Traveller to get as many of them
back working on the game.

There has been much discussion wich way to take Traveller now - both
concerning rules and background. In my opinion, DGP did the best Traveller
materials ever with their MegaTraveller line - especially the Alien books,
the Starship Operator\'s Manual and World Builder\'s Handbook. I think it\'d
create great consistency to continue this line. By making new products
compatible with these old products, it would ensure great quality and
immediate playability. I\'d be overdelighted to see Zhodani & Droyne, Hivers &
K\'kree and Humans & Nonhumans published, as well as the advertised Robots &
Cyborgs, not to mention the Clones & Constructs sourcebook, which was only an
idea at the time DGP ended their MT support.

Of course this would probably mean a return to the MT rules and setting.
Personally I love this game beyond all, because it\'s the most technically
consistent game I\'ve ever seen. Granted, there are some wierd rules, but
overall, I love it. I even think the vehicle design rules are great, and it
is quite possible to design vehicles and ships without the use of a computer.

What is most important to me is something with a quality like the DGP alien
modules, preferably consistent with the high quality products (ie. DGP MT
stuff) already made.

Sincerely

Mark Seemann
uekelund@pc.ibt.dk


