I didn\'t post the original quote, nor can I cite the source, but I *can*
corroborate it. In my anthropology course last semester, we saw a film and
read a chapter (well, it was on the syllabus and I\'m sure the people who
paid attention in class did) about a tribe in the Kalahari that lives at a
primitive huinter/gatherer level.

A study was done comparing their claric intake vs. the time they spent
hunting, gathering, preparing food, and so on. It came out to about a 37 or
so hour work week - and they didn\'t seem to have the population problem
postulated in the remainder of your post.

>That seems totally contra-intuitive. Why would anyone change from their
>pleasant pastoral hunter/gather society where they only have to work a
>few hours a day to the back-breaking day-long toil of agriculture?

Because it\'s about as *consistent* as life gets. I can settle ad not have
to worry about whether or not the herds and grasses will be plentiful. I
can settle down and have a more stable lifestyle. The hunter-gatherer may
be moderately more carefree at times, but he never knows just where the
next meal is coming from.

>Now that is manifestly untrue. Throughout recorded history the percentage of
>society that was needed for food production has steadily fallen as technology
>improved (and vice versa).

Right, but more and more labor gets shifted into other roles. Women
rejoiced at the advent of the washing machine until they realized it meant
they had *more clothes* to wash :) Modern telecommunications let us
communicate faster than ever before - but instead of maintaining the same
workload and having more leisure time, we communicate more and accomplish
more in the same amount of time. THat\'s progress :)

>Wait a minute. If one man can gather/hunt enough to survive in two hours,
>then he can gather/hunt enough for 5 people to survive in 10 hours. Thus
>20% of the society can support the rest. In medieval economy it took 4

Not neccesarrily true. Besides, any excess means that those who are
supported can become specialists. If I don\'t have to worry about gathering
food, I can concentrate on something useful, like pottery, metalworking,
number-crunching, diplomacy, or even becoming a thespian :)

Besides which, the figure I was given for these tribesmen wasn\'t
significantly lower than our work week for self-sustenance.

In any case, that\'s it for me. I just thought I\'d say I heard about this
calorie-counting <40 hour work week idea from a fairly reliable source as
well!

