    'day' => '12',
    'date' => 'Fri, 12 Jan 96 18:51:52 PST',
    'body' => 'Hans Rancke-Madsen <rancke@diku.dk> writes:

>Leonard Erickson writes:
>>Remember, here on earth we have numerous examples of *independently
>>evolved* cultures, civilizations and technologies. At TL 0 there are
>>*hundreds*. At TL1 there are still a dozen or so. After that we start
>>getting too much cross-fertilizing.
>>
>>But for TL 0 and TL1 (and even some of TL2) we actually *do* have
>>enough of a sample to make some statements regarding what tech gets
>>developed when.
>
>Yes, and those statements are fairly useless for determining what technology
>can be implemented at any given tech level. In a universe wnere 95% or more
>of all worlds have been _settled_, the mechanics of technological invention
>is fairly irrelevant. As I\'ve stated several times, I\'m postulating that
>the _knowledge_ is freely available. IT DOES NOT HAVE TO BE INVENTED (sorry
>to shout, but I want to make sure it is noticed this time).

Some folks are discussing the way things get invented. The above
applies to *that*.

>>Sorry, you are sufferring from a common misconception. TL0 hunter/gatherers
>>have *more* leisure time than even *we* do. It only takes a few hours a day
>>to provide the necessities of life. The rest of the time is free to do what
>>you want.
>
>Could you give me a quote for that astonishing information? If you did have
>a tribe living in an area where everybody could gather enough to live on in
>a couple of hours, pretty soon the population would increase to the point
>where this was no longer true. Then some or all of the tribe would have to
>go farther afield to collect their vittles and it would take them a few
>extra hours just to move out to collect and to return to the tribe. Pretty
>soon there would be more people, and eventually they would have to spend
>most of each day gathering. Surely the reason for migration (and we know
>that there have been migrations all the way back the long years of human
>pre-history) is to provide food for people who would otherwise starve.

Check out real Neolithic cultures like the Polynesians. They had
controls in place to limit population by *custom*.

Also note the phrase *hunter*. It takes a certain number of people to
run a successful hunt against most larger critters. So unless the tribe
*splits*, anybody who leaves won\'t have enough folks to get everything
done.

>>The introduction of of agriculture *reduces* free time,
>
>That seems totally contra-intuitive. Why would anyone change from their
>pleasant pastoral hunter/gather society where they only have to work a
>few hours a day to the back-breaking day-long toil of agriculture?

To avoid the unpleasant portions of said society. Things like starving
if they overhunt the herds. It may be *harder* to do large scale
farming, but the food supply is steadier.

>>and you don\'t start getting it back until this century.
>
>Now that is manifestly untrue. Throughout recorded history the percentage of
>society that was needed for food production has steadily fallen as technology
>improved (and vice versa).

But I\'m referring to the *amount of time* one has to spend each day
working to either raise food, or do the job that gets you your food.
That jumps *way* up when you start large scale farming, and slowly
decrases from there until quite recently (last century or so), when it
starts dropping rapidly.

>> Agriculture allows more people.
>
>Wait a minute. If one man can gather/hunt enough to survive in two hours,
>then he can gather/hunt enough for 5 people to survive in 10 hours. Thus
>20% of the society can support the rest.

Except for one minor detail. Namely, the "Why should I?" factor. What
incentive is there for those people to spend all day hunting for
someone else? There\'s evidence it did happen to *some* extent. But only
for the craftsmen types. If Joe is really good at chipping flint, it
makes more sense to let him do that and give him a share of the hunt.

But the number of people *needed* for such tasks is limited. So the
number that the rest of the group are willing to support is limited.

>In medieval economy it took 4
>peasants (well, people living outside of cities) to support 1 non-peasant
>(or city-dweller). Of course, he needs a lot more land to do it, but back
>then he did have a lot more land. Your claim just dosen\'t make sense. I
>must be missing some facts. Please provide them.

Agriculture allows higher population densities, not necessarily higher
ratios of food producers to non-food producers.

>>>But in the Traveller Universe the idea dosen\'t have to be invented. They did
>>>that already on Terra... and on Vland... and on Zhdant... and on Darrian...
>>
>>Do you have any idea how *hard* it is to get across the idea of something
>>like this?
>
>No, and I don\'t see what that has to do with the subject under discussion.

Simple. Unless they can *see* a use for most math, they won\'t go to the
trouble of learning it. Please note how few folks *bothered* to learn
to read, write, or do arithnmetic until it was *required*. They figured
they had better things to do with their time.

So as I keep pointing out, lower tech societies are quite likely to not
be *interested* in upgrading their tech level.

>>Once you get them to grasp the idea, they may take it and run with it.
>
>And that\'s exactly what I\'ve been arguing: They _might_. Because writing is
>TL 0, so if the Referee has the local authorities on a TL 0 world whip out a
>bit of papyrus and a _ghifel_ feather and issue the PCs with a pass that
>must be kept at all time on pain of death, he can.

More likely they\'ll be issued a clay tablet stamped with a special
"seal", or some oddly carved token. That is the sort of thing that
would *already* be in use at low tech levels.

A planet that had been settled and "backslid" would be more likely to
keep odd bits of high tech. A planet that had been *contacted*
wouldn\'t.

>>Or they may look at it and say, "Gee, that\'s interesting, but not terribly
>>useful".
>
>So they might. So the Referee is quite entitled to have the aforementioned
>TL 0 society _not_ know about writing. Now what about TL 1 societies? Are
>there any level 1 technologies that absolutely depends on writing in order
>to function? At what point does the Referee _have_ to include writing as a
>local accomplishment? _That\'s_ what interesting about tech levels in the
>Traveller Universe. Not what some 5000 year old Terran society did or did
>not have.

I don\'t have a tech level chart handy, so I can\'t say for sure. But
*record keeping* becomes necessary as soon as you go from individual
plots to "mass agriculture". And record keeping requires both
arithmetic, and at least written *symbols* for things if not actual
writting. Egyptian heiroglyphics are not all that far above that level.

Sureveying starts at that level or a bit above, as does the start of
civil engineering.

>>>>Domesticating animals is another major invention. :-)
>>>
>>>But they can be used at TL 0. I know that for a fact, because the Plains
>>>Indians did it.
>>
>>They are an example of a people "stealing" a useful idea from as more
>>advanced culture. Which shows that tech transfer *does* happen.
>
>AH HA! That is just what I\'ve been arguing that TLs are. A measure of what
>a society can do if they want to. As opposed to what they couldn\'t do even
>if they wanted to, because they did not have the technological basis for
>it.

Well, any "natives aren\'t all that likely to pick up the idea of riding
animals from Imperial contacts, because the Imperials won\'t be riding
animals, they\'ll be riding air-rafts.

>>But only the bits of tech that the low-tech folks can understand and that
>>they *want*.
>
>As for the want, surely that is in the province of the Referee. If he says
>that these people have kept the art of writing alive because they worship
>The Bard of Avon (Never to be mentioned by his True Name on pain of...)
>then who are we to say him nay?

I *really* don\'t think that it\'s all that likely that planets with tech
levels *that* low are populated by folks who were formerly at a high
tech level and lost it. Much more likely is that they came up from
their own stone age, on their own until contact.

Fallen civilations and "new" civilizations have very little in common.
But "fallen" ones should be rare unless you go along with Hard Times and
the Virus.

>>>Yes, but there\'s no reason why someone couldn\'t introduce the idea of writing
>>>into a TL 0 society without further ado. The tools are all there for the
>>>making: Sticks and clay tablets, ink and papyrus, hard stone and softer
>>>stone, flint and wood - all are available at TL 0. You don\'t need steel pens
>>>and paper to write. Oh, and there\'s the Inka system of knots in string.
>
>>But to go back to those Plains Indians... They *didn\'t* steal writing.
>>Why? Because they had no *need* for it!
>
>Again, so what? The Plains Indians didn\'t steal it. What has that got to do
>with TL 0 societies in the year 1115 Imperial? The Plains Indian society has
>been dust for 5000 years. Some Referee\'s players may be visiting the
>Chaoseans tomorrow. It\'s wether _they_ retained it (or imported it) that\'s
>interesting.

Retained is possible, Importing it is unlikely, as they don\'t have any
*need* for it. In fact, they are quite likely to hold the Imperials in
contempt for needing to write things down to remember them.

>>The Inca system is thought to not really be "writing".
>
>But you can imagine a writing system based on knots in strings, can\'t you?
>I can.

Sure. But the information density is *lousy*. :-)

>>But even *those* require a certain level of pre-existing base technology.
>>You can\'t "randomly" invent something until all the parts/materials needed
>>exist.
>
>Of course you can\'t. That\'s the whole basis of tech levels, IMO. When you
>know what tech level a society is, you should know what parts/material it
>can produce and that should tell you what inventions are possible and what
>inventions are not. Those inventions that are possible (but not mandatory)
>at TL X are, I submit, TL X inventions.

True enough. But there\'s a *lot* of spread between when something
becomes *possible* and when it happens. And quite often, the difference
is "theory".

The materials and skills required to create a working radio transmitter
are available clear back in *Roman* times, if not earlier. But there\'s
*no* way anybody at that tech level would invent one randomly, because
even if they built it, they wouldn\'t know what it was good for.

>>>Of course there is. That\'s the whole essense of the concept of TLs, IMO. You
>>>can\'t have TL 5 without some TL 4 foundations, etc. I agree. But the
>>>inventions are already done. We don\'t have to wait for someone to invent
>>>the microscope so that we can discover germs, because in the year 5600 AD
>>>the microscope has been invented scores of times on scores of worlds and
>>>we already know about germs and know how to deal with them.
>>
>>Actually, you *don\'t* need a microscope for germ theory. You just need
>>it to help *confirm* it. It was propsed *before* the microscope.
>
>I didn\'t say anything about germ theory, I said germs. As far as I\'m
>concerned germ _theory_ is TL 0.

But *discovering* germs doesn\'t get you anything. Realizing that there
is *something* that causes diseases and is spread by contact or close
approach, and can be kept from spreading by keeping things clean is far
more important, whether you call the vector "germs" or "evil spirits".

It\'s not what the vector is that\'s the important point, it\'s the idea
that there *are* vectors.

>>>>The turing maschine (a theoretical computer) could have been invented with
>>>>Greek mathematics. However, nobody did it. Probably, the Greeks could have
>>>>built primitive calculation maschines if somebody told them how.

>>>But if you are a Referee preparing an adventure on Chaosheo (E87A788-1 in
>>>1117) you couldn\'t care less about what the ancient Greeks did or didn\'t
>>>do. What\'s interesting is wether the Chaosheans can have a turing machine
>>>or not. Can they? Why not? If the ancient Greeks _could_ have invented it
>>>then who\'s to say the Chaoseans didn\'t?

>>Us.

>Speak for yourself.

>>The Greeks could *build* a turing machine if we told them how. But they
>>couldn\'t *use* it. To *use* one, you need a lot of math and logic that
>>they didn\'t have. Since they didn\'t have the *theory*, they wouldn\'t have
>>any *use* for it.

>The original poster said that the Greeks had the necessary math. Don\'t go
>changing the assumptions on me, it ain\'t a nice way to argue. In any case,
>it\'s irrelevant, since mathematics is also a TL 0 science. So the Chaoseans
>_could_ have whatever mathematical knowledge they needed to run the thing.
>Remember: _The knowledge is freely available_.

I disagree with the original poster. The Greeks had the technical
skills. They did not have the math. You need more than the types of
logic known at the time to be able to *program* a Turing machine.
Programming *uses* logic, but it is *not* logic.

And again, I don\'t think the Greeks would have seen much *point* in a
Turing machine.

>>Again, I suggest re-checking your history. It wasn\'t all that long
>>between when decent lenses started being produced and when the
>>telescope was invented. There\'s no "centuries" involved. *Maybe* a
>>decade or two.

>I\'ll do just that. (And there is, too ;-)

Well, consider that the telescope was *reported* to Galileo in the
1500s. And that in the 1400s, Bacon *didn\'t* know about using lenses to
magnify things, though he does note that a *globe* of water can magnify
and focus light somewhat.

That doesn\'t leave much room for "centuries" :-)


