    'topic' => ' agriculture & development',
    'body' => 'On Wed, 17 Jan 1996, Steve Lieb wrote:

> I think all the head-scratching about why an individual or society would
> convert from a hunter-gatherer system to an agriculturally-based system when
> the H/G has so much more leisure time is all missing the point, a bit:
> Certainly, if the H/G is in a sparsely populated area, food is relatively
> easy to come by.  However, as populatino increases, the area required to get
> this food increases, not even taking into account game/forage depletion -
> another serious factor.

Resident anthropology student here :). Basically, as far as is known (I
mean, really, how many of us were around when all these initial
conversions took place), population increases and a decreased amount of
available food resources is generally accepted as the reason for societal
conversion to an agricultural as opposed to hunting/gathering model.
However, that isn\'t all there is to it- As you mention below, stable food
supply and security are other factors as well. In addition, one has to
keep in mind that keeping a surplus in the event of disaster is much
easier when you are producing more than you need to consume...however,
there is far more to it than that.

> 1) an agricultural system provides much more stable food supply, sure not
> perfect, but NOT subject to migrations, die-offs, etc.  Herding, my personal
> fave for a transition betreen h/g to agri life, kind of gives you the best
> of both worlds - as long as you can protect your food from other
> h/g\'s...which is a nice segue to:

While stable in ideal situations, agriculture has just as many problems
as hunting and gathering. Crop disease, the whims of weather (ask any
Prairie farmer about weather and his or her crops), a single hail storm,
floods...you name it. The only stable aspect of agriculture over hunting
and gathering is the fact that you determine what is being grown, where,
and how much will be planted.

> 2) security.  the biggest threat to humans were other humans.  security in
> numbers.  more security in big numbers.  even more security in big numbers
> behind big walls.

Erm...actually, before the advent of \'civilization\', the biggest threat
to humans would have been other predators and not necessarily other
humans Human vs Human conflict generally occurs in situations where one
group maintains herds which can be pirated, or where one group has access
to resources (of one sort or another) that another group needs or wants.
Hunting and gathering societies tend to have far less conflict with other
human groups than herders, or societies which practise agriculture.

> 3) comfort - i\'m surprised nobody mentioned this yet.  it\'s a pain in the
> ass to pack up a camp every day.  even if your bedroll is a shitty little
> thing, every day you DON\'T move, you can \'comfort up\' your surroundings.
> every new site always has a new collection of rocks, knots, roots, and burrs
> that have to be dealt with or put up with.

Don\'t be surprised. The comfort level in a hunting gathering society is
no different than in an industrialized one. What is any different about
packing up and moving, and spending so many hours a week engaged in
survival activities than spending 10 hours a day working in a factory,
paying bills, and trying to make ends meet? Nothing. Different socieites,
different comfort standards.

> 5) finally, h/g is opportunistic.  at least, more so than agriculture.  sure
> the h/g has more leisure, but never knows exactly where the next meal is
> coming from.  now, if you know that, barring flood or drought, that whole
> field of wheat will be there tomorrow, you can PLAN.  and PLANNING is what
> societies are based on.

I\'m not sure who wrote the monograph, but there is an excellent piece on
the !Kung which explains in great detail why Hunting and Gathering
involves a lot of planning, and isn\'t as opportunistic as most people
seem to believe it to be.

