    'topic' => 'tech levels (both contacted and fallen)',
    'body' => 'Hans Rancke-Madsen <rancke@diku.dk> writes:

>A 37 hour week is roughly 5 1/2 hours a day, which is quite a bit more than
>"a couple", but even so I can see that I have to revise some of my ideas.

That\'s also in a *desert* (The Kalahari). In more typical areas, it
takes a lot less time.

>One thing, though: What did these neolitic people _do_ with their free time?
>Please don\'t take this as a snide remark; I\'m genuinely curious.

That\'s one of the reasons they invented "society". All those complex
rules, raditions and taboos that "primitive" societies have exist for
two reasons. First, to help keep the population controlled. Second, to
keep life from being too boring.

This is also where art and many crafts come from.

>Ah, I see. But who besides you are arguing about the way things get invented?

There were a few and still are to some extent.

>>>Wait a minute. If one man can gather/hunt enough to survive in two hours,
>>>then he can gather/hunt enough for 5 people to survive in 10 hours. Thus
>>>20% of the society can support the rest.
>>
>>Except for one minor detail. Namely, the "Why should I?" factor. What
>>incentive is there for those people to spend all day hunting for
>>someone else? There\'s evidence it did happen to *some* extent. But only
>>for the craftsmen types. If Joe is really good at chipping flint, it
>>makes more sense to let him do that and give him a share of the hunt.
>
>Actually, in the context I\'m discussing (tech implementation) it makes
>possibilities _more_ interesting since, I maintain, there are quite a
>few customs and technologies that are possible for a TL 0 society that
>wasn\'t, historically, invented on Terra. So if one hunter can support
>4 non-hunters then some very interesting social structures are possible
>even on TL 0 worlds. Grist for a Referee\'s mill!

Remember that they\'ll have learbed the hard way that too many people
equals starvation. So they\'ll not go *too* far in that direction. But
it can be a possibility. It certainly means that they\'ll have the time
ands inclination to hunt for things the Imperials want to buy or to
produce "narive crafts" for sale. Assuming the Imerials come up with
something they want as payment.

>>Simple. Unless they can *see* a use for most math, they won\'t go to the
>>trouble of learning it. Please note how few folks *bothered* to learn
>>to read, write, or do arithnmetic until it was *required*. They figured
>>they had better things to do with their time.
>>
>>So as I keep pointing out, lower tech societies are quite likely to not
>>be *interested* in upgrading their tech level.
>
>Yes, but there is a world of difference between "quite likely" and
>"absolutely required to by the inexorable dynamics of TL 0 societies".
>In the first case _they might_. In the second they absolutely won\'t.
>Surely you can see the difference?

The problem I\'m trying to avoid is the all too typical one of "it is
*possible* (and maybe even *done* in rare cases), so why can\'t they all
do it". Rare behavior should *stay* rare. If you want realistic
cultures, only a very few will do it.

>>>And that\'s exactly what I\'ve been arguing: They _might_. Because writing is
>>>TL 0, so if the Referee has the local authorities on a TL 0 world whip out a
>>>bit of papyrus and a _ghifel_ feather and issue the PCs with a pass that
>>>must be kept at all time on pain of death, he can.
>>
>>More likely they\'ll be issued a clay tablet stamped with a special
>>"seal", or some oddly carved token. That is the sort of thing that
>>would *already* be in use at low tech levels.
>
>This is a remarkably parochial view. Not to mention totally boring. What\'s
>the fun of lugging your players to an alien planet if their society is
>going to be a carbon copy of some ancient Earth society?

Actually, I\'d find the written pass "boring", myself. Also, consider
the flip side of this. The players may be able to counterfeit the
written pass fairly easily (give me a scanner and some native "paper"
and I bet that i could!). Counterfeiting a "roll seal" or some sort of
carved token is a *lot* harder.

For that matter, if violating the "rules" carries a death penalty, it\'s
quite possible that your "pass" may be a tattoo, or scar pattern or the
like. Not only hard to counterfeit, but a *literal* pain to get.

The idea is to look at what "primitive" societies used for "id", and
use things along the same lines. That\'s far more interesting than a
written pass. It also let\'s the natives keep the fact that they can
write in reserve as a nasty surprise for the players. Picture a player
who has pissed off a native being asked to deliver some "artwork" to
the folks back at the port. And when he gewts there, he finds out the
hard way that it\'s a warrant for his arrest. :-)

>>A planet that had been settled and "backslid" would be more likely to
>>keep odd bits of high tech. A planet that had been *contacted* wouldn\'t.
>
>Apparently you think that most of the low-tech worlds in the Traveller
>universe are native worlds. I disagree. Of the 10.000 worlds of the
>Imperium, 50 _at most_ have "native" human populations (in fact, many of
>the 46 minor human races known were seeded on worlds outside the Imperium),
>and many of those are high-tech. It\'s harder to tell about the minor non-
>humans, because we don\'t know enough about them, so I suppose that\'s just
>something we shall have to disagree about. But IMO most of the low-tech
>worlds in the Traveller Universe are regressed societies. So I think that
>retained technology is highly relevant.

I\'ve *never* been comfortable with that sort of assumption. It just
doesn\'t make sense. *Especially* on hostile worlds. Natives make a lot
more sense, and fit in better with the sort of SF that inspired
Traveller.

>>Well, any "natives aren\'t all that likely to pick up the idea of riding
>>animals from Imperial contacts, because the Imperials won\'t be riding
>>animals, they\'ll be riding air-rafts.

>Many "natives" are likely to be descendants of settlers who brought riding
>animals to the planet because, unlike tractors and air-rafts, they can be
>produced by a colonial economy and they manufacture their own replacements.

In which case they\'d *already* have the riding animals. So they
wouldn\'t need to pick up the idea from the Imperials *anyway*.

>>I *really* don\'t think that it\'s all that likely that planets with tech
>>levels *that* low are populated by folks who were formerly at a high
>>tech level and lost it. Much more likely is that they came up from
>>their own stone age, on their own until contact.
>
>We shall have to agree to disagree on that. But let me try this: You will
>admit that _some_ societies will be of that kind, won\'t you? So the stuff
>we\'re discussing will be applicaple in _some_ instances, regardless of how
>frequent we each believe it would be.

Sure, *some* will. But it\'s going to require a relatively "friendly"
planet, *and* a good reason for them to have had enough people to
survive, but not enough to maintain tech.

>>Fallen civilations and "new" civilizations have very little in common.
>>But "fallen" ones should be rare unless you go along with Hard Times and
>>the Virus.
>
>In a universe that has a drive which occasionally flings a starship up to
>36 parsecs off course and turns into slag? I would say that fallen
>civilizations would be quite common. Not to mention the effects of The
>long Night...

It\'d have to be a *huge* ship to have a population that could survive
long enough to fall and then work back up. *Minimum* of 100 or so of
breeding age. Populations lower than that tend to die off from genetic
accidents and just plain "bad luck".

The "long night" situation isn\'t *that* much different. Some types of
colony (mining sites) aren\'t likely to survive long if contact is lost.
Picture a deep sea oil rig trying to survive if the supply copters quit
coming.

Places *planned* as colonies would be better of, depernding on how far
along they were. Anybody who designs anything other than a mining setup
or a research station that *isn\'t* iuntended to be self-sufficient is
too much of an idiot to have been in charge (though it will happen
occasionally).

Such places would lose tech for some things, but for the most part it\'d
not affect them all that much. Maybe we need to come up with a "how to
build a colony" set of "rules", and list what happens at each stage if
they get cut off.

>>True enough. But there\'s a *lot* of spread between when something becomes
>>*possible* and when it happens. And quite often, the difference is "theory".

>Right! You _do_ agree with me, after all! The difference IS theory. Of which
>any society in contact with an interstellar society can obtain any amount it
>desires.

Aside from our differences over what they *would* desire, I have to
point out that many "theories" require certain steps beforehand.

An Afghan gunsmith may be able to make a wonderful copy of a firearm,
but that won\'t let him design a new one. For that, he has to know *why*
it is put together the way it is. Likewise, many forms of even "simple"
engineering require that you not only know *how* to build something,
but *why* it is built that way. Which requires familarity with *all*
the theory, including the necessary steps leading up to it.

Mind you, there are a lot of "false steps" along the way, so you can
skip a lot of that if you have someone to teach you. But there are
still things you *have* to learn before you can learn the things you
want to.

>>The materials and skills required to create a working radio transmitter
>>are available clear back in *Roman* times, if not earlier. But there\'s
>>*no* way anybody at that tech level would invent one randomly, because
>>even if they built it, they wouldn\'t know what it was good for.
>
>I get a distinct feeling of deja vu... Anyway, people in contact with an
>interstellar society _would_ know what it was good for. And they wouldn\'t
>need to invent it, either. Just to build it.

They wouldn\'t build that sort of transmitter if they were in contact
with that high a tech level. First, it\'s *real* inefficient, and second
it really messes up the RF bands. But it *is* what a scout stuck in
such a society might put together as a distress signal.

A look at the third world is instructive. They tend to do several
different things. They buy "obsolete" equipment cheaply to use (that\'s
what has happened to practically every US and European phone switch
that was in working order when replaced by a higher tech switch. It got
shipped to someplace in the third world and installed). They also
"leapfrog" some things, for example, it\'s cheaper and easier to link
cities via satellite and and airplane than to string wires and build
highways.  Railroads are still a good investment in the places that
don\'t have them or roads though.

Of course, this *does* make them dependent on the high tech societies,
but it\'s generally worth it. There\'s little reason to suppose thast
it\'ll be any different in the Imperium *unless* there are restrictions
on technology transfer. In that case, you will see folks smuggling it
in anyway (Iraq and most of it\'s nuclear, chemical, and bio warfare
gear) and folks managing to smuggle in the knowledge, or even just
invent it themselves, knowing that it is possible.

>>It\'s not what the vector is that\'s the important point, it\'s the idea
>>that there *are* vectors.

>Precisely! Another instance where you agree with me. The idea is the
>important thing. And ideas are available at any TL.

Not quite. Ideas *do* require backing of the ideas they are built upon
in many cases. Germ theory *is* a fairly low level idea in the
heirarchy though. You mainly need the idea that it is *possible* to do
something about disease as a precursor.

>>Well, consider that the telescope was *reported* to Galileo in the
>>1500s. And that in the 1400s, Bacon *didn\'t* know about using lenses to
>>magnify things, though he does note that a *globe* of water can magnify
>>and focus light somewhat.

>> That doesn\'t leave much room for "centuries" :-)

>The notion that the fact that someone in England didn\'t know about lenses
>proves that they didn\'t exist anywhere in the world is... not sound.

A well educated, well read *scholar* interested in such things had no
knowledge of them existing in anywhere in Europe. And since you
specifically mentioned *glasses*, that pretty much takes care of that.
The only reference I can think of from before that is a vague reference
to Nero or one of the other Emperors using an "emerald lens" and it\'s
not at all certain that the reference is actually period, or that it
was followed up on.

Also, the idea of sticking one lens in front of another isn\'t at all
hard to come up with. It follows human nature.... "if one lens makes
things look bigger, maybe two will make them look *real* big"

Oh yeah, a society that has fallen from a higher tech level isn\'t
likely to wind up as hunter/gatherers. The idea that it is *easier*
wouldn\'t occur to them anymore than it did to you. Once they find
edible plants and animals, they\'ll start herding and farming. Once
they\'ve got a food supply, they\'ll worry about trying to preserrve
technology.

ps. I\'d suggest that we use "native" or "contacted" for indigenous low
tech societies, and "fallen" for the backslid type.

