    'body' => 'Does anybody want to help me work out a chart of tech implementation levels?
That is, a series of levels denoting the technological support someone with
all the necessary knowledge would need in order to be able to introduce a
new technology into a society that lacks it.

Note that this would solely deal with capabilities. There may very well be
social reasons - custom, religion, etc. - why such innovations won\'t work
(Very possibly the reasons why it hasen\'t been introduced before), but for
our purposes we presuppose that there are no such barriers.

It would propably be best not to tie us down to any existing tech levels,
neither Traveller nor GURPS nor any other. Perhaps, once we are done, we
can relate these Tech Implementation Levels (TILs for short) to Traveller
and GURPS TLs.

I propose the following definitions:

TIL 0 is any technology that a person with the proper knowledge and access
to the required raw materials can implement with little or no help.

TIL 1 is any technology that a person with the proper knowledge and access
to the required raw materials can implement with the help of the surrounding
society (in effect, if the local authorities says: "Give this man whatever
help he needs, within reason.")

TIL N, for N>1, is any technology that a person with the proper knowledge
and access to the required raw material can implement if, and only if, one
or more TIL N-1 technologies are available. (If several technologies of
different TIL are required, the highest TIL apply).

Note the "required raw materials". I would like to make this chart as
independant of Earth conditions as possible, but I don\'t think it can
be done altogether. For one thing, we have to assume the presence of the
appropiate raw materials. For another, we have to assume the ABSENCE of
any exotic materials. One could, for example, imagine an alien plant
whose pollen was as volatile as gunpowder and suddenly have TIL 0
explosives. This would IMO be unmanagable. So assume terrestial conditions.

I suggest that we first agree on what constitutes TIL 0 and 1. Some of it
will involve judgement calls. For example, it would propably be possible
for one man to make a crude iron sword all by himself. But the labor
involved in digging out the ore, refining it, building af forge, etc.
would, IMO, take so long for a single man that it would prove prohibitive.

Here\'s my suggestion for TIL 0 and 1. The categories are suggestions too.
Alternate suggestions are invited.

Technology Implementation Level Zero:
=====================================

MATERIALS: Wood, charcoal, clay, flint, soft stone, grass, salt, hide,
           gold, copper, sulphur.

CONTAINERS: Baskets, small clay pots, gourds, skin bottles.

WEAPONS: Flint knife, flint spear, flint axe, bow, fire-hardened and flint-
         tipped arrows, sling, slingstones, boomerang, atlatl, bola, whip,
         lariat.

MILITARY: Nothing.

MEASUREMENTS: Pedometry, sundials.

COMMUNICATIONS: Writing, smoke signals, beacons, semaphore, flags.

COMPUTING: Arithmetic, math, geometry, calculus, trigonometry, algebra,
           abacus.

ECONOMIC: Barter, personal IOUs, natural "coins" (rare sea-shells, pearls,
          etc.)

ENVIRONMENT: Natural caves, huts, tents.

FOOD: Hunting, gathering, kitchen gardening, salting, smoking, drying,
      fermentation (?), winter wine.

MEDICAL: Herbs, diagnosis.

LAND TRANSPORTATION: Foot travel, small riding animals (horse, llama, etc).

SEA TRANSPORTATION: Dugout canoe, raft.

AIR TRANSPORTATION: None.

SPACE TRANSPORTATION: None.

ENERGY: Muscles, beast of burden, yoke, horse collar.

ENERGY STORAGE: Weights.



Technology Implementation Level One:
====================================

MATERIALS: Hard stone, bricks, cement, iron, silver, quicksilver, tin,
           lead, glass, wool, cotton, silk, leather, coal, bronze, brass.

CONTAINERS: Large clay pots, glass bottles, leather bottles.

WEAPONS: Bronze and iron knife, spear, axe, and sword, bow, crossbow,
         metal-tipped arrows and bolts, lead slingstones, leather armor,
         quilted armor, brigantine.

MILITARY: Chariots, war elephants, siege machines.

MEASUREMENTS: Water clock.

COMMUNICATIONS: Heliographs [mirrors], signal stations, courier relays,
                paved roads.

COMPUTING: Logarithmic tables.

ECONOMIC: Money (Institution-backed IOUs), coins.

ENVIRONMENT: Carved caves, brick and stone buildings, sewers.

FOOD: Agriculture, animal husbandry, irrigation, crop rotation, animal
      fertilizers, food silos.

MEDICAL: Sterilization, crude surgery.

LAND TRANSPORTATION: Wheel, carts, stirrups.

SEA TRANSPORTATION: Rowboats, galleys.

AIR TRANSPORTATION: None. (Gliders (?))

SPACE TRANSPORTATION: None.

ENERGY: Water wheels, wind mills.

ENERGY STORAGE: Water (dams).



      Hans Rancke
University of Copenhagen
