    'body' => 'Hans Rancke-Madsen <rancke@diku.dk> writes:

>Leonard Erickson writes:
>>Hans Rancke-Madsen <rancke@diku.dk> writes:
>>Other than the "post atomic war" type stuff, most of the US SF which
>>seems to be the basis for Traveller has that sort of story as an
>>*exception*. Look at Andre Norton, Poul Anderson, etc.
>
>Poul Anderson was one of the authors I would have used as an example. I
>find it difficult to believe that you haven\'t read any stories of
>regressed societies if you\'re a SF fan. But I\'ll have a look at my
>collection and give you the titles of a few books. (Offhand I recall
>that A.B. Chandler has several stories about lost colonies).

I\'ve got most of Chandler\'s stuff. Though his stories are (IMHO) are a
lot less like Traveller than (for example) E.C.Tub\'s "Dumarest of
Terra" series (which *has* to be where they got fast drug and slow drug)
And Chandler\'s Universe has a history that was specifically set up to
*make* lost colonies likely. Traveller has nothing equivalent to the
"gaussjammers".

>Anyway, the un-interdicted TL 0 worlds in the Traveller Universe are
>exceptions too. There is one in the entire Deneb Domain. TL 1-3 worlds
>are more numerous (about two dozen), but still few enough.

Still, that\'s rather common, all things considered.

>But if an indigenous people did have a local animal that could be trained to
>be a riding and/or draft animal and just hadn\'t gotten the idea of
>domestication on their own, why should some friendly scout not be able to
>teach them how?

Because he\'ll be up on charges if he does? :-)

Try and find a copy of Norton\'s "The Sioux Spaceman" for a story that
makes the idea work.

>>Quite a few will. More people than you think have hobbies that give them
>>knowledge of at least *some* obsolete tech. Some have quite a bit. For
>>example, I myself know things like how to make gunpowder, sulfuric and
>>nitric acids, and a lot of other chemical stuff starting pretty much from
>>nothing but raw materials. I not only know the *current* methods, which
>>require hard to produce catalysts and the like, but I also know the
>>*historical* methods, which are much easier, even if they are less efficient.

>And I bet you could teach them to an indigenous population too, couldn\'t you?

If I had a *good* reason. I know enough history to be *real* leary of
that sort of tampering. Too much sufferring has been caused by people
with good intentions trying to "help" natives. That\'s one of the
reasons the third world is in such a mess.

Interesting bit of data from folks trying to "correct" the problems.
It\'s easy to get the natives to adopt medicine, because the results are
obvious, and it almost never runs into any cultural taboos. But trying
to get them to adopt birth control, or even switch to crops that will
do a better job of supporting them, and they will *not* do it. Birth
control won\'t sell because the culture has it ingrained that you need
all the kids you can have, just to have enough survive to take care of
you when you get old. Even though modern medicine changes that, the
*culture* sees no point in changing. The new crops look different, have
to be planted and cultivated differently, and harvested and prepared
for eating differently. Again, they aren\'t interested.

Even in the middle of a *famine* it\'s not at all uncommon to have
perfectly good food thrown away or wasted, because it\'s not "normal"
food. A lot of "aid" has that happen to it.

It\'s not necessarily that the natives are *stupid* (though the lowering
of intelligence caused by long term borderline malnutrition may pay a
part). It\'s that these cultural values evolved over centuries as the
result of learning the *hard* way what did and didn\'t work.

It\'s *way* too easy to have things backfire. At least until the culture
gets to a medieval or later *social* level. As you note below, it\'s
hard to underestimate the contariness of people.

>>If the ship\'s library is intact, they *will* have more knowledge than I do.
>>What I listed above is the stuff I can do *without* reference materials.

>I think you underestimate the tremendous effort needed to establish a new
>impromptu colony.

No. Depending on the local conditions they could have a *real* hard
time of it. But if they are to have *any* chance of long-term survival,
the air has to be breathable, the water has to be somewhat drinkable,
and available in reasonable quantities. And edible plants/animals have
to be available fairly close to the landing site.

Ever had any survival training? I\'ve had *some*, not a full course, but
enough to know just how much hassle is involved. On the other hand, if
you aren\'t *too* picky, there are lots of edible critters out there.

>But that objection is easily disposed of: Have the ship
>just barely make it to the ground.

So they don\'t have the power plant? Do realize that if there aren\'t at
least a few weeks worth of food onboard (even if it\'s some pretty awful
emergency rations) then the odds of surviving are just about zip. It
takes *time* to see if plants are edible, and even longer with animals.
Especially given the wide variations possible between planets. You are
very lucky if you managed to test one item per *day* per person you can
*spare* to do the testing.

>Or have one faction keep the ship and
>have another (larger) faction run away. The faction with the ship
>eventually succumb to those accidents and genetic drift you spoke of. In
>the meantime the other faction has had to shift for itself and has lost
>a lot.

Quite a lot. They\'d be down to paleolithic levels in no time.

>>It costs less to make the stuff locally than to ship it over interstellar
>>distances.
>
>Bulk transportation costs across one or two parsecs are fairly low.

Compare them to what it costs to move stuff inside a system. *IF* you
have to go to one of the other planets for it, it\'s easy to use solar
sails, or even "mass driver" tugs to start the cargo towards the
destination, and the same to capture it at the other end. So it takes a
year or two. The ore/ice/whatever doesn\'t care. And the costs are very,
very low.

If you can find it on-planet, then costs are pretty cheap too.

>>*Especially* once you have decent fusion power. With that tech level, I can
>>extract chemically pure elements from ordinary rock.
>
>By that token it would be cheaper to extract the stuff in a system with
>fusion power and transport it to systems with lower TL.

But it\'s *also* cheap to *import* the fusion reactor, techs, etc and do
it in your system. In case you haven\'t noticed, nations on earth don\'t
like being dependent on outsiders for anything critical. Expecting
*planets* to feel differently is ignoring human cussedness.

>>Once the population hits a million or so self-sufficient is the only
>>thing that makes sense
>
>There is quite a spread from the couple of hundreds of people that you
>say is the minimum needed to make the survival of a population plausible
>and a million. A population of a million is not an outpost or even a colony,
>it\'s a mainworld. And I agree that it will be self-sufficient. As long as
>they can build their replacenment parts...

I deliberately went "high" on that figure. Depending on the tech level
the population *wants* a colony as small as a few *thousand* could be
viable. Picture a colony set up by the Amish... :-)

>>(work out what it costs for food *plus shipping costs* and several *months*
>>of reserves, then compare it with what it costs to have a few hundred folks
>>raising and processing food).

>That depends. Are you talking about "a few hundred" using machinery and soil
>supplements imported from a high-tech world or are you talking about all
>the people necessary to build the machines from scratch? Because unless
>you\'re talking about the second, the colony isn\'t self-sufficient in the
>long run. Those machines wear out.

You really don\'t need *that* much machinery to have "few hundreds"
feeding "a million". And it *will* be repairable locally. Take a look
at the mid 19th century. Farm machinery had come into being, but was
still mostly animal "powered".

Fertilizer is *not* a problem if you design the sewage system properly.
One of these days, I\'m going to get brave enough to buy a tilipia(sp)
at the local store and see how they taste. They are a "designed in"
part of the integrated sewage systems being designed these days. You
run the sewage thru very minimal treatment and then into a series of
ponds and marshes. The plants in the firsty few lock up things like
toxic metals, and break down the organics. The last few are used for
raising fish (the tilipia) and edible water plants.

You can even recover some of the "metals" by harvesting plants in the
primary ponds and burning them. The ash will be enriched enough to be
processed (though only if you *really* need to do so).

It doesn\'t take many people to handle this part of things. Others will
be doing normal farming,. and that will probably use fertilizer
produced from the waste in process the fish and plants. They\'ll keep
you from getting tired of fish, rice, and whatever. :-)

>>Yes, we control the dice. So we are justified in having *a* low probability
>>event occur. Even a string of them, if it gives us an "interesting" locale.
>>But doing so over and over again for hundreds of planets isn\'t even
>>"cheating". It\'s just plain lazy. And stupid, to boot.
>
>Hundreds? Of un-interdicted pre-industrial worlds (TL 0-3) there are about
>23 (give or take a couple, I ran through the listings pretty fast) in the
>Deneb Domain. That\'s a far cry from "hundreds". Of these some may very well
>be contacted. But many of them have populations of less than a million.
>Some of them in the thousands (a few even in the hundreds). That dosen\'t
>say "indigenous" to me, does it to you?

The 23 is a better number for the whole of "known space"!

Depending on tech level, hundreds and thousands *can* be indigenous.
Remember, the population on Earth only hit a million in the last
thousand or two years. Back when we were primarily hunter/gatherers the
population was quite likely in the tens of thousands. And there was a
point *somewhere* in the last couple of million years when the
population was in the dozens...

>>>So a *few* planets populated by the descendants of castaways can be
>>justified. But not the widespread numbers we see.
>
>How widespread do you see it?

See above.

Also, you are ignoring a somewhat more likely possibility. For worlds
with relatively low populations and a "low" tech level, it\'s possible
that they are colonies created by "back to nature" types. Sort of like
the communes so common in the late 60s and early 70s.

This gives interesting possibilities. They may *actively* not want high
tech.

>>>Mining sites are just a variation of the misjumped passenger liner. Although
>>>they would be much rarer, I agree, because most outfits would extract their
>>>people before they closed down. Unless the final disruption was violent
>>>(like a war or ar Reaver attack on the staging world). But again, we can
>>>decide that that was just what happened.

>>But only once or twice. After that, we\'re back to the "it makes no
>>sense" problem.

>Oh, I think we can squeeze a few more than two out of that scenario. It\'s
>a big universe and the Reaver mentality is universal.

It\'s not *that* big, and the odds against a "mining camp" surviving are
pretty slim. Especially given that reavers *do* have some brains. About
six months to a year after knocking off the staging base, they\'d figure
that the mine would be easy pickings...

>>But they *don\'t* allow for a *legion* of such planets!

>anyway - for the whole Imperium. And I\'m not saying that some of them can\'t
>be contacted worlds. But there\'s a problem with those. They _have_ to be
>aliens. The canon dosen\'t allow us more than one minor human race per
>sector on the average. Now, aliens are all right as a change of pace. They
>are also all right if someone else does all the scut-work of detailing them
>for me. But personally I get more mileage out of using my time to detail an
>alien human society than I get from detailing a totally alien species,
>biology and mentality. Frankly, it\'s not cost-effective (for me) to invent
>believable aliens. Takes too much time and creativity that could have been
>used more profitably on other projects. So my low-tech societies are mostly
>human. And that means regressed (or deliberately restrained) societies. YMMV.

Just *how* belivable they need to be can vary. It can range from
"humans in alien costumes" level seen in most of Star Trek to the
fairly well worked out stuff of C.J.Cherryh, Poul Anderson, and Gordon
Dickson. Note that all three of them seem to take the same approach.
Dickson has been pretty explicit about it, Anderson has dropped some
hints, and I have strong suspicions that Cherryh does what they do.

Study some terran animal that is at least *somewhat* social, and base
your aliens on that. Most of that sort of work is found under
"ethology", though some is under anthropology. You get reactions that
"make sense" but *only* if your players can twist their viewpoint
around the right way. You, having the researcher\'s conclusios in front
of you have no such problem. :-)

BTW, iyt can get a bit scary when you *do* manage to "warp" your head
around to see things from the alien viewpoint. Being able to "think
like a kif" was interesting, but not something I\'d want to do very
often!

>>Want to bet? It\'s a lot cheaper than shipping in food.

>Is that something that you\'ve calculated or is it just an assumption on
>your part? If the first, could you let me see the calculations? I think
>I once calculated the transportation overhead for bulk cargo at 1 Cr per
>kilo, but I won\'t swear to it. I\'ll see if I can dig out my figures.

Don\'t forget that you have much the *same* cost for *producing* the
food "on site" as at wherever the shipper gets it. Add in the extra
layers of "middlemen" (shipping brokers, wholesalers, etc) involved in
the longer trip. Figure a 10% "charge" for each layer.

Oh yeah. The *real* killer on some of this. How many foods *can\'t*
handle sitting around for a week? or Two weeks? So if you want *fresh*
food, it *has* to be produced locally. Damn little produce will handle
two weeks of shipping all that well. Meat will have to be frozen. Etc.

And I\'m sure Europe has the same sort of advertising campaigns we keep
seeing "Buy Oregon fryers, they\'re fresher", and all the other
exhortations to buy from local suppliers.

>>Miners and small research groups do ok on shipped in food.

>What is "small"? If it\'s more than a couple of hundred then you have a
>nucleus of a population large enough to satisfy you (by your own earlier
>posting). If it\'s more than a couple of dozens we\'ve got enough to
>satisfy me.

A couple of hundred *aren\'t* going to survive if the place isn\'t
self-sufficient to at least *some* extent. How long would the bases on
Antartica survive if contact was cut off?

Now, compare that with someplace like the Falklands, or some of the
small islands that have bases/research outposts on them. If it\'s
possible to raise some food there (or collect it), they *will* do it,
simply because it gives some variety over canned goods, and gardening,
hunting, or harvesting wild fruits/vegetables is something to *do* in
your off time (ie it alleviates boredom).

And consider that since ships are not merely the *fastest* but the
*only* means of communication, that\'s another reason for trying to find
a local source of food. You can\'t call for help if there\'s a problem.
It also wastes *time* having "too frequent" supply runs. Even if a
scout can carry a month\'s supplies for them, how much does it cost to
operate the ship for the two weeks & two jumps involved? If it\'s a
bigger ship, the costs get *worse*, not better.

>>>In fact, I can\'t see how a high-tech outpost or a misjumped ship can avoid
>>>back-sliding. All the way down to hunter-gatherer is a bit far, but there\'s
>>>no way they can produce the things needed to keep their high-tech equipment
>>>going once they are cut off from the parent society.

>>True. But that *doesn\'t* mean that they can\'t produce lower tech stuff.
>>And don\'t be so sure about the inability to rebuild things. Give me an
>>environment where I can breathe the air, drink the water without too
>>much treatment, and eat some of the native life, and give me the ship\'s
>>library. It may take me several *years*, but given the resources of
>>even a *small* ship I\'ll be able to do one *hell* of a lot.

>>[...]

>>A *Traveller* ship can produce more power than most powerplants. And it
>>too, will be able to fix all the parts small enough to get to the
>>"shop" and lots of others that can\'t be. That\'s why "Engineering" needs
>>so much space. :-)

>Sure. And there are a lot of mid- and even high-tech worlds out there that
>have population groups that started out that way. But the ship wears out.
>You die.

Yeah, but I\'m pointing out that given several *years*, a ship could
rebuild almost anything. Rebuilding the jump drive might be a stretch.
But it might be doable too.

>If you\'ve trained a successor it may be all right. If not then it\'s
>too bad that the ship had that machine shop, because unless the people on it
>were exceptional human beings, sure as God made little green apples they will
>have based their society on stuff that can only be made with the facilities
>of the ship. And when the ship power plant goes, they are in real big
>trouble. Sure, you taught your children a lot, but did they teach their
>children? Oh, I don\'t say that it\'s inevetable, but it dosen\'t take many
>mistakes to ruin such a setup.

True, which is why I\'d be trying for fixing the ship *first*, then if
that looks out of reach, you look at the resources you\'ve located, and
figure on what ought to be a "sustainable" tech level. You can *try* to
keep the ship going, but it\'s true that sooner or later *something*
would break that you couldn\'t fix (though it\'s possible that you could
build *past* that point if you got lucky on finding ore deposits and
the like).

But assuming a few hundred people, I see no reason for the
"sustainable" tech level to be much below 19th century. And a lot
*higher* in spots.

The idea is that you use the ship to help make the things you need to
make what you don\'t have.

ps. the heck with nanotech. We are approaching the "3d reproducing
pantograph". That is, a gizmo that you feed the CAD/CAM files in,
supply it with raw materials, and it makes the gizmo, all in one
"operation". Quite likely assembling it at the molecular or atomic
level by something that resembles "molecular beam ion implantation" the
way that technology resembles spray painting.

That\'d screw up a lot of traveller too. :-)


