    'from' => 'Robert Flammang FLAMMANG@vms.cis.pitt.ed',
    'year' => 1996,
    'index' => 'ac431',
    'body' => 'Hi. One of the things that\'s really fun about the Traveller Universe is the
multitude of different quirks, systems and milieus that must be explained by
the creative (or not so creative) referee. I\'ve really enjoyed reading about
the Hiroshi-as-fascist conspiracy as an excellent example of a creative
theory that explains one quirk in a Universe which is almost as difficult to
understand (sometimes) as the real one we live in.

I probably won\'t adapt Phil\'s particular example into my own campaign,
as it wouldn\'t jibe very well with some of my own particlar "historical"
theories and rationalizations which I have been developing in my 17 years of
playing CT. But what I liked about it was the way Phil McGregor was
motivated by the need for a rational explanation for a strange aspect of the
CT Universe.  This same motive is what had driven me in my own developement
of the "history" of known space. (That\'s CT\'s known space, not L.Niven\'s.)

Right from the outset of playing Traveller, I was struck by several
hard-to-understand "facts" that needed rationalizing:

1)The Imperium is a feudal society. How can this be?

2)There is an immense range in TL from world to world. Hctb?

3)Technology has advanced very slowly over the last 35 centuies.

4)The trade rules make no economic sense (assuming a free market
economy).

5)300,000 years ago, the ancients knew which races (the six major
races) were going to get the jump (or should I say Jump-Drive) on their
competitors. We can surmise that this fact is true from the presense of the
Droyne, Humanity, Centaurs, Hivers, Vargr, and Aslan on their 3000- century
old coynes. (See Adv. 3, Twilight\'s Peak)

6)Devices such as jump drive, anti-gravity and black globes are
magical; they break well known laws of physics. They are also isolated.
Whatever science went into making them has not impacted technology in a wide
range of applications; magic does not commonly occur in CT outside of these
three inventions. (Let me ignore psionics at the moment.)

7)Why would the Imperium be so interested in settling the Spinward
Marches, which is on the other side of the great rift in enemy territory,
when there\'s all this empty territory rimward? The main thrust of Imperial
expansion was spinward even before the Solomani Rim seceded from the
Imperium. (Perhaps this was one of the Solomani motives for doing so.)

I\'ve made up a "history" that explains these seven "facts" in a
somewhat rational manner. And which jibed with all the Traveller
Canon I knew about until the DGP adventure on Kyusu. And here it is...

3000 centuries ago, after all his descendants were dead, Grampa knew
which species were going to get the jump drive because he knew which systems
he had left jump drives lying around in. He also knew that the hundreds of
other intellegent species in known space weren\'t going to make j-drive on
their own. This was because there are no indications in the natural universe
that such a thing as j-drive was at all possible. Therefore it would only be
by way of an amazingly improbable fluke that it could ever be invented
independently by a primative culture. (How exactly Grampa got j-drive is not
important to the history that follows.)

While these six races were learning how to copy Grampa\'s j-drive,
they also learned about his anti-grav. (They didn\'t learn about his black
globes or psionics till later.) These races DO NOT understand the physics of
these devices. Indeed they may not be intellectually capable of ever
understanding them. But they did figure out how to copy them, at least to
some extent.

When the Vilani were expanding and subjugating other races with
their new found technology, they hid from their subject races the fact that
they did not invent j-drive or AG. They used these technologies as proof
that they had Major intellects compared with everyone else. In fact, what
they had was a Major patron. When the other Major races appeared on the
seen, they too maintained this lie. To do otherwise would be to admit
inferiority to the Vilani.

As the Vilani expanded, their j-drive tech leaked to many of the
minor races on their borders, notably to the Vegans, who quickly expanded in
the region just coreward of Terra. The Vilani grew alarmed at the existence
of pocket empires all around their borders, so they began the Pacification
Campaigns. The Vilani used their tightly controlled J-2 technology (the
minor races only had J-1) to military advantage. They absorbed the
subjugated pocket empires, and clamped the borders of civilization shut,
lest technology continue to leak out of their empire.

Of course, they never imagined that other major races might arise,
because they never knew that Grampa had other proteges. Otherwise, they
would have never been so stupid.

And stupid they were, deliberately so. They had it pretty good. New
technology was a risk (it might be leaked out) so they settled for control
instead of growth.

The Terrans found j-drive artifacts in their asteroid belt and soon
after they contacted the Vilani. The Vilani thought they were just another
minor race and tried to absorb them. They did not succeed at first. In fact,
in the early Interstellar Wars, they lost the Vegan Polity, a heavily
industrialized, very high population, former pocket empire that was just
dying to escape the Imperium.

So the Vilani, realizing that they had to defeat the Vegans as well
as the Terrans, began to build a real navy for the first time in 1500 years.
It was a J-1 fleet. No sense in allowing the Vegans to get their hands on
J-2 technology thru captured ships. So the Imperium made a huge juggernaut
of a fleet that was going to roll over the rebellious rimward province. The
only problem was that the juggernaut was outmanoevered and destroyed
piecemeal by the Terran J-2 fleet.

The megacorporations were furious. The incompetent bums in power had
allowed the wolfling Terrans to steal their J-2 secrets! A major power
struggle ensued. The entire rimward province was purged of its incompetent
and treacherous hierarchy. Legions of executives and middle managers were
being put to death. While all this was going on, the Terrans continued to
gain ground as polity after polity quit the empire and joined the Terran
Confederation. The Imperial Navy was in shambles.

After some years, the Imperium stopped its hemorrhaging. It built up
a huge J-2 armada to defeat the Confederation navy and utterly exterminate
all rival possessors of J-2 technology. The armada was promptly destroyed by
the Confederacy\'s J-3 fleets.

Oops. It looks like the Terrans hadn\'t stolen Vilani technology
after all. They had an independent source for their j-drives. In fact, they
had better j-drives than the Vilani now.

It was about this time that the Imperium was contacted by the
agressive and rapidly expanding Vargr who came pouring across the corridor.

It was all over for the Imperium of course. By this time, the major
threat to the Confederation came from within.

The Confederation was ruled by a Security Council made up of 15
Terran nations, and by a General Assembly made up of 150 Terran nations and
about as many Confederation worlds. (One world, one vote, unless you were
Terra of course.) As the decades wore on, this arrangement became less and
less acceptable to the Confederation outworlds who, after all, bore the
brunt of the war.  After a century and a half of war, the Imperium was
conquered, and a debate broke out as to how it was to be administered.

The UN decided that each Imperial world was to get a seat in the
General Assembly. The voice of any single Confederation world would
therefore go from one out of 300 seats, to one out of 9000. The Security
Council remained entirely in Terran hands. (Actually, after an initial
protest, Luna was given a seat on the Security Council too.)

It seems incredible to Imperials today that the UN could expect to
get away with such an insulting decree. It reflected the ridiculously
insular and parochial views which were dominant on Terra at that time.  But
the majority (90%) of the officers and men in the Confederation Navy were
not from Terra. And they simply refused to obey.

Grand Admiral Hiroshi Estigaribia granted complete local autonomy to
member worlds. All interstellar authority was administered by the Admiralty
at Dingir (later moved to Ershur.) There was no bloody coup; there was
simply nothing Terra could do about it.

It was Estigariabia who first coined the term "Solomani" to describe
the rulers of the 2nd Imperium; the term "Terran" had fallen out of favor
with the Admiralty. "Vilani" is a Vilani word meaning "people of Vland."
"Zhodani" is a Vilani word meaning "people of Zhdant." "Solomani" is a
Vilani word meaning "people of peace (s\'lom.)" The term was politically
effective, as it reminded everyone that it was Estigaribia and his people who
ended the Interstellar Wars. The term was originally meant to apply to all
citizens of the new Empire, once their worlds had been officially re-admitted.

Well, as everyone knows, things didn\'t work out as Hiroshi planned.
But before I tell my version of that story, now might be a good time to
reflect on how Terra\'s winning the war with reconstructed grandpaternal
technology affected our culture.

The technology that the asteroidal archeologists had uncovered was
of immense military significance. Even before contact with the Vilani,
anti-gravity revolutionized the way wars were fought, and later, the way
people lived. After contact with the Vilani, it was the archeologists who
won the wars for us, in a much more striking (and important) way than
physicists had won wars in the previous centuries. After all,
archeologically related technology had saved our culture from extinction,
whereas physics related technology (it could be argued, and was) was darn
near guilty of complicity in our nuclear destruction.

Also, physics was seen, at that time, (rightly or wrongly) as a dead
science. Breakthroughs were quite rare in the 22nd century. And researchers
were discouraged. Physicists had told us everything they could about the
natural world, it seemed. And so it was, that among the military, the movers
and the shakers, and even among those intellectuals who knew about the
significance of the Ancients, Archeology replaced Physics as the Queen of
the Sciences. Most future technological advances, it was to turn out, would
come from Archeology.

Hiroshi\'s heirs were to invoke his name, and crown themselves
emperors of the Ramshackle Empire. The flag officers of the new empire, who
were in charge of all interstellar management, evolved into a feudal
nobility.  This nobility was not heriditary at first. But the opinion of
many of the naval officers was that the Vilani, as a race, were incapable of
self governance. High appointments were restricted to "genetic" Solomani. (a
social fiction - most Solomani genes were a mix of Terran DNA and that of
other minor races and various Vilani minorities who fought for the
Confederacy) In regions where genetic Solomani were rare, positions, quite
naturally, stayed in the family. In the rimward regions, a "tradition of
democracy" (if not democracy itself) and fraternity and equality lingered
for much longer.

Feudalism worked like this: Due to Hiroshi\'s decree, the barons did
not regularly have direct legal authority over the worlds they were given
charge of. So the barons established starports, where they could regulate
(and tax) interstellar trade. There was one starport per barony, and the
baron was entitled to a cut of anything going between his barony and
offworld. These starports were extraterratorial, the worlds themselves had
no control over them. If merchants tried to bypass the starports, they were
guilty of breaking interstellar law (which was legistlated by nobles) and
had their contraband confiscated, at the very least.

Baronies were grouped into marches, presided over by a marquis.
Marches were grouped into counties, and counties into duchies. Each duchy
was presided over by a Duke, who in turn presided over his counts and
marquises as they met in conclave to decide on the regulations that governed
trade and tariff between the baronies, and, incidently, to determine their
own cuts. The bounderies of the duchies were set by the Admiralty; they
normally coresponded to subsector boundaries.

In return for all this taxation and regulation, the nobility
provided for protection from pirates, maintainance of the spaceways, and the
keeping of the peace.

Of course, the nobility did whatever they could to expand
interstellar trade, and their cuts, as much as they possibly could. This
meant using the forces of interstellar economic competition (which they had
entirely on their leash) to encourage the worlds not to become too self
sufficient. One common example of this is reflected in the diverse TL\'s
within the Imperium.  A world rich with natural resources was discouraged
from developing high-tech industry. It therefore must import its technology
(of which the nobles get a cut) in exchange for its raw materials (of which
the nobles get a cut.) As long as the nobles keep their subjects secure and
well fed (as opposed to angry and rebellious) they can keep on skimming off
of the interstellar economy, upon which everyone, gentle and common,
depends.

This system of feudalism was to survive the long night more or less
intact. It was maintained in slightly modified form by Cleon I when he
declared himself ruler of the 3rd Imperium 2000 years later. Cleon was,
after all, a noble himself. He built the power of his empire on three
pillars:

I)The gentry. All imperial nobles swear fealty directly to His Majesty
the Emperor as well as to his own immediate liege. The emperor is entitled
to some taxes from his vassels. He regulates trade between duchies
(subsectors) through his Minister of Trade, whom he personally appoints.
The Ministry of Trade maintains a system of courts through which the peerage
may appeal for judgements of trade matters above the conclave level. These
judges are given non-heriditary, titular patents of nobility, so that they
may stand in rank with the plaintiffs they judge. These appointments are
made by His Majesty himself, or by one of his viceroys, subject to his
approval.

The nobility maintain the subsector navies, which keep the spaceways
open, and defend the realm. They are kept in line by the Imperial Navy\'s
sector fleets, whose assets are sufficient to put down the occasional
subsector rebellion.  The Imperial Navy is the personal property of His
Majesty. In wartime, it takes direct command of the subsector navies.

II)The worlds. The world governments swear fealty directly to His
Majesty. They are given complete independence in their internal affairs.
Even nobles are bound to obey their laws, although a noble does have the
right to have his case tried by an Imperial Court, before a jury of his
peers.

The worlds have their own military forces. In war time their navies
serve under the Imperial Navy (as their oath of fealty requires.) They
contribute a fraction of their military budget to the subsector Duke and the
Emperor for the maintainance of the interstellar military.

The huge populations of many of the worlds give the Emperor his most
powerful tax base. He is often a jealous protector of his worlds\' rights
against the nobility. This sometimes involves granting patents of nobility
to a world\'s rulers, so they can stand in rank with the peers and be heard
during subsector conclaves.

III)The Megacorporations. The Emperor grants certain companies, at his
pleasure, Imperial Charters. These charters, among other things, give a
company the right to move its property from one world to another without
paying interstellar taxes to the regional nobility, as long as the move is
not made with the purpose of retail sales. This right allows Megacorps to
amass large manufacturing plants on the surface of a world without paying
alot of overhead to the local nobility. These charters are not lightly
granted. (His Majesty does not normally make a policy of pissing off his
nobles.) Getting a charter for a company generally involves giving the
Emperor a fair chunk of its holdings. Charters are a way the Emperor has of
managing his interstellar wealth independently of the gentry.

----

OK. Feudalism is complicated, so it took alot of explaining. Most
people on this list will be horrified by my description of the 3rd Imperium.
(It\'s SO midieval!) You are probably used to thinking of the Imperium as the
Good Guys. But I subscribe to the old description of the Imperium as being a
corrupt and declining and incredibly bloated interstellar state. This
description is found in Adventure 1: Kinunir. (After all, that\'s where I
first heard of the Imperium!)

The emperors of the 3rd Imperium are elected by the Imperial Senate.
Senators are appointed for life by the Emperor. He can appoint absolutely
anyone he wants, but he usually appoints prominant members of powerful
families, major cultural figures, or religious authorities. These
appointments are NOT hereditary. The Senate has the power to counsel the
Emperor, and to elect his successor. In practice, they almost always elect
his chosen heir.

The Senate is Cleon\'s major contribution to civilization. It
provides for a uniform means of succession to the throne. Lack of such a
means, you may recall, was the single most important factor in the 2nd
Imperium\'s fall.

I based my conception of the Imperial Senate on my limited knowledge
of the old Byzantine Senate. I made it up before I ever heard of the Moot.
The Byzantine Empire has been a major inspiration to what I\'ve written
above. It too was based on trade, and it too was corrupt, declining and
bloated!

Well OK, lets look at my scorecard:
1)The Imperium is a feudal society. How can this be?
-Imperial feudalism mooches off of interstellar trade.

2)There is an immense range in TL from world to world. Hctb?
-The nobles interfere with "normal" technological
developement.

3)Technology has advanced very slowly over the last 35 centuies.
-Physics ran out of social steam.

4)The trade rules make no economic sense.
-It\'s a command economy. Of course it makes no sense.

5)Foreknowledge of the Six Major Races.
-None of them are Major, according to the Library Data
definition. They\'re all proteges of Grampa.

6)Devices such as jump drive, anti-gravity and black globes are
magical.  Whatever science went into making them has not impacted technology
in a wide range of applications. Magic does not commonly occur in CT outside
of these three inventions.
-Basically the magic devices don\'t have lots of applications
because they\'re voodoo technology. The engineers
who build them don\'t know how they work. And nobody
thinks that\'s strange anymore.

7)Why would the Imperium be so interested in settling the Spinward
Marches, which is on the other side of the great rift in enemy territory,
when there\'s all this empty territory rimward? The main thrust of Imperial
Expansion was spinward even before the Solomani Rim seceded from the
Imperium. (Perhaps this was one of the Solomani motives for doing so.)

Allright, I haven\'t answered that one yet. Here goes.

Early on in the developement of the 3rd Imperium, archeologists in
the Scout Service noticed that the "center-of-gravity" of the distribution
of Ancient sites was located on the opposite side of the Great Rift. Fearful
that the Zhodani might settle the area first, the emperors pressed hard to
settle the Spinward Marches. And they were well rewarded; Black Globes were
discovered there. The emperors are very possesive of Ancient artifacts.
Basically, His Majesty is the only person legally allowed to own one.

So the Imperator of the Third Imperium has traditionally followed
the footsteps of the Fuhrer of the Third Reich; he\'s a big collector of
magical relics from throughout the world/known-space. He believes that
control of such relics will give him power to rule over mankind. And in the
case of the emperor, he may be right.

Well, I guess this post is long enough now. I hope this inspires
more creativity of the type that Phil showed in his posts. I love stuff like
this! Please make lots of comments about this.

By the way Phil, I think the plague of Duskir was detailed in
"Solomani and Aslan." It didn\'t break out until after the Solomani
conquest. It was a factor in the fall of the Ramshackle Empire, not the
1st Imperium.


-Rob
