    'index' => 'ac434',
    'body' => '>        Right from the outset of playing Traveller, I was struck by several
>hard-to-understand "facts" that needed rationalizing:

Much of this is understandable if you remember that communications
is no faster than travel and it takes on the order of a year for
ships/messages to reach the frontier from the capital.  For these
reasons the Imperium is in a very similar situation as that faced
by the Roman and Spanish Empires.

>1)      The Imperium is a feudal society. How can this be?

It is forced by the fact that time delays are too large for direct
rule.  Fuedal systems arrose to handle such forced decentralization
while maintaining central athority.

>2)      There is an immense range in TL from world to world. Hctb?

We have an immense range from continent to continent (and even withing
continents).  Look at Africa.   And we have much faster trade and
communications between parts of the world than the Imperium has
between systems.

>3)      Technology has advanced very slowly over the last 35 centuies.

This takes a presumption that the modern western attitudes toward
technology and change is a passing one.  This is not that far fetched.
The concept of "progress" is one that sets western attitudes apart
from most historical cultures.  If you look at Ancient Greece, the
Roman Empire, several Chinese Dynasties, you see cultures that
could have made major technological changes and simply chose not
to.

>7)      Why would the Imperium be so interested in settling the Spinward
>Marches, which is on the other side of the great rift in enemy territory,
>when there\'s all this empty territory rimward?

The Spinward Marches aren\'t "in" enemy territory.  They were settle
because they were mostly unclaimed and undeveloped.  When Imperium
settlement in that direction ran up against Zhodani settlement
coming from the other direction, Imperial Expansion mostly came
to a halt.  Is the Imperium all that "interested" in the
Spinward Marches?  I don\'t see that they get any attention
disproportionated to their situation.

>The main thrust of Imperial
>expansion was spinward even before the Solomani Rim seceded from the
>Imperium. (Perhaps this was one of the Solomani motives for doing so.)

I don\'t agree.  When the Solomani Sphere was part of the Imperium
there was significant expansion.  Now, expansion in that direction
is blocked by the Solomani (who are still expanding).  The Imperium
expanded into the Spinward marches because there was no barrier
to doing so, and stopped when the Zhodani put up a barrier.

