    'body' => '> I don\'t agree.  First of all, there was also a huge difference in the
> training and leadership involved (a difference that, in the American
> Civil War, allowed Southern forces to acheive victory over armies
> that were superior in both numbers and equipment).

  Leadership yes, training no - Southern advantages had more to do with
superior battlefield direction.  As far as equipment goes, the South was
able to maintain battlefield parity in weapons until fairly late in the
war.  This was due to a combination of pre-war planning (Seccesionists
stocked Southern armories and funded a manufacturing plant i Virginia),
purchases in Europe, and arms and artillery captured from the Union.

  Actually, I\'ve seen it argued that the North could have won much
earlier if they had taken advantage of the new cartridge firearms earlier
in the war.  Conservatism in the procurement department prevented the
early fielding of large number of rapid-firing arms that would have given
Northern units a firepower advantage.  The South would have been unable
to match the Union\'s advantage due to lack of manufacturing capacity.

> Second of all, the advantage that superior technology gives you
> is greatly diminished when you go from defeating forces to
> occupying and holding territory.  In the Gulf War things would
> have been a lot different if we had needed to hold territory with
> a significant population.

  Very true.  I recently watched the Frontline documentary on the war,
and it was clear that the Army, haunted by visions of a second Vietnam,
wanted no part of a march into Iraq.

>
> > FOOD: Hunting, gathering, kitchen gardening, salting, smoking, drying,
> >       fermentation (?), winter wine.
> I agree wth the (?) for fermentation, wouldn\'t you need some sort of
> container, both to hold the fementing mash, but also for boiling the hops
> etc..  Unless anyone knows of a recipie that doesn\'t need the boling process?

  Boiling is used for two things in the fermentation process.  In beer
preparation (grain fermentation), boiling water is added to other water
in certain proportions to get the proper temp for the extration of sugars
through enymatic extraction.  Second, boiling is used to sterilize the
mixture prior to adding yeast.  Neither is necessary for fermentation -
there are plenty of bugs in the air that will make alcohol for you.
Problem is the other tastes you get.  The Sumerians made beer by tossing
a loaf of bread in a pot of water and waiting a week - tastes weird but
it\'ll get you drunk.  Oh, the above applies to fruit-based alcohol (wine)
as well.

>
>
> > ====================================
> > CONTAINERS: Large clay pots, glass bottles, leather bottles.
> How would the tube (assuming blown glass) be made?  It could be made from
> brass, though making tubes is quite a tricky thing.

  Charred wood works - one can also use native copper.

> > MILITARY: Chariots, war elephants, siege machines.
> Chariots and siege machines probably need Iron age tools.  Although you
> could make the wood working tools out of bronze, they don\'t hold their
> edges well.
> Its like the argument that the Egyptians who built the statues in
> the Valley of Kings, had to be Iron age.  You can\'t carve Granite with
> bronze tools!

  But you can carve with stone tools - the Pyramids were built with flint
tools, as were the tombs in the Valley of the Kings.  It\'s slow, but with
enough manpower, no problem

> No. Depending on the local conditions they could have a *real* hard
> time of it. But if they are to have *any* chance of long-term survival,
> the air has to be breathable, the water has to be somewhat drinkable,
> and available in reasonable quantities. And edible plants/animals have
> to be available fairly close to the landing site.

  The last is the one I have a hard time buying - what\'s the chance the
native vegitation/animal life is fully compatible?

>
> Right from the outset of playing Traveller, I was struck by several
> hard-to-understand "facts" that needed rationalizing:
>
> 1)The Imperium is a feudal society. How can this be?

  I seem to recall that in interviews, Marc Miller has atributed this to
the comunications limitation imposed by the jump drive - long delays in
command and control favor feudalism.

> 2)There is an immense range in TL from world to world. Hctb?

  As long as one assumes it reflects local ability to produce products,
no problem.

> 3)Technology has advanced very slowly over the last 35 centuies.

  This assumes that progress from tech level to tech level is linear and
each level takes the same amount of time.  it took lots of time to get
from 0 to 1 and 1 to 2 - why not long times for say 12 to 13?

> 4)The trade rules make no economic sense (assuming a free market
> economy).

  Who said the Imperium had a free market, especially with all those high
Law Levels out there. :-)

> 5)300,000 years ago, the ancients knew which races (the six major
> races) were going to get the jump (or should I say Jump-Drive) on their
> competitors. We can surmise that this fact is true from the presense of the
> Droyne, Humanity, Centaurs, Hivers, Vargr, and Aslan on their 3000- century
> old coynes. (See Adv. 3, Twilight\'s Peak)

  I seem to recall that the Coynes are nowhere near that old -
Grandfather popped out of his pocket universe more recently to hand them
out.  No mystery at all!

>
> 6)Devices such as jump drive, anti-gravity and black globes are
> magical; they break well known laws of physics. They are also isolated.
> Whatever science went into making them has not impacted technology in a wide
> range of applications; magic does not commonly occur in CT outside of these
> three inventions. (Let me ignore psionics at the moment.)

  Well, the game would not be Traveller without jump drive, and the other
two are cool.  What\'s your point?

7)Why would the Imperium be so interested in settling the Spinward
> Marches, which is on the other side of the great rift in enemy territory,
> when there\'s all this empty territory rimward? The main thrust of Imperial
> expansion was spinward even before the Solomani Rim seceded from the
> Imperium. (Perhaps this was one of the Solomani motives for doing so.)

  This is the one point where you have something.  Vargr suppression is
my explanation, but who knows?

  By the way, we know that the Aslan did not discover J-drive themselves
- they got it from the Solomani.  Unless you figure Granfather arranged
that, well, it think it causes a bit of a problem with your theory.


