On Tue, 23 Jan 1996, Hans Rancke-Madsen wrote:

> Phillip McGregor writes:
> >However, the main problem is that there was only a one TL difference between
> >the competitors ... the Terrans achieved Jump3 while the Vilani had only
> >Jump2.
> >
> >Looking along the same TL lines, Jump3 is TL12 and Jump2 TL 11.

Okay, here\'s a TL point for you all from a lurker (myself).   The
closest star to our planet (Earth) is Proxima Centauri at about 1.3
parsecs; the next closest star, Barnard\'s Star, is 1.8 parsecs away.
Now, from a strict constructionist POV, Earth achieves a Jump1 drive at
TL 10, which allows for one parsec jumps, but can\'t GET anywhere.  If you
jump towards Proxima Centauri, you come up just over a light year short
with a Jump1 drive.  Even if you are generous with the rules, a light
year is by no means a short distance.  According to the timeline in the
TNE main book, Terrans encounter the Vilani at Barnard\'s Star (1.8pc or
Jump2 away) 9 years after just _discovering_ jump drive.  That TL
progression seems a little speedy to me, considering how long it took
aviation technology to bridge the oceans, for example.  Kind of throws a
wrench into abstracted tech level definition.  If Barnard\'s Star was
another parsec in either direction, tech level would have been radically
different.

Just some thoughts.

