Let me just start by saying that I have never actually *played* 2300AD; I\'ve
only read the books and some adventures.  Therefore I don\'t have much
opinion on lots of practical issues.

The thing I like the best is that it has a very "hard science" feel to it.
There\'s no grav vehicles or artificial gravity in ships or "black globes".
Just about the only thing that works like "magic" is the stutterwarp, and
you\'ve gotta get past lightspeed *somehow*.

I also liked the aliens--what we know of them.  The Kafers and the Ebers are
both wonderfully detailled and *truly* alien, but it\'s a little frustruating
not to know more about other races, such as the Sung.  Also, there are
details that I\'d like to have on those races in game terms that just aren\'t
available--e.g. how equivelant characteristics such as strength compare to
those of Humans.  On the other hand, if there\'s information on the market,
players as well as referees will buy it, and alot of the mystery could be
lost (witness the case of the Droyne/Ancients in Traveller). Also, since the
aliens in 2300 are *so* alien, it\'s real work to figure out ways for them to
interact with Humans (with the exception of the Kafers, of course).

Then there are the ships.  I like what\'s in the basic set in terms of
describing ships, but it\'s not enough.  As an old _Traveller_ player, I look
forward to designing my own ships and would like some idea of how to come up
with deckplans for when they\'re needed.

The world generation system is absolutely ingeneous.  I love it to death.
It gives the characteristics that you need for a frontier world right away
(unlike _Traveller_ which is good for describing settled regions of space).
Also, I liked the way animal encounters were set up--making sure that
animals wouldn\'t be in locations that couldn\'t support them.

That\'s about all I can think of... right now.  Thanks for letting me sound
off; please forward to any relevant groups.

