    'body' => '
>
>Right from the outset of playing Traveller, I was struck by several
>hard-to-understand "facts" that needed rationalizing:
>
>1)The Imperium is a feudal society. How can this be?

I never liked this idea of a fuedal society. It seems to me to one of the
possible systems they could have used for the game. Because communication
times are reduced to travel times and some reaches of the Imperium are great
time distances from the core a large degree of autonomy exists in sectors,
subsectors and systems. To hold the Imperium together under such
circumstances would require a strong sense of duty to the Capital. Leaders
that owed their legitimacy to the Capital and the Core would provide this
sense of duty and would act to ensure their sphere of influence was
maintained within the fold of the Imperium. Democratic leaders on the other
hand who owed their legitimacy to the people or citizens of their sector,
subsector, and system, would have little sense of duty to the Capital in a
situation of large communication times with the Capital.
I guess that is how it is justified and maintained.
How it started, I have no idea. I too think it is kind of odd.
>
>2)There is an immense range in TL from world to world. Hctb?

I had a problem with that one for a while also. I still do a little. If you
think of TL as a measure of availability than of anything more substantial.
TL could be explained by a number of things. What explanation you give to
players for the TL of a particular world depends very much on what the other
indicators are for that world.
>
>3)Technology has advanced very slowly over the last 35 centuies.
>
>4)The trade rules make no economic sense (assuming a free market
>economy).

Each world has its own regime and this determines how that world relates to
any supposed interstellar markets.
Also, because communication time is equal to travel time the type of free
market we think of today is hardly relevant. The best approx is
pre-telegraph times on Earth where communication times were the same as
travel times over large distances. Over short distances signalling by flag,
fire or light was used but over long distances communication time is pretty
much the same as travel time.
In circumstances where communication times are close to travel times and
those times are large, the structure of business would be a lot like the
grand English and Dutch East India Companies and the Hudson Bay Company.
That is how I like to think of trade in the Traveller environment and have
found that reading about these great trading companies and their rivalry has
given me a good feel for how to run it in the Trav universe.

>
>5)300,000 years ago, the ancients knew which races (the six major
>races) were going to get the jump (or should I say Jump-Drive) on their
>competitors. We can surmise that this fact is true from the presense of the
>Droyne, Humanity, Centaurs, Hivers, Vargr, and Aslan on their 3000- century
>old coynes. (See Adv. 3, Twilight\'s Peak)
>

I never liked Twilights Peak anyway. I have always thought that the concept
of the Ancients was rather cliched post-God invention that Von Daniken would
respect greatly. "Was God an astronaut?"

>6)Devices such as jump drive, anti-gravity and black globes are
>magical; they break well known laws of physics. They are also isolated.
>Whatever science went into making them has not impacted technology in a wide
>range of applications; magic does not commonly occur in CT outside of these
>three inventions. (Let me ignore psionics at the moment.)

I agree and believe that it is left like this to avoid unnecessarily
complicating the fundamentals of the game. There is plenty of scope for
individual referees to take up the task of incorperating the further
implications of these technologies in their own senarios. In my experience
it hasn\'t really been a problem. I would simply let it be known to the
players that it was commonly rumoured that research into the full potential
and other uses of those technologies was well underway in secret facilities
on many high-tech worlds. Authorities deny this of course.
 Make it seem like there are many things that appear as magic in the
universe that can really only be explained by a few scientists and other
people capable of seeing the wiring under the board. Players hate that - I
like to think of it as the "Call of Cthullu" or "X-files" effect.

Simon Harding
