    'topic' => ' XBOAT digest 511',
    'body' => 'Even the WWII example you use is not correct - the Allies didn\'t
>win because they had more tanks, they won because they had better
>airplanes (in large part due to higher octane aviation fuel that allowed
>higher power to weight ratios) that gave air superiority and battlefield
>control.
>>>1.  I think that the point that is being made is that overwhelming
quantitive superiority will defeat technological superiority, and with a
terrible cost.  Take the Eastern front during WWII.  The Wehrmacht was a
technologically superior superior and much better trained force than the Red
Army.  The Red Army, however, was HUGE.  It is estimated that the Germans
killed some 20 million Soviets.  Losses like that would have bled most
countries white.  The Soviets just absorbed the losses and keep on
fighting.<<<<

  Soviet failure was due to the purges done by Stalin before the war, not
tech inferiority.  The T-34 was the best tank of the war, bar none, and
the KV and JS series of heavy tanks could take on anything the Germans
had at equivalent times (plus their engines ran more reliabley as well).
Soviet Artillery was the best in the world (accuracy and range).  Soviet
small arms were at least as good as the German, plus they worked much
better in extreme cold.  Soviet aircraft were qualitatively equal, though
failure of doctrine and inferior, inexperienced pilots made the Soviet
air force ineffective until late in the war.

  The Soviets, with some lend-lease help, won WWII, and they did it with
weapons evey bit the match for those fielded by the Germans.  Our
perceptions of the Soviet war machine was distorted by the cold war and
the use of German descriptions of eastern front combat.  MAsters of
strategic decit and armed with quality weapons, Stalin\'s legions saved
the West\'s butt.

>>>>Not really on topic but:
2.  The Allies won for many reasons, air power was one of them.  As for the
Allies having better planes I guess that it depends on your definition of
better.  Both sides had excellent aircraft.  Air power alone cannot win a
war against a determined enemy.  You need an army to go in and take ground,
and in many cases a navy to control the seas as well.<<<<

  Allied aircrft destoyed the communication systems and fuel production
facitities of the Germans before the invasion.  After, Allied tactical
airpower made daylight German movements suicidal.  Note the succes of the
Battle of the Bulge, conducted when Allied aircraft were grounded by weather.

>>>>As for the Gulf War, tech did not win that. What won it was *training*
- the allies had it, and the Iraqis didn\'t. Tech gave the allies an edge,
but it was training that was the killer. The Iraqi soldiers were little
better than partly trained rabble compared to the western and allied
forces ... good enough to stand off Pasdaran (Iranian) "human wave"
attacks, but nowhere *near* good enough to beat the allies. I would say
that an equivalent force of 1970\'s allied troops would have been able to
trash the Iraqis probably just as quickly if they were trained to
equivalent standards. <<<<<

  Allied aircraft, like the F-117, enjoyed tech advantages that allowed
the destruction of much of the air defense net operated by Iraq.  Guided
missiles then destroyed much of the Iraqi tank force, as well as
infrastructure and the Iraqi soldier\'s will to resist.  Allied tanks and
artillery routinely engaged and destroyed Iraqi targets at ranges the
Iraqis could not match, due to gun stabilisation, rangefinders, and
depleted uranium projectiles.  Technology counts - training was
important, but superiour tech allowed victory to be achieved far faster
and with far fewer casualties.

  As an aside, a friend of mine was a reserve officer commanding a unit
equiped with M1A1 tanks.  On the gunnery range, they practiced fire only
with the computer fire system turned off ("degraded mode").  Why?  With
the computer on, they hit first time, every time, even with the tank
moving on uneven terrain - not much of a challenge.  Technology _works_,
as long as you train your troops to use it properly.

