    'topic' => 'Explaining the Present with the Past',
    'body' => 'I got lots of responses to my "Secret Histories" post. Thank
you everyone!

>From: Summers@Ethyl-the-Frog.ARC.NASA.gov (David P. Summers)

...(many interesting comments deleted)

>>2)      There is an immense range in TL from world to world. Hctb?

>We have an immense range from continent to continent (and even withing
>continents).  Look at Africa.   And we have much faster trade and
>communications between parts of the world than the Imperium has
>between systems.

Yes, it always seemed to me that GDW made these wide variations in TL
to mimic the situation in our world today. But the wide variations we see in
Africa, Oceania, and the Americas today are primarily due to accidents of
history. The Guarani are not very technologically advanced because until
recently they were not exposed to western technology. They are rapidly
learning tho, as are the world\'s other low-tech peoples.

But in CT, by 1104 (the year Adv. #1 takes place) accidents of history
should be, well, history. The Marches have been settled for a thousand
years, and have shared a common history for that long.  There must be
another reason why TL\'s vary so much. In my previous post, I proposed that
it was due to fallout from the feudal political/social/economic system.
A case could still be made for historical reasons, but it would require
an interesting explanation.

>>3)      Technology has advanced very slowly over the last 35 centuies.
>
>This takes a presumption that the modern western attitudes toward
>technology and change is a passing one.  This is not that far fetched.
>The concept of "progress" is one that sets western attitudes apart
>from most historical cultures.  If you look at Ancient Greece, the
>Roman Empire, several Chinese Dynasties, you see cultures that
>could have made major technological changes and simply chose not
>to.

I agree completely! That\'s why I took the trouble to rationalize
how it was that our culture changed its current concept of progress to
the one prevalent in the CT universe. Other explanations are possible of
course. YMMV.

>7)      Why would the Imperium be so interested in settling the Spinward
>Marches, which is on the other side of the great rift in enemy territory,
>when there\'s all this empty territory rimward?
>
>The Spinward Marches aren\'t "in" enemy territory.  They were settle
>because they were mostly unclaimed and undeveloped.  When Imperium
>settlement in that direction ran up against Zhodani settlement
>coming from the other direction, Imperial Expansion mostly came
>to a halt.  Is the Imperium all that "interested" in the
>Spinward Marches?  I don\'t see that they get any attention
>disproportionated to their situation.

Well, I clearly exagerated when I called Deneb "enemy territory."
Still, the Spinward Marches are on the Zhodani Side of the Great Rift.
They are as far away from Sylea as Terra is, and yet they were being
colonized 60 years after the founding of the Imperium. It wasn\'t until
four centuries later that Terra was absorbed.

There are scads of ways of rationalizing this. At first I just told
my players that there had been hostile states between Sylea and the Rim.
But when I read that Ancient sites tended to center around the Spinward
Marches, I saw a way to fit that interesting datum into my overall scheme
of the Imperium. 8^)

>From: mhclark@iastate.edu

