Yes, my scenario for the variation in TL implies that the TL is a
measure of implamentation ability, and not discovery. I guess I agree with
Hans on that. (I say that with some trepidation, he\'s been taking a lot of
heat lately!)

...(more stuff deleted)

>> 4)The trade rules make no economic sense (assuming a free market
>> economy).
>
>  Who said the Imperium had a free market, especially with all those high
>Law Levels out there. :-)

High Law Levels, and feudalism to boot! Yes it seems pretty obvious
that the Imperium must have a command economy. The only issue is what form
does it take? I detailed my scenario earlier, so I\'ll shut up now. But on
an almost related topic, I\'ll mention that National Geographic had an article
on the Hanseatic League last year. It provided for some interesting insights
into feudal economics, a subject I know almost nothing about.

>> 5)300,000 years ago, the ancients knew which races (the six major
>> races) were going to get the jump (or should I say Jump-Drive) on their
