[regading technology level variations]
>        Yes, it always seemed to me that GDW made these wide variations in TL
>to mimic the situation in our world today. But the wide variations we see in
>Africa, Oceania, and the Americas today are primarily due to accidents of
>history.

There are similar accidents of history in the Imperium.

>The Guarani are not very technologically advanced because until
>recently they were not exposed to western technology. They are rapidly
>learning tho, as are the world\'s other low-tech peoples.

Not true.  The inability of third world nations to keep up, even after
over a century of exposure to western technology, has been a source
of continuing frustration.  This is in the face United Nations (and
other) programs to address just that problem.  Given the Imperium
laise-faire attutude toward local development, backward nations are
faced with same catch-22.  You can\'t afford to import technology
unless you have the technology to make some thing worth while.
(In addition to the problem that, since technolgies are interlinked,
the lack of technolgies cripples your ability to use technologies you
do import).

>But in CT, by 1104 (the year Adv. #1 takes place) accidents of history
>should be, well, history. The Marches have been settled for a thousand
>years, and have shared a common history for that long.

And part of that history is one of regression and loss of trade.  Also,
large portions of the Spinward Marches weren\'t part of the Imperium
for all the thousand years (a lot of it still isn\'t).  If you add
in Imperial neglect and the fact that trade is restricted to only
those who can afford expensive high tech craft (imagine an African
village that wants to improve itself when everything has be imported
by Lear Jet) I don\'t see a big problem.

>        Well, I clearly exagerated when I called Deneb "enemy territory."
