    'body' => 'Greetings All:

To follow up on a recent comment:

"I\'ve got most of Chandler\'s stuff. Though his stories are (IMHO) are a
lot less like Traveller than (for example) E.C.Tub\'s "Dumarest of
Terra" series (which *has* to be where they got fast drug and slow drug)
And Chandler\'s Universe has a history that was specifically set up to
*make* lost colonies likely. Traveller has nothing equivalent to the
\'gaussjammers\'."

While I agree in general, wasn\'t there a incident involving some
slower-than-light colony ships that provides the background history to
(Classic) Traveller Adventure 5: Trillion Credit Squadron? I seem to recall
some multi-generation colony ships getting lost and developing a thriving
micro-civilization in the sector they ended up in (Far Islands? Books are
home...). A jump-capable ship mis-jumps into the area and they discover it
and start to copy jump technology...

Also, anybody out there ever read Marc Miller\'s description of how to set up
a Traveller game, using his first session of running (Classic) Traveller
Adventure 4: Leviathan? As you may recall, Leviathan was actually written by
the folks of Games Workshop before they were swallowed by the Space
Hulk/Warhammer Monster. Marc got the manuscript (according to the article)
and started running it for the local group. The first planet they came to had
a atmosphere of zero (vacuum) but also had a population! So, he postulated a
lost colony, built along the lines of Fritz Leiber\'s classic SF story "A Pail
of Air" (a must read to show how you could adapt low tech to a vacuum
situation!). He threw in a few interesting tidbits along the way (including
some rather gross creatures), and ta-da! Instant lost colony...

Fred Kiesche
(FKiesche3@aol.com)
(Knight of the Third Imperium)

