    'body' => '>  Soviet failure was due to the purges done by Stalin before the war, not
>tech inferiority.
The Soviets had no failure, they were on the winning side :).  They had a
bad start.

>The T-34 was the best tank of the war, bar none, and
>the KV and JS series of heavy tanks could take on anything the Germans
>had at equivalent times (plus their engines ran more reliabley as well).

>Soviet Artillery was the best in the world (accuracy and range).
I was never a gunner so I don\'t know about the quality of artillery, I
always though guns wuz guns. :)
But I do know that they had LOTS of guns, and the ammo to use with them.

>Soviet small arms were at least as good as the German, plus they worked much
>better in extreme cold.
>From my military experience, all small arms seem to work about equally in
the extreme cold, give equal care.  The Soviets were probably just better
trained in how to use them in the cold weather.

You are partly right about distortions resulting from the Cold War and
descriptions.  As for your claims about the quality of the Soviet equipment,
could you please e-mail a bibliography of your sources?  I will freely admit
that my knowledge of the Red Army at that time is not extensive.  The point
that I was trying to make was that overwelming numbers can defeat
technology.  Maybe I used a bad example.  Perhaps the Anglo-Zulu war would
be a better example of how huge numbers can defeat technology.

>
>>>>>Not really on topic but:
>2.  The Allies won for many reasons, air power was one of them.  As for the
>Allies having better planes I guess that it depends on your definition of
>better.  Both sides had excellent aircraft.  Air power alone cannot win a
>war against a determined enemy.  You need an army to go in and take ground,
>and in many cases a navy to control the seas as well.<<<<
>
>  Allied aircrft destoyed the communication systems and fuel production
>facitities of the Germans before the invasion.  After, Allied tactical
>airpower made daylight German movements suicidal.  Note the succes of the
>Battle of the Bulge, conducted when Allied aircraft were grounded by weather.
All true.  I am not downplaying the importance of air or navy power.  But
again, air power alone did not win Overlord or the Battle of the Bulge, it
supported it.  No matter what, men are needed to go in on the ground and
physically remove the enemy from the ground they are holding, and then to
protect that ground which has been taken.

> Technology counts - training was important, but superiour tech dallowed
victory to be achieved far faster
>and with far fewer casualties.
>  As an aside, a friend of mine was a reserve officer commanding a unit
>equiped with M1A1 tanks.  On the gunnery range, they practiced fire only
>with the computer fire system turned off ("degraded mode").  Why?  With
>the computer on, they hit first time, every time, even with the tank
>moving on uneven terrain - not much of a challenge.  Technology _works_,
>as long as you train your troops to use it properly.
Here I entirely agree with you.  The trick to TRAIN.  Technology is an
important factor, but the most important factor is people.  People are made
better with training.
