    'from' => 'Michael Davis',
    'topic' => ' Jump Torps and the X-Boats.',
    'body' => 'On Fri, 26 Jan 1996 05:39:35 -0500 you wrote:

>The jump-torpedoes would never ne able to replace the X-Boat network for
>several reasons.
>1. They have a limited storeage capacity for messages.
>   Compare the space for storeage and transition media in an
>   X-Boat with the torpedo.

Even now we can store large amounts of data in very small spaces, the
storage capacity is not a factor.

>2. They are not secure.
>   You can\'t predict when or where a torpedo (or ship) is going
>   to arrive in your system with any great accuracy.
>   When it arrives a j-torp broadcasts its message reguardless of
>   who\'s about.
>   An X-Boat can establish a tight beam link with the IISS suport
>   vessel to down load its messages securely.

Secure!!  A torp would be secure, the message would be secure and
without any problem a torp could set up a tight laser link, we do that
now.

>3. Cost!  What is the cost per "unit message" of the j-torp and
>   an X-Boat?  Are the torpedoes reuseable?  I understand that
>   these are *disposable*, say for saving the ship\'s log if it
>   looks like the ship is going to be destroyed.

Cost is a factor in everything but \'unit message\' cost would not
factor in.  I always see a torp as a disposable, after all you are not
going to match vectors before the torp jumps and it will not be worth
the cost to recover and you may not be able to recover it.

>
>4. "Politics"  The X-Boat network is the Govenments
>   communications network (it carries civilian mail to help pay the
>   costs).  Certain groups are going to highlight the unsecureity
>   of j-torps, to help the IISS keep its patch.
>

Wrong, the X-Boat network is the Civil network, both the military and
the Imperial family maintain a fleet of jump 6 ships for passing
messages.  The X-Boats just carry the mail for everyone else, and they
carry the bulk of normal Imperial business.

There are a lot of limits on Jump Torps and their uses.  In one case
you have the complete jump torp which is just a starship without a
crew.  This is very expensive to build and operate, and you have a
large chance to lose it in use.  On the other hand you have the jump
torp that depends on the mother ship to power it jump drive and cut a
tape to use in the computer.  While smaller and cheaper it has its own
problems, such as the extra equipment required on the mothership and
the fact that the mothership must move away from the planet to use the
torp.
The X-boats are a cheap and reusable method of communicating while
jump torps are expensive to use and normally are just one shot
affairs.  But I have allowed jump torps at times, in one case the
player set up jump six route between two systems for humm shall we say
business purposes.  The jump torp had a mothership that serviced and
recovered it, normally the mothership would handle the insystem
movement to place the torp on the trajectory, charge the jump drive,
and program the jump computer.  When a torp arrived insystem the
mothership would recover, repair, and restock the torp for reuse.  I
had placed losses on the torps at 10% and required extra costs for the
motherships with the schedule he wanted to use. (He did not expect the
men on the ships to take any R&R and had to pay the price, and when he
wanted to move the motherships to another system he found out that it
cost a great amount to ship 400 ton insystem ships.)

Even one of my own characters uses jump torps for emergency messages
between her base (generation ship in deep space) and her companies.
These torps are one use only systems and cost as much as a small ship.
  Their main use is to call of help for the base.

Jump torps may have a place but that place is a very limited because
of cost, for normal business uses the X-Boat system is very cost
effective to use.  Think of it, your letter to grandma, the latest
profit figures, and a update to a library would cost a lot less than
the fuel used to charge the jump drive for the torp.  Now the
information about the Navy winning or losing a battle, a upswing in
prices of certain goods, or even the gossip of the court might be
worth the cost of a torp.


**********
Michael Davis
**********
