    'body' => 'Mon, 29 Jan 1996 10:50:42, That Computer Guy <darkstar@UDel.Edu>
>And I have to ask why?  J-6 is only for military couriers.  The
>X-boats for private citizens are j-4.

The fact is that X-boats are presented as the fastest form of
communications unless you can afford the huge cost of maintaining
a network of j-6 couriers.  This gives the big powers an edge.
Jump Torps, unless they cost almost as much as a jump-6 courier,
fundamentally mess with this (which is an important part of the
background).  You also have other side effects (such as in
military situations that I mentions).

You have to remember (and this is a mistake made over and over)
is that new technologies have consequences that don\'t immediately
occur unless you think about it (and sometime not even then).
If you introduce a technology (especially one that touches
on a fundamental limitation to the society, in this case
communications) you are messing with the background.

>Also, we haven\'t come up with
>the cost of one of these beasties.  How are we to know that they are
>cheaper and more cost effective than a X-boat?

I\'ve seen various schemes where you rule by fiat that the Imperium
plots against, or they are (for some reason) one shot divises, or
they are unusually expensive.  The problem with this, as you get
with all arbitrary "this is how it works" decisisions, is that
it just strains suspension of disbelief a bit further and makes
it all seem a bit hokey.  (and even then, you keep having to
deal with every new and unexpeted use the players can some
up with).

If you like jump torps enought that you are willing to make
a significant change the background, that\'s fine.  But you
have to be aware that you are making a significant change.

