    'body' => 'Charles,
You made some interesting points, here are a few replies.  We may have to
agree to disagree in the end \'methinks ;-)

> From: Charles Collin <charles@hebb.psych.mcgill.ca>
> Subject: Jump Torps
> To Alun:
>
> Here are your reasons for why jump torps could not replace X-boats, and
> my objections to them.
>
> Limited Storeage Capacity:  I don\'t think this is true.  We can hold
> several terrabytes of info in something a few cubic meters in volume
> now.  By TL 10 or 12, storage capacities should be virtually unlimited by
> our standards.
Agred, but data, and data formats tend to expand to fill the available
space. (The jump in disk space needed for Word 6, over Word 2 is enormous)

> Lack of Security:  Someone pointed out that you could easily have a jump
> torp come in system and tight beam its message at a ground station.  This
> is a TL-8 procedure.  It could then erase its messages to prevent enemy
> interception.
But this requires that the j-torp knows *where* it is on arival, *where*
the recieving station is, and the recieving station needs to know where
and when the j-torp will appear!  The mechanics of jump don\'t allow this
sort of accuracy.  You need some astrogation on the part of the arriving
ship to fix its position.  Either good sensors at the reciever or a
broadcast from the arriving ship to alert the recieving station to align
its tight-beam link.  A jump exit position can vary by several
hundred-thousand kilometers, and the time of exit can vary by upto a day
or so.
The notes on the j-torp in Leviethan sugest that the j-torp broadcasts
its data on arrival, reguardless as to who (if anyone) is listening.


> High Cost:  This one is hard to figure.  Some people have argued that the
> jump torps should be disposable because the cost of recovery would be too
> high.  I disagree.  You just have to put a small dirt-cheap chemical
> rocket or ion drive on it, and it can eventually guide itself into orbit
> around whatever system body you like.  Depending on where it comes in,
> recovery time might be days, weeks or months, but in a continuously
> running communication system, this wouldn\'t be a problem.
Would all this, plus the guidance system, tightbeam link, astrogation,
