    'index' => 'ac516',
    'body' => 'In Reply to Alun:


>>>>>>>>>>
Charles,
You made some interesting points, here are a few replies.  We may have to
agree to disagree in the end \'methinks ;-)
<<<<<<<<<<

Thanks for the compliment, and I return it.  I also agree that we may
have to agree to disagree.  But please allow me one more chance to convince
you of the error of your ways :-)


>>>>>>>>>>
> Limited Storeage Capacity:  I don\'t think this is true.  We can hold
> several terrabytes of info in something a few cubic meters in volume
> now.  By TL 10 or 12, storage capacities should be virtually unlimited by
> our standards.
Agred, but data, and data formats tend to expand to fill the available
space. (The jump in disk space needed for Word 6, over Word 2 is enormous)
<<<<<<<<<<

I agree in turn, but the I think the rate of data size increase is slower
and more likely to hit a cieling value (e.g., there\'s no need for more
than 24-bit color, since the human eye can\'t distinguish finer gradients
anyway) than storage capacity.  In any case, a j-torp would certainly be
able to carry an adequate amount of info to make it practical.


>>>>>>>>>>
> Lack of Security:  Someone pointed out that you could easily have a jump
> torp come in system and tight beam its message at a ground station.  This
> is a TL-8 procedure.  It could then erase its messages to prevent enemy
> interception.
But this requires that the j-torp knows *where* it is on arival, *where*
[snip]
hundred-thousand kilometers, and the time of exit can vary by upto a day
or so.
The notes on the j-torp in Leviethan sugest that the j-torp broadcasts
its data on arrival, reguardless as to who (if anyone) is listening.
<<<<<<<<<<<

I guess there\'s no real way to resolve this issue.  It just depends on
how smart you think a j-torp can be made.  If it can do the following
sequence, then it\'s probably pretty secure:

1) enter the system and determine its position relative to a ground station.
2) send a broadcast message to a ground station saying "prepare to
recieve tight beam message from coordinates XYZ".
3) send a tightbeam to the groundstation.
4) erase all info once it has been successfully transmitted (or when
someone tries to tamper with the torp).


>>>>>>>>>>>
> High Cost:  This one is hard to figure.  Some people have argued that the
> jump torps should be disposable because the cost of recovery would be too
> high.  I disagree.  You just have to put a small dirt-cheap chemical
> rocket or ion drive on it, and it can eventually guide itself into orbit
> around whatever system body you like.  Depending on where it comes in,
> recovery time might be days, weeks or months, but in a continuously
> running communication system, this wouldn\'t be a problem.
Would all this, plus the guidance system, tightbeam link, astrogation,
jump drive, message banks, power system and fuel, all fit into a
jump-torpedo?
<<<<<<<<<<<

Again, it\'s a question of how good you think you can build a jump-torp.
Intuitively, I think all of the above could probably fit in something 50
cubic meters in volume (4 tons).  The Voyager probes have primitive
versions of all the systems you mention (except, of course, the jump
drives :-), and they\'re quite a manageable size.  With increased tech, it
doesn\'t strike me as implausible.  Any gearheads out there want to try
designing one of these things with FF&S?



In Reply to Robert Flammang:

>J-torps affect the
>X-boat network about as much as automated drones affect Federal Express
>today.

I don\'t think your analogy is correct.  It would be more apt (IMO) to
say: J-torps affect the X-boat network about as much as the Galileo probe
affects the Space Shuttle Outer System Exploration Program (SSOSEP?).
That is to say, it renders it non-existant.  One does not send a large
manned craft to do what a small unmanned craft can do if one is trying to
be economical.

Charles.


