David P. Summers writes:
>I\'m not sure what you mean.  Are you saying that if I could buy a machine
>that delivers my package faster than Federal Express, without my
>ever having to go to a Fed Exp office (or wait for pickup), to
>any destination regardless how remote from federal express offices
>it is, that it wouldn\'t affect Federal Express?  Boloney.

Well, if it cost a million dollars per package, each time you used it,
you\'d probably begin to think that Federal Express wasn\'t such a bad
deal after all. And if Federal Express owned rights to the technology
and got a royality every time you used the machine, they probably wouldn\'t
mind either way what you did.

If the machine had the possibility of going off in the wrong direction
and posing a hazard to the general public, there are various legal and
regulatory agencies who\'d probably care very much when and where you
used your machine.

Even though we\'re all using e-mail, the Post Office is still doing some
business. They haven\'t been completely marginalized by this example of
new and better technology. Reading the news, the PO is now attempting to
set itself up as some kind of controller for e-mail, applying some type
of virtual "stamp" to every piece of e-mail for starters, with the
implication that we would all be billed for this service. Think that might
have an impact on how we use this technology?

