    'from' => 'Andy Lilly',
    'year' => 1996,
    'index' => 'ac545',
    'body' => 'JUMP TORPEDOES

Comparing x-boats to j-torps, it seems to me that the latter will have a
limited storage, significantly higher cost and (marginally) lower guarantee
of arrival. I believe that for all major routes, the economies of carrying
the gigagigagigagigabytes of data which will go between systems will make
the x-boats the only sensible option (we\'re not just talking electronic
postcards here - remember the amount of banking, administration, etc. data
which must pass between major systems - all heavily encrypted). To carry the
same amount of data as an x-boat you might need to have 10 or more j-torps.
Which if they\'re not recovered add to the garbage floating in space (even a
self-destruct leaves debris).

Another consideration is the law. A j-torp entering a system from jump is
small and difficult to detect; even with automatic collision advoidance,
there may have been incidents in the past where such things nearly hit other
spacecraft or (more likely) were fired upon as potential missiles. Having a
pilot along (ala x-boat) gives you someone to blame and someone to take
action when the computer runs out of ideas...

For Leviathan, the ship was operating in a _frontier_ area. It _couldn\'t_
use x-boats and the rules restricting j-torp usage wouldn\'t apply because of
the lack of shipping in the area. There seems to me no reason whatsoever why
such an expeditionary group couldn\'t have got special dispensation to use
j-torps.

There has been some discussion on military usage. Naturally this would be
less restricted (since the military tend to ignore or make the rules as
suits them). No, they\'re not inherently faster than using normal ships to
carry messages but they do have a stealth advantage. This could lead to a
sudden proliferation of jump-capable attack torpedoes for world bombardment,
much like the asteroid/mass-driver attack discussion which we had some
months back (no, please, don\'t start that up again!).

>News of Strephon\'s death travelled to the Spinward Marches through j-6
>Imperiallines couriers. I don\'t see how j-torps (at TL15) could be any
>faster than that.

PSIONICS STEPS IN...

Not j-torps no, but it is known that the Imperium uses psi\'s for its own
intelligence purposes and some psi\'s can communicate telepathically across
interstellar distances. In my games this is used as the Emperor\'s private
commo system to all his sector governors. It\'s only used in emergencies, but
it does allow him to act before anyone else gets word via the x-boat system.
Then there are his groups of psionic advisers who look into the future,
check the minds of all around for assassins, etc. The Emperor in my games
really is the power centre of the Imperium and much of the feudal hierarchy
of dukes, et al. is sustained by his power rather than just on the say of
some voting body like the Moot!

THE IMPERIAL BOOT

Oh, and when people are talking about whether common ships (e.g.
adventurers\' ships) can be jump 6, etc. then I would point you toward the
care with which Han Solo in Star Wars had to hide his ship\'s capabilities,
and compare it with traffic police today. Anyone with big engines and (for
starships) weapons who can\'t show why they need them is going to be in
trouble. Every ship that lands at every major starport should be visited by
customs, quarantine, safety engineers, etc. for landing checks.
Irregularities are quickly noticed unless carefully camouflaged...

"Morning, sir."
Jake Blaine noticed the slight edge of sarcasm in the customs sargeant\'s
voice. The compupad was in the man\'s hand, carefully angled so Jake couldn\'t
quite see what was on the screen but the officer\'s eyes kept sweeping down
it as though he had to keep reminding himself of a substantial list of
irregularities.
"Anything... wrong?" Nervous, though Jake, and added quickly "Officer?" in a
more confident and friendly tone.
"This ship\'s license never seems to have been updated to include the engine
upgrade..." said the officer, steely eyes staring into Jake\'s.
"Ah, well, I felt it was a little underpowered-"
"It is a trader, sir?"
"Yes, of course-"
"And the 6-G drives save you time getting out to the jump point, eh, sir?"
"Yes, of course-"
"And it would just be ridiculously silly of me to think that these drives
would be for out-running customs ships, wouldn\'t it?" The man assumed a
fixed lupine smile.
"Er, yes - it\'s purely the jump point-"
"Hmmm."
Jake fell silent.
"Anything else?" asked the officer.
"Errr..."
"Like a complete history of the local universe, isn\'t it sir?"
"Sorry?"
"Well, clearly the economy is tightening for speed to jump point to be so
critical as to invest MILLIONS OF CREDITS on the extra drives, then there\'s
the clear indication that star law enforcement is waning and piracy is on
the increase..."
"Whaa?"
"I refer of course to the extra pop-up turret. And clearly the pirates are
becoming more sophisticated, hence your need for long range jamming
equipment-"
Jake choked but the officer continued.
"-which, to prevent falling into the hands of any boarders, you thoughtfully
concealed beneath the deck plates under two of the passenger cabins... then
your personal armoury-"
"Ship defence!" coughed out Jake.
"Hmmm." The officer began reading from the list. "Two suits battledress, two
FGMP-15, two PGMP-14, ten Gauss rifles, 5000 rounds of ammo... that was just
in the FIRST locker we opened... then in the hold... how exactly did you get
hold of a grav\' tank, Mr. Blaine?"
..

whereas:

"Morning, your excellency."
Duke Josiah Deerguard made note of the appropriate deference in the customs
captain\'s voice.
"No problems I hope?" asked the Duke rhetorically, some inflection or tone
somehow managing to convey the messages that there had better not be or (a)
the officer would get an earful, (b) whichever engineer or administrator
among the Duke\'s staff had failed in their duty would be looking for a new
job.
"None sir. I just wanted to explain the extra few minutes delay in
processing your landing forms because of the extra checks we\'re obliged to
make now on the new Duplenix Jump-6 drives. I\'m glad to say that yours are
in perfect working order. No doubt a necessity to a diplomat of such
regional importance."
"Hmmm. Naturally." The Duke smiled his standard \'thank you, little
insignificant person\' smile and dismissed the officer.

PERSONAL WEAPONS VS. STARSHIPS IN CT

Hmmm, everyone\'s answered this one already, but I would like to reiterate
Charles\' canon quote (from a wide variety of CT books) that "...an average
hull can take 1000 points of "personal weapons" damage from lasers before a
man-sized hole is made. Even an iris valve can take 100..." and I usually
rule that this is assuming they are making a careful effort to cut/blast
said hole. Using a FGMP at close range to do this is dangerous because you
will get significant back-blast (molten metal, et al) from the energy bolt
hitting the hull. To put it in perspective, yes it\'s a canon quote (from
Mercenary I think) that a ship\'s laser makes a 50 meter radius crater/blast
area when fired at the ground.

CONTRA-GRAV & ANTI-GRAV

Phillip McGregor pointed out the problem with (particularly TNE) that
manoeuvre drives are supposed to be contra-grav now, so ships can just hover
in to land with no need for streamlining even on a world with an atmosphere.

Well, in my games I rule that:
(a) All grav\' devices create a gravitational force. They don\'t just
neutralise gravity. i.e. it\'s just like any other thrust-based system - it
has to be directed and controlled. And you can just hover downward through
the air, but any bricks had better hope that they don\'t try landing on a
\'just more than 1G\' world or a world with high winds, etc.

Alternatively, you could rule:
(b) That contra-grav does neutralise gravity but that this is not on an
automatic 1:1 basis, i.e. considerable amounts of control are required to
ensure the gravitic forces are balanced. So a grav\' cart is easy - always
used at the same altitude on the starport field, it needs only a single
setting to always hover 6" off the ground. However, when it meets a 9"
barrier, it doesn\'t just \'lift itself\' over - it can be lifted to a new
height by a user (e.g. to 12"), and will then stay there - the difference in
c-g settings is so minimal that the unit will act a bit like one of those
ceiling lights on a spring that you can pull down to a given height and it
always stays there until adjusted. Naturally flying a grav\' vehicle or ship
is a slightly more complex matter, and that\'s why you still need pilots to
do it. Remember that a c-g non-streamlined ship which gets blown off course
when landing is a bit like a balloon with a propeller engine - i.e. not very
controllable. The restriction on having at least minimal streamlining might
well be a legal requirement for landings, to ensure no mishaps occur. Then
again, worlds with a lot of floating grav cities may be so used to the
concept that flying bricks are (literally) a part of their existence...

Andy Lilly
Coordinating BITS (British Isles Traveller Support)

