    'from' => 'Hans Rancke-Madsen rancke@diku.dk',
    'year' => 1996,
    'index' => 'ac546',
    'topic' => 'A workable CT jump torpedo',
    'body' => 'David P. Summers have been arguing about the un-canonicality of jump
torpedoes
for a while now. However, it is quite possible to make a jump torpedo without
violating the 100 T drive envelope restriction. The concept is simple: You
take a jump engine (actually you only need the jump capacitor part of a jump
engine, but I don\'t think we know just how big a percentage of a jump engine
is capacitors). Around that you erect a collapsible framework or inflate a
ballon or something similar. You then put a jump net around it (The most 
elegant solution would be a ballon with the jump net already around it; the 
framework suggestion is just to anticipate any arguments about wether such
a ballon can be fashioned with TL 9+ technology). You use your own computer 
and your own jump engine to energize the torpedo capacitors. In the period 
of grace you have before the capacitors have to be discarded (the same 
period of grace you use to get drop tanks away from a ship that uses them) 
you uncouple the torpedo and push it away from your ship.

The size of a torpedo thus becomes about size of a jump drive, minus the
engine part of a drive plus the message medium, radio, collapsible framework
or balloon and the jump net. Roughly 2+ T for a jump-1 torpedo up to 7+ T
for a jump-6 torpedo. It should be reusable, though.

Now, if I were to run "Leviathan" I would make the jump torpedoes work this
way to avoid discussions with the players.


David:
>[Note, just so we don\'t forget, loss of the x-boat network is only
>one problem that jump-torps introduce to the background (I\'ve
>mentioned some before) and even you patch enough arbitrary restrictions
>to keep x-boats going, you still have to deal with those.]

But as you see, you have to deal with them anyway, because jump-torpedoes
ARE demonstrably possibly.

