    'year' => 1996,
    'from' => 'David P. Summers',
    'body' => 'Sat, 03 Feb 1996, Robert Flammang <FLAMMANG@vms.cis.pitt.edu>
>>This goes under the heading of imposing arbitrary restrictions
>>to make it work.  (in this case making j-torps arbitrarily expensive).
>
>Me:
>Hmm... I guess I don\'t see how anybody (you included) can avoid making
>arbitrary restrictions on j-torp technology. Steve and I arbitrarily
>restrict them by assuming high production costs. You arbitrarily
>restrict them by assuming they can\'t exist.

The restriction on jump-torps is based on a minumum size for a jump
unit which is easy to accept and also fits with other aspects of the
game (like why there aren\'t an ships under 100 tons).

>Hokeyness is a perennial problem in all science fiction, Traveller
>included. Since arbitrary restrictions on magical technology cannot be
>avoided, one has to cover up the hokeyness with well reasoned
>environments and good old fashioned showmanship. I always thought that
>CT did a particularly good job with this. It\'s why I like the game.

I agree it\'s a perennial problem, which is why one needs to
be on the look out for it.  A friend was telling me about the
one-suspension of disbelief rule.  Most people will allow
you to suspend disbelief one fact to set up a story.  If you
keep forcing someone to suspend belief on facts, things just
become more and more hokey.

Traveller is based on the belief that FTL travel is possible.
Everything else is pretty much a logic extrapolation off of how
they have set it up and how techology might have evolved. (there
a few minor things, but it\'s too late to try and remove them).

The problem with j-torps is that, to be done believably, you
really have to follow through with all the logical consequences.
This involves fundamental changes to the background.  It would
be a playable background, but it would be a different one.

>I couldn\'t agree more with the principle. But I need to point out that
>j-torps are not "new." They\'ve been around for quite awhile now. Longer
>than FFS by a decade.

They were mentioned in one adventure, not written my Marc Miller, and
never thouched on again.  My guess is that the sort of slipped by
GDW and, after they realized the consquences, they just quietly
dropped them.

>        Back to the old argument regarding military tactics.

It\'s an arguement that I have seen little contradiction of.

>I believe
>you said words to the effect of, "J-torps make it safer for a scout ship
>to jump into an enemy-occupied system. A scout ship can launch a j-torp back
>to the main fleet faster than it or a companion could jump back itself.
>In the pre-j-torp universe, such scouts might be blasted before they got
>a shot at returning."

No.  That wasn\'t my scenario.  There are a lot of scenario\'s.  You
set up a torpedo for two jump-3\'s (or make one a bit bigger so it
can do two jump-6\'s) and have in jump in and out of an unknown system.
Or you send in a torp that broadcasts sensor information and you jump
in near the system and monitor broadcasts as you come in through normal
space.  Or you have spy ship and it uses jump torps to send back
periodic reports without having to leave the system.  You can keep
coming with such secenarios.

Looking at it more fundamentally, Having to risks ships to jump into
a unknown system is one of the basic dilema\'s in Traveller, as is the
inability to send reports back without lessening your strength or
abandoning the position.  After all, jump torps make communications
easier and difficult communications is a fundamental premise of the
Traveller background.  They can\'t help but affect it.


