  {
    'month' => '02',
    'subj' => 'More about J-torps',
    'mo' => 'Feb',
    'ts-index' => '1996-02-07.ac563',
    'ts' => '1996Feb07',
    'file' => 'XBOAT96/XBT96526.TXT',
    'id' => '<199602071703.SAA07445@embla.diku.dk>',
    'index' => 'ac563',
    'body' => 'David P. Summers writes:
>And now you have to explain why a few factions in the Imperium went to the
>huge expense of mainting fleets of j-6 couriers and why j-torps didn\'t make
>such information much more widely available.

David, even though jump torpedoes are perfectly possible under CT, you\'d
still need ships (or space stations) to fire them off. The torps have to be
sent off from somewhere away from a gravity field. The torpedo capacitors
have to be energized by a jump engine and programmed by a sufficiently
large computer. Unless you want to throw the torpedo away (an expensive
way of sending a message) you need a ship at the destination to go fetch
it. If you don\'t want the torpedo to broadcast the message when it gets
to its destination, you _have_ to go fetch it in order to get the message.
Even then the torpedo has to broadcast a homing signal, which will hardly
enhance its popularity among people who went to such a lot of trouble to
keep their J-6 couriers secret as we\'re told they did. In short you need at
least one ship per node of a J-torp network. Plus the support structure to
keep the nodes manned (shipped? ;-) all the time. Add to this the impossi-
bility of keeping a J-torp network secret and the convenience of being able
to convey live people secretly by the couriers and I see plenty of reason
for the existence of Imperialines and equivalent networks.

>The problem is that your definition of "old" depends on how long it takes
>to get to a certain point in one course of action arbitarily chosen from
>a whole set of possibilities. In fact, I can think of one where the
>information from the torp is not only not 2 weeks old, but it isn\'t even
>1 week old (you send it into the system and jump near the system to recieve
>the data).

If you\'re near enough to recieve the data in less than a week then you\'re
near enough to collect it yourself. Besides, scout ships are _not_ at risk
when jumping into a strange system. Star systems are big places. If they
choose someplace off the main intra-system trade routes (like somewhere
off the plane of the system) the odds of a defensive ship being within
attack range of their point of emergence is vanishingly small.

>However, this only points up one of the problems with j-torps.  The
>fact that only a few factions of the Imperium can afford the huge cost
>of keeping up a network of j-6 couriers means that they can out-race
>the X-boat network and get important info before anyone else.  The
>high cost of j-6 ships is a partial restriction, and cheaper J-torps
>make such a information available to factions that can\'t keep of a
>network of couriers.

But with couriers you don\'t need a network to outrace the X-boat net. You
only need ONE J-6 courier. Granted that it will loose a day refuelling at
each intermediary system, but it will still outrace the X-boats. Given
pre-placed fuel dumps the loss can be cut to hours. And expensive as they
are, there are thousands of worlds with the budget to keep one courier
stationed permanently at Capital (I don\'t think many would, but they could.
Certainly there are not a single sector-wide organisation that couldn\'t
afford it. Heck, there must be universities in the Spinward Marches that
could afford it). Compare that to the cost of keeping a ship on standby for
every 6 parsecs the message must travel, and the J-torp network dosen\'t
seem nearly as attractive.

(And, yes, I know that Imperrialines have many couriers. Certainly. That
enhances the flexibility of the system and allow you to routinely send
messages back and forth at J-6; and such a system is propably too
expensive for anybody except for the Navy, the Scouts, the Bureaucracy,
the Archdukes and the 14 Megacorporations. But a cut-rate system, one
that only allows you to recieve advanced warning of truly portentous
events, is within the budget of any cut-rate government and sector-wide
corporation.)

>To many worlds, visits of any ship, let alone a jump-6 ones, are
>infrequent.  With jump torps a world can keep torp sitting around
>to send off if they need.  It hardly pays to keep a jump-6 ship
>and a crew just sitting around.

But that\'s just what they have to have in order to send a J6 torpedo. You
can\'t send a torpedo without a jump engine and a computer.

>Fine if a jump-torp costs as much as jump-6 courier and requires a crew as
>costly just keep around.  Regardless of the implausibility of this (which
has already been covered),

Not so implausible after all, as I\'ve just demonstrated.

>let me ask...  Do you charge the cost of a jump-6 courier ship to your PC\'s
>for every jump-torp they have?  Do you require them to maintain an whole
>new crew just to use one?

No, of course not. All it costs them is the price of the torp itself and the
storage space it takes up (which is _not_ insignificant to the average free
trader). And of course they can\'t use torps of a higher jump number than the
ship\'s engine.

>The restriction on jump-torps is based on a minimum size for a jump
>unit which is easy to accept and also fits with other aspects of the
>game (like why there aren\'t an ships under 100 tons).

But wich dosen\'t actually restrict jump torps at all. The true restriction
is that you need a comparable jump engine placed outside a gravity field
in order to send them off. (And a ship to fetch them unless you want to
pay (what is it, jump engines are 3 MCr per ton, arent they?) 21 MCr per
message. Even if we decide that the capacitors alone are only 10% of the
price of a jump engine (an assumption that I don\'t believe myself  -  I
think those zuchai are quite expensive) you\'re still talking 2+ million
credits for a torp. Oh, you\'d definitely want a ship around to fetch
them in.)

>No.  That wasn\'t my scenario.  There are a lot of scenario\'s.  You
>set up a torpedo for two jump-3\'s (or make one a bit bigger so it
>can do two jump-6\'s) and have in jump in and out of an unknown system.

Now, that isn\'t possible under the rules unless you include the necessary
fuel for the second jump _and_ the engine in the design. Even then you
have to define that it is possible to calculate a second jump a week
ahead. It may be, but that is not established anywhere. But if you can,
you can do the same with an unmanned ship.

>Or you send in a torp that broadcasts sensor information and you jump
>in near the system and monitor broadcasts as you come in through normal
>space.  Or you have spy ship and it uses jump torps to send back
>periodic reports without having to leave the system.  You can keep
>coming with such secenarios.

I already have, but I was running a whole planet in a TCS campaign so I
used multiple scout ships for the spy system. Believe me, when you have the
ressources of a world you don\'t strain at using a few score scouts to
set up spy posts.

>Looking at it more fundamentally, Having to risks ships to jump into
>a unknown system is one of the basic dilema\'s in Traveller, as is the
>inability to send reports back without lessening your strength or
>abandoning the position.

You don\'t risk ships by sending them into a strange system if you\'re
intelligent about it. And you don\'t lessen any force that includes
10,000-100,000 T ships by detatching couriers. Compared to the cost of
the big starships, the cost of a couple of hundred couriers is
insignificant.

>Mon, 5 Feb 1996, Hans Rancke-Madsen <rancke@diku.dk>
>>David P. Summers have been arguing about the un-canonicality of jump
>>torpedoes for a while now.
>
>Um, no.  I\'ve been arguing they mess up the background.

OK. My mistake.

>[actually proposal on how to get around size restrictions and make
>a jump torpedo deleted.]
>You might be able to find a loophole in the rules to make a jump torp.

That wasn\'t a loophole. That\'s the logical concatenation of a couple of
well-established facts and rules.

>This isn\'t the point.  Since they mess up the background,

Well, first of all, you haven\'t convinced me that they do mess up the
background. A J-torp network won\'t be nearly as cheap as you think, and
it would have several downsides.

>you either don\'t try and interpret the ruless to make them possible,
>rewrite the background, or play with fundamental inconsistencies in
>your setting.

But now you\'re the one who is trying to impose arbitrary restrictions on
the setting. I\'ve just demonstrated that a jump torpedo is possible under
the rules. What are you going to do when one of your players works out a
proper description, walk into Bilstein Yards and plunk down the money to
have a prototype built and then try to flog it to the Navy? Are you going
to have the Navy procurement officer draw himself up haughtily and say:
"Sah! _Gentlemen_ daun\'t use jump tahpedoes! Begaune!" ?

I\'d much rather try to convince my players that a J-torp network isn\'t in
use in the Imperium because it\'s inferior to couriers (Or even that a smart
X-boat manufacturer had "convinced" the Imperium of that). At least I\'d have
a shot at making my players believe me. Saying: "You can\'t, because I say
so!" has a tendency to irk them.

>Already covered by others.  Basically, there is no reason they should be so
>expensive and to not have any affect at all they have to cost more than a
>jump-6 ship and it\'s crew, which makes them mostly pointless (ie you can\'t
>have it both ways, if they are cheap enough to be useful they will be used
>and affect the background).

We already know that the reason the X-Boat network isn\'t J-6 is a political
decision, so that\'s why they don\'t use J-6 torpedoes. The people who can
afford a J-torp network can also afford a fleet of J-6 cruisers, and there
are advantages to the cruisers that the torps lack. Thus the cruisers only
have to be in the neighbourhood of the J-torp network, pricewise. And, of
course, there are one situation where a jump torp is still useful, even if
a manned courier is more versatile: When you have storage space for a torp,
but not for a courier. For _emergency_ messages. In fact, just the situation
that is described in _Leviathan_.




