    'id' => ' <"29485 Wed Feb  7 13:31:16 1996"@bnr.ca>',
    'body' => 'Hello all,

Trying to implement several solar system generators
made me wish there were a system that was relatively
exceptionless -- that is, there being few or no branches
to take in the process.  Such a system would be more
elegant and straighforward for implementation on a
computer.

Last weekend, I set up a loose framework for such a
system.  The idea behind it is here:

1) generate the number of orbits and
           the object in each orbit.  use a
           statistical process like 2d6 or 3d6...

2) calculate some value (based on the
      combined masses, for example) of the
           orbitals.

        3) use this value as an index into a table
           to determine the star type and class,
   as well as orbit and habitable-zone
           info for that star.

4) determine the orbits of each orbital,
   using its orbit number, neighboring
   masses, and any orbit multipliers
   based on star type.

The result: not bad.  It was very very easy to write
a 4k script to churn out 1000\'s of them, and the systems
seem to be reasonable.  I sacrificed some granularity
in my program (stars have no magnitude, just a class),
but that\'s not inherent in the algorithm.

Any suggestions or something I hadn\'t thought of?

Rob
