    'year' => 1996,
    'from' => 'David P. Summers',
    'body' => '[Note: just so we don\'t forget, this discussion only focuses on
some of the problems of jump torps).
[OK, looking back I spent way too much time on this message,
further comments will have to be much more brief.]
Wed, 7 Feb 1996, Hans Rancke-Madsen <rancke@diku.dk>
>David, even though jump torpedoes are perfectly possible under CT,

This is debatable, I won\'t repeat the arguements that have been gone
over by others.

>you\'d
>still need ships (or space stations) to fire them off. The torps have to be
>sent off from somewhere away from a gravity field.  The torpedo capacitors
>have to be energized by a jump engine and programmed by a sufficiently
>large computer.  [Rest of the comments on tending jump-torps delelted.]

This is all equally true of X-boats.  However, you certainly aren\'t
going to need a ship the size of an X-boat tender to handle
a jumptorp.  Regarding the issue of secrecy.  Even if small planetary
craft (even with the torp) were just a fraction of the cost of
a jump-6 courier, tight beam communications would be sufficient.

>If you\'re near enough to recieve the data in less than a week then you\'re
>near enough to collect it yourself. Besides, scout ships are _not_ at risk
>when jumping into a strange system. Star systems are big places.
[Rest deleted]

OK, you are somewhat contridictory here.  You point out that you
need to be close enough to collect data but then claim you can
not be close to be safe from attack.  The fact is that a j-torp
could be sent right in 10 diameters from the main world, something
that could be too risky to do with a ship.  It can then broadcast
info which can be picked up by ships that have jumped to a point
outside of sensor range (and are relatively safe).

>But with couriers you don\'t need a network to outrace the X-boat net. You
>only need ONE J-6 courier.  Granted that it will loose a day refuelling at
>each intermediary system, but it will still outrace the X-boats. Given
>pre-placed fuel dumps the loss can be cut to hours. And expensive as they
>are, there are thousands of worlds with the budget to keep one courier
>stationed permanently at Capital (I don\'t think many would, but they could.
>Certainly there are not a single sector-wide organisation that couldn\'t
>afford it. Heck, there must be universities in the Spinward Marches that
>could afford it). Compare that to the cost of keeping a ship on standby for
>every 6 parsecs the message must travel, and the J-torp network dosen\'t
>seem nearly as attractive.

Firstly, as an aside, which is mostly irrelavent because it doesn\'t apply
to the jump networks the major factions did indeed maintain (because they
did, in fact, need them, read the Rebellion Sourcebook) but applies to
people like (taking your example) a university that wants fast
communications to one point.  For the cost of both the jump-6 ship and the
maintenance of a hole string a fuel dumps, you could probably have one guy
just sitting there with a communications setup (and call also be used for
general electronic espionage) who recieves the message and turns on the
next torp (and send messages faster and still save money).  This is
especially true of message over short distances because if you want to send
messages over only one or two jumps (like from one university to the other)
this is even more true since the large cost of the jump 6 ships dwarfs
everything else.  (As you think about jump-torps, you keep coming up with
more and more ways in which people would want to use them, which is exactly
why they cause so much trouble with the background.)

Secondly (and more importantly), if you want to spread information widely
and at the fastest possible speed (like the major factions needed to), you
need a network.  In travelling across the Imperium the continual loss for
refueling and
lifesupport replenishment (which you negelect), would meant that you message
would arrive weeks later than you oppositions.  Furthermore, having one
jump-6 ship will be useless if the message needs to go to more than one
place, or doesn\'t originate where you expect (you may need to send an
urgent message to the capitol).  For all these reasons, the major factions
in the Imperium did indeed find it necessary to maintain a whole network of
couriers, and it is this network that jump-torps would have rendered
obsolete.


>(And, yes, I know that Imperrialines have many couriers. Certainly. That
>enhances the flexibility of the system and allow you to routinely send
>messages back and forth at J-6; and such a system is propably too
>expensive for anybody except for the Navy, the Scouts, the Bureaucracy,
>the Archdukes and the 14 Megacorporations.

This is exactly the point.  It is that hughly expensive system of couriers
that allowed some factions to get critical info first.  While a system
of torps would be expensive, the fact that would only be a fraction of
the cost of couriers would make available more widely.  Not to everone,
but to a lot more people than were actually able to have them in the
Rebellion sourcebook.

>>To many worlds, visits of any ship, let alone a jump-6 ones, are
>>infrequent.  With jump torps a world can keep torp sitting around
>>to send off if they need.  It hardly pays to keep a jump-6 ship
>>and a crew just sitting around.

>But that\'s just what they have to have in order to send a J6 torpedo. You
>can\'t send a torpedo without a jump engine and a computer.

Um, no.  The jump torps that people talk about come with a jumpdrive
and small computer (this is why there are those discussion of how
small you can make a jump engine).  According to the rules, you
can\'t send anything that doesn\'t have it\'s own jump field generator.

>No, of course not. All it costs them is the price of the torp itself and the
>storage space it takes up (which is _not_ insignificant to the average free
>trader). And of course they can\'t use torps of a higher jump number than the
>ship\'s engine.

If you do it this way things get worse because now one jump-6 ship,
which could only take a message to one spot, can now send messages
simulataneously to every world withing jump-6.

>I already have, but I was running a whole planet in a TCS campaign so I
>used multiple scout ships for the spy system. Believe me, when you have the
>ressources of a world you don\'t strain at using a few score scouts to
>set up spy posts.

Not realistictic.  A real organization has limited resources and wasting
money one place takes money away from everywhere else.

>You don\'t risk ships by sending them into a strange system if you\'re
>intelligent about it. And you don\'t lessen any force that includes
>10,000-100,000 T ships by detatching couriers. Compared to the cost of
>the big starships, the cost of a couple of hundred couriers is
>insignificant.

OK, I had real trouble understanding the point of that sentence, but
it appears to ingore the main dilemma.  If you keep your force together
to enter every strange system; a) you risk loosing the whole war in one
blunder, b) you can\'t respond to enemy activity else where (because you
need to keep that force as big as possible to deal with what you find
when you jump in).  If you send in scouts you suffer a stead attrition
of men and materials.

>That wasn\'t a loophole. That\'s the logical concatenation of a couple of
>well-established facts and rules.

It was a debatable concatentation.  You were using the rules to address
issues that they clearly weren\'t intended to cover and blithly assuming
there would be no problems.  It\'s not an unreasonable _possiblity_
but it is just that, only a _possibilty_.

>I\'d much rather try to convince my players that a J-torp network isn\'t in
>use in the Imperium because it\'s inferior to couriers (Or even that a smart
>X-boat manufacturer had "convinced" the Imperium of that). At least I\'d have
>a shot at making my players believe me. Saying: "You can\'t, because I say
>so!" has a tendency to irk them.

This is a matter of viewpoint I guess.  I find the attempt to have
jump-torps so useful in some cases but have no affect on
the background strained (for reasons scattered over many posts).
The idea that every ship needs a jumpdrive is, in fact, part of
the rules and, since we don\'t have a theory of how jump drives
work to contradict it, the idea that there would be a minumum
size to a jump drive is very reasonable.

Deciding that one introduce new technologies with out changing the
general setup, only to encounter major problems as the unforseeable
consequences of those technologies play themselves out is nothing
new.  It teaches us that new technologies get used and make a
difference.

>We already know that the reason the X-Boat network isn\'t J-6 is a political
>decision, so that\'s why they don\'t use J-6 torpedoes.  The people who can
>afford a J-torp network can also afford a fleet of J-6 cruisers

Again, this can\'t be true.  If a jump torps costs as much as a j-6
cruiser to build and maintain there would be no point to them.
The fact that people are using jump-torps because they are
so much easier than sending a whole ship means that a network
of torps will, in fact, be that much easier to maintain that
a network of ships.

>When you have storage space for a torp,
>but not for a courier. For _emergency_ messages.

In fact you have pointed up yet another problem with jump torps.
They make emergency messages possible.  For example, a spy ship
can now send the info collected so far and then go into the
risk venture.  Before they had to way the risk of what they
might be able to collect against the fact that they might
not get anything back if they don\'t leave right then.  (For
me, facing such dilema\'s is a major part of gaming and to
just eliminate it by writing "jump-torp" on a sheet diminishes
the game).

