    'day' => '08',
    'topic' => 'Trade and Commerce',
    'body' => 'Recently, I was trying to get a feel for the sort of volume of trade and
shipping which goes on in a place like the Marches. You get a vague feel of
\'Oh, such-a-number of Free-traders berthed at the port.\' and at places like
Rhylanor, a feeling of large landing fields, with numerous small freighters,
and an *unspecified* number of large merchantmen.

What I was after was an indication of the amount of shipping, hence the
amount of ships required, and also perhaps a feel for the flow of the
shipping. Kind of, bulk ore carriers go from here to there, and Machine
Parts go from this place to that place. In order to do this, I went back to
the economics of the situation with Adventure 5 (TCS), and Book 2 of Striker
for the formula for GDP (Gross Domestic Product). Without angering an
economists who might play Traveller, I wanted to get a justification for
        a) the amount of trade or spec cargoes available,
        b) the number of ships moving those cargoes,
        c) the direction the cargoes were headed.

I have created a spreadsheet for the adjusted GDP\'s of all the worlds in the
Marches, adjusted for their Tech Level, and for their Starport type. (a TL12
world with a Starport C has a credit worth roughly half that of a TL15 world
with Starport A). The TL15 Starport A credit is *The Imperial Credit*, and
can be roughly equated to the emotional value placed on the US Dollar diring
the middle to latter part of this century. It was accepted at face value,
even where it was not necessarily supposed to be accepted.

This spreadsheet has caused some surprises with the GDP of some planets, but
to determine trade, what I am really after is a feel for the percentage of
GDP which is exported/imported. For example, Australia exports approx. 12%
of GDP, and imports 14% (depending on the year in question.) In the same
year, the US exported 11% and imported 15% of GDP, and Uruguay (to take
datum points from all parts of the spectrum) exported 14%, and imported 20%!

Does anyone have any ideas for calculating the percentage of GDP which
becomes foreign trade? I don\'t care how complex they are (but hopefully they
can be expressed in Excel 5.0/7.0 and calculated in real time on a 486!) I
was hoping to consider the tech level, maybe law level, and starport type as
determinants in the final figure, although others may come to light.

Even at this stage, assuming 5% of GDP is sent off world, and (through MT
Ref\'s guide) the value of a ton of shipping is Cr4000, that is still an
awesome tonnage being moved. The most surprising example is Entrope
(0720/SM). While Rhylanor moves Cr8 Trillion as 5% of its Cr167 Trillion
GDP, this 40 *million* tons **PER WEEK**. Entrope has a GDP of Cr672
Trillion MEASURED IN IMPERIAL CREDITS. This represents 161 Million tons of
shipping per week. If you look at the map, *where does it GO*?? Mind you,
that would explain why the Sword Worlders want the Entropic worlds so badly.
Other High Ratings include Porozlo, Trin (before the TNE disaster), Mora,
Riverland, Jewell. These are not all the systems above 10 million tons per week.

With these sort of numbers, I want to really nail down a foreign trade
calculation. It does state a very good case for Bulk Carriers though. 1/2
million ton J3 or J4 freighters with set runs. Free traders pick up five
categories of cargo in this case.
        1) Overflow. Not enough to warrant an extra bulk freighter;
        2) Speculative or one-off trade, not locked into a shipping contract;
        3) Contract arguments, the old "I\'d rather send it by Nocturnal
Airlines!", so you get picked instead;
        4) Short runs, or runs to very low-GDP worlds (infrequent runs maybe);
        5) Niche markets.

This means that although the amount of trade assumed to be happening has
skyrocketed from my original impressions, and some places will have a bulk
freighter leaving every few hours, the trade tables will probably not have
to be revised. Also tradewars become rarer (Tukera is NOT going to be
interested in the average 200-ton trader or three), but much more intense
(the value of a single run has a lot of zeroes after it!) Ship encounters
will also be perhaps skewed in favour of (*Much*) larger ships in some systems.

If anyone is interested in the spreadsheet, let me know, and I will send a
copy of either the output, or the .XLS file, or if someone wishes to place
it on their web page or FTP site, I am happy to oblige, and inform the list.
The file is approx. 210Kb

I will publish more analysis, as I think of it. For example, looking at the
map, most of the high value worlds are best served by J3-J4 ships for urgent
freight.

Enjoy
A P Madden
