    'index' => 'ac579',
    'body' => 'Regarding Jump-torps and other high tech stuff which changes the nature of the
established Traveller "universe" or background...

One of the biggest dangers in any role playing game is that of upsetting game
balance. I\'m sure that the issue of long communication routes making the feudal
aspect of the imperium necessary has already been discussed, but it illustrates
a very important point. If you add new technology like this it really does
radically alter the nature of universe in which you play ( aha - play - we
mustn\'t forget WHY we are involved with Traveller - for myself, I like to PLAY
or Ref. the game ). Consider the rise of the automobile and highway over the
horse, and the radical changes that occurred because of that. It\'s not
neccessarily bad, but like building the atom bomb, you have to ask "should we ?"
rather than just "can we ?".

In fact, a better question than "How would it work ?" would be "How will it
affect my players, and the campaign they\'re involved in ?". And if the answer
doesn\'t equal more FUN, then avoid it.

I have yet to meet a referee who hasn\'t regretted adding new technology to
his/her game. Invariably  the new wonder toy turns into a monster, and you have
to pray you can find a way to dispose of it fast befre it wrecks your campaign
completely ( either by making your players too powerful [so they get bored] or
by making their goals either too easy, or meaningless in the greater scheme of
things ).

My advice : think twice. Great new ideas don\'t necessarily make for great
gameplay.
