>>I already have, but I was running a whole planet in a TCS campaign so I
>>used multiple scout ships for the spy system. Believe me, when you have the
>>ressources of a world you don\'t strain at using a few score scouts to
>>set up spy posts.
>
>Not realistictic.  A real organization has limited resources and wasting
>money one place takes money away from everywhere else.

That depends on the scale involved. I did have limited ressources. I wanted
those couriers I bought to be available in a crisis. Until then I thought
they might as well do something.

A single high-population world could afford more than 100,000 jump-6 couriers
if they didn\'t spend their naval budget on anything else. Certainly someone
with the ressources of more than one world can afford a few hundred.

>If you keep your force together to enter every strange system; a) you risk
>loosing the whole war in one blunder, b) you can\'t respond to enemy
>activity else where (because you need to keep that force as big as
>possible to deal with what you find when you jump in).

If you only have two or three courier ships you have trouble, yes. But a
Traveller task force would have scores of couriers.

>If you send in scouts you suffer a stead attrition of men and materials.

Not unless you send them in close to the mainworld. A scout can collect
all the relevant material just as well from a few hundred thousand kms
away.

>It was a debatable concatentation.  You were using the rules to address
>issues that they clearly weren\'t intended to cover and blithly assuming
>there would be no problems.  It\'s not an unreasonable _possiblity_
>but it is just that, only a _possibilty_.

OK, so show me the snag.

>The idea that every ship needs a jumpdrive is, in fact, part of the rules
>and, since we don\'t have a theory of how jump drives work to contradict it,
>the idea that there would be a minumum size to a jump drive is very
>reasonable.

But my torps do have a jump drive and they do generate a 100 T jump field.

>>We already know that the reason the X-Boat network isn\'t J-6 is a political
>>decision, so that\'s why they don\'t use J-6 torpedoes.  The people who can
>>afford a J-torp network can also afford a fleet of J-6 cruisers
>
>Again, this can\'t be true.  If a jump torps costs as much as a j-6 cruiser
>to build and maintain there would be no point to them.

I didn\'t say that. I said that a J-torp _network_ required a lot of J-6
ships and thus cost on the same order as the couriers. Espescially when
you realize that to account for the Rebellion effects we have to account
for we only need a few hundred couriers all round.

>In fact you have pointed up yet another problem with jump torps. They make
>emergency messages possible.  For example, a spy ship can now send the info
>collected so far and then go into the risk venture. Before they had to weigh
>the risk of what they might be able to collect against the fact that they
>might not get anything back if they don\'t leave right then.

What do you mean "before"? I\'ve never run a game where that was true, nor
do I recall any official adventures where that was an issue.

>(For me, facing such dilema\'s is a major part of gaming

How often in your gaming have you faced that kind of dillema? (Just curious)

>and to just eliminate it by writing "jump-torp" on a sheet diminishes
>the game).

Well, that\'s a good reason for you to refrain from using jump torpedoes, but
I don\'t see that it has anything to do with wether jump torpedoes will
invalidate the Traveller background or not. Incidentally, there\'s plenty of
scope for making players leave behind jump torpedoes: They cost a hell of a
lot and they take up a non-trivial part of the average free trader\'s cargo
space. and if all else fails they can always break down.


