    'index' => 'ac595',
    'body' => 'Hi Wil, in response to your response:

>From: anwfh@acad2.alaska.edu (William F. Hostman)

>Rob, your assumption is based upon an idea that makeing it difficult to do
>prevents major impacts upon the published history; such a device, even as
>an emergency lifeboat system, would have had major effects during the 4th
>and fifth frontier wars, as losing sides could send out the message that
>contained their attacker\'s force strengths, location, and such, as well as
>known weaknesses. Such data becomes invaluable, especially if the fleet
>sends 1 per ship to neighboring systems, where they can activate merchant
>shipping and such ( even a few hours warning is a major change), as well as
>step up monitoring for up to a week.

I do assume that difficult-to-build, ergo expensive, j-torps will not
require major changes or rationalizations to the existing CT background.
I think this is a safe assumption. Even without j-torps, a losing side
could send out a ship with intelligence on enemy forces, etc. Such data
will be invaluable with or without j-torps. I see no reason to assume
that these capabilities have ever been non-existant in the CT universe.
I know of no canon that precludes such intelligence gathering
capabilities.

Maybe you can point to a specific battle in the 4th or 5th Frontier Wars
and show me how canon states (or implies) that no "timely" information
about a battle be allowed to leave the system.

I can think of one counter-example. The fleet at Regina had advanced
warning of the invading Zhodani fleet jumping in from
<<A-nearby-nonimperial-world-whose-name-I-cant-remember>> a few hours
(or was it a whole day) before the Zhos kicked off the 5th Frontier War.

And here\'s another: While the battle was raging over Regina, news got
out to nearby worlds. Rhylanor received news of the battle before it
received word of a victor. Clearly, whoever sent that message out MIGHT
have been from the losing side (as far as he knew at the time.)

>shipping and such ( even a few hours warning is a major change), as well as
>step up monitoring for up to a week.

Please explain what you mean by "up to a week."

-Rob

