    'topic' => 'Defense of _Leviathan_ Jump Torpedoes',
    'body' => '>>So does the ones I\'m defending. But the energy is created by the ship and
>>fed to the torp (since the torp dosen\'t have any fuel),
>
>Actually ,they do have fuel.

The ones in _Leviathan_, true. But that\'s about all we\'re told about them.
They consist of a jump drive, fuel, and a recording unit. There\'s not even
a computer to generate a jump solution. Nor are we told anything about
their size, price, or performance. To reconcile this with the rest of the
canonical material is easy. I can think of several explanations:

Small jump drives are based on the inferior jump drive used by [damn... I
forget... was it the Hivers?]. Everything we\'re told about jump drives
concerns the regular jump drive, so we can establish any sort of rules we
like for the other kind (Except that they burn out after 10-12 uses (Which
will explain why they are not used for the X-boat network too)). Including
being able to generate a smaller than 100 T jump field.

Or it could be a third type of drive. If there are two different ways to do
something, why not a third? Again, the proper parameters will prevent them
from marginalising the X-boat networks.

Or we could limit the application to jump-1 or jump-2. Perhaps its a new
invention, one not fully developed. That will explain why it wasn\'t used
for the X-boat network: It wasn\'t invented back then.



