    'topic' => 'CT!',
    'body' => 'Dear Tom,

I am not sure about 100 per cent CT fans, I am a CT/MT fan and in the
last weeks I have avoided reading any message that had to do with either
TNE comparisons or jump torps (personally I think they are inconsistent with
everything  else ergo they are not in my universe. I am sure I
cannot/don\'t want to  convince others to follow my view).

TNE is another game (and has his own mailing list). I have chosen not to buy
any TNE expansion and regret having bought the basic manual. My attitude
versus TNE has been that of sitting on the river banks waiting...It seems
I might have been lucky.

In any case I find the discussion on intelligence etc interesting and
I do not think it has really anything to do with the existence of jump
torps. AWACS planes or soviet spy ships are/were not especially small. It is
very likely that  building an efficient and cost effective starship
analogue will require more than 100 tons in any case.

The Imperial Navy  AWACS ship that I posted some time ago (see
http://astro.sns.it/~mstiavel/Traveller/equip/AWACS.txt) was indeed 800
tons. I have not played enough MT battles to be sure that that design is
really cost effective and I suspect that even minor changes in the way
sensor tasks are performed would have radical effects on the design of
similar starships.

The experiments with the Iridium Brigade that were discussed on xboat
this summer confirmed the role of intelligence also on the battlefield.

The importance of intelligence in its various forms has been recognized
since Sun Tzu\'s time and seems to me to be proportional to : 1- the
ability of your opponent to move rapidly and 2- the degree of lethality
of firepower (if you are throwing snow balls at each other you probably
do not need intelligence).

If one had available Boccob\'s Infinitely Ranged Ray of Instantaneous Utter
Destruction (sorry I have been playing some other game lately..) he would
probably spend most of its remaining money in intelligence: an enemy
seen is a dead enemy.

I suspect that the importance of the various forms of intelligence will
only increase in the future as weapons become more deadly.

            Cheers,
