    'topic' => ' Defense of Rancke Jump Torpedoes',
    'body' => '[This is getting very repatitive.  I\'ll try to be brief.  I have also
changed the order to move more repetative points to the back.]

Thu, 15 Feb 1996, Hans Rancke-Madsen <rancke@diku.dk>

>Except the _Starship Operator\'s Manual_. A jump drive consist of three things:
>A jump grid, capacitors and a special fusion reactor. The fusion reactor burns
>the fuel real fast and store it in the capacitors. The capacitors are capable
>of holding that energy for a short while before it has to be discharged. When
>they discharge the grid forms the jump field. Logically it should make no
>difference wether the capacitors was charged by an onboard fusion reactor or
>one exterior to the field. Once the energy is in the capacitors, the fusion
>reactor\'s part of the job is done.

Of course you\'be just revolutionized the whole concept of space travel in
Traveller. It is typical of attempts introduce a technology which will only
have a selected effect is that your attempts to patch it to work just one
way have their own side effects.  What you have proposed eliminates the
need for ships to carry their own jump fuel.  Instead you just have a
reactor at 100 diams in each system that launches ships into jump space.
Take any ship design and start cutting out the space you need for jump fuel
and you can see what a big difference this will make.  In fact, travel will
start working a lot more like Bablylon 5 (with installations that launch
smaller and civilian traffic but with military ships going their own way if
they need to).

>You assume wrong. If sending a jump torpedo to the 100 diameter limit to
>collect info and relaying it is a feasible tactic then sending an unmanned
>ship to do the same is equally feasible, just more expensive.

A) It also more risky.  If you have enemies sitting there your men are dead.
B) There is nothing "just" about more expensive.  We are talking about the
  resources you need to fight a war.  Saving them can make all the difference.
C) It also ties up manpower, also a limited comodity.

You seem to feel that the loss of a few jump torps compares to the loss
of jump 6 ships and their crews.  I find this absurd, but none of
this isn\'t stuff we haven\'t covered before so we will have to let
each reader make up their own mind.

>If the
>admiral wants it badly enough he can do it even without j-torps. Thus
>J-torps does not _add_ a new option.

[deletions]

>I didn\'t say J-torps wouldn\'t add new options.

Either they do or they don\'t.  As it turns out they do.  They let
you do things without tying up and risking human life and put
jump-6 message capability that fits in a ship.

>I said these new options
>wouldn\'t make the huge difference you claim.  If the knowledge to be derived
>from such tactics is big enough to change the result of a lot of battles then
>a scoutship  is a cheap price to pay.  If a scoutship is too expensive to
>loose on such a venture where a torpedo is not, then the benefit to be
>derived from the tactic is not enough to invalidate the Traveller background.

This is more than simplistic.  You seem to be claiming that if tatics
are important then ships must be cheap or that if ships are cheap then
tactics must be unimportant.  Why you think this must be is unclear.
The fact is that tatical information and ships are _both_ important.
This produces one of the fundamental delima\'s of traveller warfare
(one that separates tatical brilliance from mere competance), how
much of the second do you risk to get the first (and reduce the risk
to your fleet as a whole)?  Your approach just whips away this dilema
with a new gizmo, and not only changes the background, but also
(IMO) diminishes it.

>>That and more.  Just start thinking about all the kind of info a fleet
>>could use about a system it wants to enter.
>
>No, we\'re talking about information available from an exposed position (like
>the defenders 100 diameter limit) AND not available from a safer place in the
>system. What would that be?

And how do you know where the safe positions are if you don\'t know
anything about the system (which is your problem in the first place).

>>No. The design was j-4. The equipment used to make a j-4 network _was_ the
>>most effective available.  With torps you can have the same network, at j-4
>>for the same reasons the old one was, and save the Imperium big bucks.
>
>Was jump 4 the best available when the system was set up? Perhaps it was.

It wasn\'t.

>>Right.  And j-torps make such a network cheaper for a lot less than the
>>cost of the couriers (plus ships crew).
>
>Not if each node demands a jump-6 ship to maintain.

Aside from the open quesiton (among others) of how you can get a torp
to safely jump when it\'s being fed energy from another ship  (a ship
can\'t even be close to the torp, to just assume that an energy beam
right to it won\'t cause a misjump is questionable).  The fact is
that even then, you save money on each node that needs to send a
message to more than one destination (which is true of any message
propigating out from a central point).  If you were going to send
a message to 4 system you would need 4 jump-6 ships.  Now you just
need one.

>There is every need if you want a covert network. Ships in normal space can
>be traced much more easily than ships jumping. But I didn\'t say a full base.
>Just a ship.

First of all, that\'s not true, jumping produces a transient.  Second of
all, if you are going to refuel a ship and replenish life support, you
are going to need a base.  Or you need to keep a jump-6 ship sitting
permanently staffed and ready to go.  Either way we are talking expensive.

>>This is what the factions actually did.
>
>I\'d like some quotes about that, actually. It\'s not an unreasonable thing for
>them to do, but where does it say that they did?

Read the Rebellion Source books.  The factions with jump-6 couriers got
info to their people generally through the Imperium, not at a few
selected locations.

>>OK, first of all, you are getting into something I just hate. A background
>>that, instead of coming up with reasonable technologies and having a
>>background that fits, you have background where one or more technologies
>>"just happen to have" exactly the right cost and performance so they have
>>exactly the right effect.
>
>Funny, that\'s just the kind of thing I enjoy. Trying to reconcile two
>seemingly contradictory facts.

I guess to each their own.  I prefer a background where I\'m not always
running into things there are clearly there just to make something
work the way it wouldn\'t have in the first place.  Real things don\'t
work that way.

>Not quite. There\'s a jump-6 courier in _Fighting Ships_ that costs MCr 255.
>I won\'t mind betting that I could make a cheaper one, but I like using
>canonical background material. So MCr 255 it is.

You are right, your jump-6 torps are a lot cheaper than a ship.  So that
leave the point.  They save a lot of money.  That makes a different.
As just one, Anyone who needs to send multiple messages back from
an expition can now just send one ship rather than having to send
mulitple ships  so that some can be sent back with news.

>>So you "just happened to have them".  Then what about situation where
>>you don\'t?
>
>But a Traveller fleet will have them. They\'re useful and they don\'t cost much.

Again, a fundamental point.  Useful technologies (esp. cheap ones) get
widely used and have big impacts.  That\'s how technology works.  Look
at history.

>Ah, but that\'s just my point. You CAN\'T have a hundred system defense boats
>_that can turn the tide of a battle_. The cost of those couriers are less
>than ONE _light_ cruiser.

So now, instead of having to weight each message to see if it\'s worth
the loss of a ship you can just pop off anther torp.


