>>Aside from the fact you are treating all j-torps as being "lost" (which I
>>would say is poppycock)
>
>No, I\'m saying that any admiral has to assume (worst case scenario) that he
>won\'t be able to retrieve any torpedoes he sends off. That\'s why I said
>that _for this purpose_ one had to assume they were one-shot. The default
>assumption for manne couriers is that they\'ll propably turn up again.

A default assumption that is questionable.  You are in a middle of
a war with an enemy that is keen on detroying your ships and you
assume that if something has happened to the base you are sending
a message back to, your couriers are going to be safe?  And that,
if nothing is wrong with the base, they will be unable to retrieve
the torps?  I think your assumption more than a little biased.

>No, I\'m treating tham as having vast ressources. After all, if that sort of
>information is so amazingly valuable, then it can hardly be called waste to
>provide the means to disseminate it. The question then becomes: Can we
>afford it?

One of the points that people keep missing is that, the inablity to
easily communicate IS ONE OF THE FUNDAMENTAL UNDERPINNINGS OF THE
TRAVELLER UNIVERSE (it\'s in caps because I feel like I need to
stand on the nearest builing and shout it).  The fact is that
no organization has all the comunications it wants.  Not even
the Imperium (this is why it is forced to use a feudal type
of goverment rather than more direct control).  By making
communications easier you are allow more people to get more
info (both civilian and military) and going to allow more
resources to be freed up for other things.

Again, vast resources and VAST NEEDS FOR RESOURCES.  Yes info
is important and they spend resources to get it.  It is also true
that to make that info easier and free up resourses for other
purposes it a big deal.

>A fleet courier costs MCr 255.55 has a crew of 5 men. The Imperium thinks
>in terms of fighting ships that cost from 70 times more and has nearly
>50 times larger crew (and that\'s for a light cruiser; a _Tigress_ costs
>more than 1400 times as much and has a crew more than 800 times larger.

Right, and jump torps are even cheaper.  Thus, for each 50-70
messages a fleet sends it can have a _whole new ship of the line_.
I call that a big difference.

>>If you think the Imperium is going to have ships and men just sitting
>>around, or loose them sending them into uncertain situations, when they
>>don\'t have to just because they are "big" then you are woefully mistaken.
>
>They wouldn\'t be sitting around and they wouldn\'t be any appreciable loss
>due to sending them into uncertain situations.

If you have ships designed just to be couriers, they have to be
their waiting if you want them when you need to send a message
(like you can with a torp).  And not having to send men into
uncertain situations is one of the big changes jump-torps bring.

>You mean, such information isn\'t all that important anyway?

This is the last time I\'ll say this.  _Both_ ships and info are
important.  Read my earlier message.


