    'index' => 'ac646',
    'body' => 'David P. Summers writes:
>Thu, 15 Feb 1996, Hans Rancke-Madsen <rancke@diku.dk>
>
>Of course you\'be just revolutionized the whole concept of space travel in
>Traveller.

Yep, and don\'t think I don\'t know it. Only it isn\'t "just". I got that idea
several years ago and used it in a TCS campaign run by Steve Higginbotham.
I called them \'jump projectors\'.

>It is typical of attempts introduce a technology which will only have a
>selected effect is that your attempts to patch it to work just one way
>have their own side effects.

Except it isn\'t a new technology I\'m introducing. It\'s the one described in
Da Official Rules. Which only goes to show another glaring discrepancy
between the _official_ Traveller universe and the _official_ Traveller
rules. Now that discrepancy is a very good reason, IMO, to introduce some
arbitrary restriction of the technology that disallows this application.
If you could suggest a plausible one I\'d applaud you. I\'ve been trying to
come up with one that would do it, but failed miserably. I can\'t think of
anything that would eliminate this application and stll retain the drop
tanks (and I\'d like to retain the drop tanks; they\'re neat, don\'t you think?)

>What you have proposed eliminates the need for ships to carry their own
>jump fuel.

So does drop tanks, btw. It\'s always seemed strange to me that drop tanks
weren\'t used more, commercially.

>Instead you just have a reactor at 100 diams in each system that launches
>ships into jump space.

Quite right. If anyone ever got that idea it\'ll revolutionize Charted Space.

>Take any ship design and start cutting out the space you need for jump fuel
>and you can see what a big difference this will make.

The same applies for a rational use of drop tanks. No, the big difference
comes if you assume that you can use the same drive reactor more than once per
week, which seems reasonable. I talked Steve into letting me use mine once per
day. This was an arbitrary restriction imposed in order to prevent the idea
from completely overwhelming the campaign. I didn\'t mind, though. Of course,
if you restrict the use of the drive to once per week, you eliminate most of
the problems. A little inelegant, not to mention arbitrary, though, IMO.

>>You assume wrong. If sending a jump torpedo to the 100 diameter limit to
>>collect info and relaying it is a feasible tactic then sending an unmanned
>>ship to do the same is equally feasible, just more expensive.
>
>A) It also more risky.

It can\'t be more risky than I assume. I assume that any device, no matter
what its size, that appear at a heavily defended planet\'s 100 diameter
limit and starts broadcasting is going to be toast quite fast. I don\'t even
assume that a 100 T ship will survive longer than a 5 T jump torpedo (I do
assume that they\'ll survive equally long). So the risk in both cases is 100%.

>If you have enemies sitting there your men are dead.

If you read a little more carefully you might have noticed that I wrote
\'unmanned\'.

>B) There is nothing "just" about more expensive. We are talking about the
>   resources you need to fight a war. Saving them can make all the
>   difference.

It will make _a_ difference, true, but _all_ the difference? That\'s just what
we\'re discussing. You started out by claiming that jump torpedoes would allow
this tactic, which, you further claimed, wasn\'t available at all without them.
That is, a qualitative difference. Not so. The tactic is available without
them, though at a higher price. That is, a quantitative difference. How big a
difference? Well, to reiterate, if the difference is big enough to change any
of the historical battles we\'ve been told about in the Traveller background
(which, incidentally, is a postulate you have shown absolutely no evidence to
support) then it surely is worth it to the admiral to sacrifice a small 100 T
ship. If, on the other hand, the advantage to be gained from such tactics is
not enough to warrant wasting a 100 T ship on, then it obviously can\'t be that
background-shattering.

> C) It also ties up manpower, also a limited comodity.

No it dosen\'t. I said an unmanned ship (Surely one can program a ship to
perform any task one could program a jump torpedo to do).

>>If the admiral wants it badly enough he can do it even without j-torps.
>>Thus J-torps does not _add_ a new option.
>>[...]
>>I didn\'t say J-torps wouldn\'t add new options.
>
> Either they do or they don\'t.

Quite right. I misstated. I should have said that j-torps add new options,
but that the one you cited as an example wasn\'t one of them.

>As it turns out they do.  They let you do things without tying up and
>risking human life

Agreed. But they don\'t add capabilities that will destroy the Traveller
background, which was what you claimed.

>and put jump-6 message capability that fits in a ship.

Remember the heading. We\'re talking about the Rancke Jump Torpedo here. The
RJT _does_ require a ship with a jump-X drive of its own to use J-X torpedoes.

>>I said these new options
>>wouldn\'t make the huge difference you claim.  If the knowledge to be derived
>>from such tactics is big enough to change the result of a lot of battles then
>>a scoutship  is a cheap price to pay.  If a scoutship is too expensive to
>>loose on such a venture where a torpedo is not, then the benefit to be
>>derived from the tactic is not enough to invalidate the Traveller background.
>
>This is more than simplistic.  You seem to be claiming that if tactics are
>important then ships must be cheap or that if ships are cheap then tactics
>must be unimportant.  Why you think this must be is unclear.

It\'s a matter of scale again. A Traveller fleet consists of ships worth
trillions of credits. If sacrificing one 30 MCr ship will increase this
fleet\'s chances of survival by as much as one thousandth of one percent,
then sacrificing the scout ship is _comparatively_ cheap. If sacrificing
it won\'t increase those chances by that much then making that tactic
cheaper can\'t have that background-shattering influence on the historical
battles that you claim.

>The fact is that tactical information and ships are _both_ important.

Yes, but in what proportions? You seem to equate one 30 MCr ship with a
whole 3+ TCr fleet.

>This produces one of the fundamental dilemmas of Traveller warfare (one
>that separates tatical brilliance from mere competance), how much of the
>second do you risk to get the first (and reduce the risk to your fleet as
>a whole)?

You persist in claiming that any ship that jumps into an enemy system is at
a risk that can be expressed in significant numbers. Not so. If you select
a nice quiet spot off the beaten routes, the odds against accidentally being
within reach of an enemy are literally astronomical.

>>>That and more.  Just start thinking about all the kind of info a fleet
>>>could use about a system it wants to enter.
>>
>>No, we\'re talking about information available from an exposed position (like
>>the defenders 100 diameter limit) AND not available from a safer place in the
>>system. What would that be?
>
>And how do you know where the safe positions are if you don\'t know anything
>about the system (which is your problem in the first place).

Easy. You just select a likely spot somewhere. No enemy can cover a whole
solar system. Again you display a complete lack of any grasp of scale. It\'s
the difference in performance between photons and ships again. Try
calculating the danger space of an enemy ship. That would be a sphere with
a radius equal to the reach of the ship\'s weapons plus the distance the ship
can travel in 20 minutes (which is the time it takes for a scout ship in
danger to be ready to jump out of the system again). Now calculate how many
ships you need to cover just the inner reaches of a star system.

>>>Right.  And j-torps make such a network cheaper for a lot less than the
>>>cost of the couriers (plus ships crew).
>>
>>Not if each node demands a jump-6 ship to maintain.
>
>Aside from the open quesiton (among others) of how you can get a torp to
>safely jump when it\'s being fed energy from another ship (a ship can\'t
even be close to the torp, to just assume that an energy beam right to it
won\'t cause a misjump is questionable).

Ship capacitors can retain a charge for a number of 20 minute combat turns.
That means that you have time thrust the torpedo away from the ship between
charging the capacitors and the jump (That\'s why drop tanks don\'t interfere
with a ship\'s jump field either).

>The fact is that even then, you save money on each node that needs to
>send a message to more than one destination (which is true of any message
>propagating out from a central point).  If you were going to send a
>message to 4 system you would need 4 jump-6 ships.  Now you just need one.

Very true. _IF_ you were going to send a message to four systems in the first
place. But look at the X-Boat network. How many places do you find four
connections? Furthermore, look at any place with four links. Trace each
link. How many end links do you find? Right you are: four end links. As I
mentioned in my analysis, I decided to let the fork links and the end links
cancel out in order to simplify the calculations.

>>There is every need if you want a covert network. Ships in normal space can
>>be traced much more easily than ships jumping.

>First of all, that\'s not true, jumping produces a transient.

Careful, you\'ll get into another argument. Tracing ships in jump was a
capability added by _Starship Operator\'s Manual_ and is still hotly
contested by some. Not by me, though, I like it. I didn\'t say you
couldn\'t trace a jump ship, just that it was harder than to trace a
ship in N-space. By making double jumps you only need a 20 minute head
start to get lost. It takes a lot longer to get lost in N-space. Plus
you can have a guard ship ready at your intermediate jump point and
detect would-be followers (maybe even destroy them if you\'re lucky).

>...if you are going to refuel a ship and replenish life support, you
> are going to need a base.

That\'s another one of those unsupported postulates. Why can\'t a ship be
supplied by another ship?

>Or you need to keep a jump-6 ship sitting permanently staffed and ready
>to go.  Either way we are talking expensive.

That was my side of the argument. Having a jump-6 ship permanently stationed
to relay jump torpedoes is expensive and makes the courier network competitive.

>>>This is what the factions actually did.
>>
>>I\'d like some quotes about that, actually. It\'s not an unreasonable thing for
>>them to do, but where does it say that they did?
>
>Read the Rebellion Source books. The factions with jump-6 couriers got
>info to their people generally through the Imperium, not at a few
> selected locations.

I\'ve read them and I didn\'t find anything to that effect. That\'s why I ask
you to provide some quotes so that I can find them.

>I guess to each their own.  I prefer a background where I\'m not always
>running into things there are clearly there just to make something
>work the way it wouldn\'t have in the first place.  Real things don\'t
>work that way.

But you\'re perfectly ready to impose an arbitrary restriction in the way
jump drives work that makes drop tanks possible but eliminates jump
projectors. Why are your arbitrary restrictions better than my arbitrary
restrictions?

>>Not quite. There\'s a jump-6 courier in _Fighting Ships_ that costs MCr 255.
>>I won\'t mind betting that I could make a cheaper one, but I like using
>>canonical background material. So MCr 255 it is.
>
>You are right, your jump-6 torps are a lot cheaper than a ship.  So that
>leave the point.  They save a lot of money.  That makes a different.

These sweeping statements are pretty useless, not to mention wrong. They
make _a_ difference. I never claimed otherwise. I just claim that they
don\'t necessarily make a lot of difference. If, for example, there is a
small extra chance of the jump torpedo misjumping, then torpedoes are
_not_ cheaper than X-boats.

>As just one, Anyone who needs to send multiple messages back from an
>expedition can now just send one ship rather than having to send muliple
>ships  so that some can be sent back with news.

That\'s SO vague. An expedition from where and to where? Multiple messages
to where? How often does such a situation occur?

>>But a Traveller fleet will have them. They\'re useful and they don\'t cost
>>much.
>
>Again, a fundamental point. Useful technologies (esp. cheap ones) get
>widely used and have big impacts.  That\'s how technology works.  Look
>at history.

Let\'s see. Disposable nappies are useful and they are cheap. They are widely
used, no argument there. But I fail to see the big impact. Could you mention
a few battles that has been won or lost because of disposable nappies?

>So now, instead of having to weight each message to see if it\'s worth
>the loss of a ship you can just pop off anther torp.

1) You don\'t loose the ship, it\'ll be back again in two weeks, and 2) Now you
have to weigh each message to see if it\'s worth the loss of a torp.

Yes, you\'ll be sending more messages with torps than without. It will make
a difference, sure. But what you\'ve failed to demonstrate is why it should
make a BIG difference.

>>I\'m saying that any admiral has to assume (worst case scenario) that he
>>won\'t be able to retrieve any torpedoes he sends off. That\'s why I said
>>that _for this purpose_ one had to assume they were one-shot. The default
>>assumption for manne couriers is that they\'ll propably turn up again.
>
>A default assumption that is questionable.  You are in a middle of a war
>with an enemy that is keen on detroying your ships and you assume that if
>something has happened to the base you are sending a message back to, your
>couriers are going to be safe?

Yep. Unless the courier captain is a hopeless imbecile he won\'t jump in
anywhere near the base.

>And that, if nothing is wrong with the base, they will be unable to retrieve
>the torps?

No, they\'ll propably be able to retrieve them eventually, but in the meantime
the admiral may have jumped somewhere else. I didn\'t say he wouldn\'t get them
back some of the time. I said he couldn\'t assume that when he set out.

>>No, I\'m treating tham as having vast ressources. After all, if that sort of
>>information is so amazingly valuable, then it can hardly be called waste to
>>provide the means to disseminate it. The question then becomes: Can we
>>afford it?
>
>One of the points that people keep missing is that, the inablity to easily
>communicate IS ONE OF THE FUNDAMENTAL UNDERPINNINGS OF THE TRAVELLER
>UNIVERSE (it\'s in caps because I feel like I need to stand on the nearest
>builing and shout it).

No need to shout. I\'m perfectly aware of that. Communication is limited to
the speed of jump, so to speak. Jump torpedoes make no difference there.
They don\'t go any faster than a ship.

>The fact is that no organization has all the comunications it wants. Not even
>the Imperium (this is why it is forced to use a feudal type of goverment
>rather than more direct control).

None of them can send messages faster than 6 parsecs/week, if that\'s what
you mean (With or without jump torpedoes). _That\'s_ why the Imperium is
forced to use a feudal structure.

>By making communications easier you are allow more people to get more info
>(both civilian and military)

Marginally, perhaps, but it won\'t affect the time it take messages to get
between the core to the fringes.

>and going to allow more resources to be freed up for other things.

Yes, but not a significant amount of ressources. Read my analysis.

>>A fleet courier costs MCr 255.55 has a crew of 5 men. The Imperium thinks
>>in terms of fighting ships that cost from 70 times more and has nearly
>>50 times larger crew (and that\'s for a light cruiser;

>Right, and jump torps are even cheaper.  Thus, for each 50-70 messages a
>fleet sends it can have a _whole new ship of the line_.

Light cruisers aren\'t exactly first-line units, but never mind. However,
first of all that would depend entirely on the frequency of messages.
Secondly it assumes no loss of torpedoes. You only have to loose 12 to make
it more expensive than a courier. Fourthly, couriers are more versatile.
They can, for example, deliver messages to destinations two jumps away.
Fifthly, if, as you claim, jump torpedoes increase the number of messages
sent (and I agree with you that it propably does) then the saving will be
far less. If, for example, jump torpedoes encourages admirals to send off
two messages per day, where before they would only send one per week, we\'re
already using _more_ money than with the couriers.

>I call that a big difference.

You\'ve never actually played in a TCS campaign, have you? It\'s the question
of scale again. A 30,000 T LC may seem big to you, but to people who command
fleets that are 200 times bigger it dosen\'t make a lot of difference. It
makes _some_ difference, of course, but not a big one. Not one that _must_
change the Traveller background.


