    'body' => 'Sat, 17 Feb 1996, PPUGLIESE@pimacc.pima.edu
>>What I\'m saying is that it "doesn\'t *necessarily*" have a significant
>>impact.

>I would say that, for something as important and universal as
>communications, a significant difference in cost (ignoring man power)
>does necessarily have a significant implact.
>^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

>Yeah, well, the same thing was said about air-to-air missles when guns
>were removed from US fighters. Didn\'t pan out.

Are you kidding?  The introduction of air-to-air missles had a _huge_
impact.  It\'s true cannons were put back in, but only proves they
didn\'t completely loose their value.  Nobody is arguing that j-torps
will completely replace manned ships.  But, just like missles had a
bit impact on air combat, j-torps would have a big impact on
interstellar communications.

>And I can argue that until & unless there "really" is a chance to put the
>opposing theories to a real-life test, none of us is going to know for sure.
>And neither is more valid then the other.

By this reasoning, every background, no matter how poorly thought out,
