But, this if course, is just the kind of thing that many of us are
trying to avoid.

>Except it isn\'t a new technology I\'m introducing. It\'s the one described in
>Da Official Rules. Which only goes to show another glaring discrepancy
>between the _official_ Traveller universe and the _official_ Traveller
>rules.

I don\'t know.  My reading of official rules would be that if you
can screw up a jump by just being to close, then beaming power
to the ship is right out.

>Now that discrepancy is a very good reason, IMO, to introduce some
>arbitrary restriction of the technology that disallows this application.

I don\'t consider the idea that an energy beam will cause as much
disruption to a field as simply being to close to be "abitrary".
I would say it follows quite logically.

>I can\'t think of
>anything that would eliminate this application and stll retain the drop
>tanks (and I\'d like to retain the drop tanks; they\'re neat, don\'t you think?)

I haven\'t given drop tanks much thought.  I would say that you should
be required to bring them with you when you jump (after all, if you
drop them just before, then you will be within 100 diameters of them).
I would also think that you would need field generators on them (since
you need to cover the whole vessel).  At least that is how I would
say they would have to work to be consistent.  I don\'t know how
much of a background problem they would cause.

>So does drop tanks, btw. It\'s always seemed strange to me that drop tanks
>weren\'t used more, commercially.

Drop tanks may not have been well thought out.

>The same applies for a rational use of drop tanks. No, the big difference
>comes if you assume that you can use the same drive reactor more than once per
>week, which seems reasonable.

It would be hard to see why you couldn\'t use them once a minute.

>I talked Steve into letting me use mine once per
>day. This was an arbitrary restriction imposed in order to prevent the idea
>from completely overwhelming the campaign.

This is just the sort of problem with adding techologies to an existing
background that many of us wish to avoid.

>>>You assume wrong. If sending a jump torpedo to the 100 diameter limit to
>>>collect info and relaying it is a feasible tactic then sending an unmanned
>>>ship to do the same is equally feasible, just more expensive.
>>
>>A) It also more risky.
>
>It can\'t be more risky than I assume. I assume that any device, no matter
>what its size, that appear at a heavily defended planet\'s 100 diameter
>limit and starts broadcasting is going to be toast quite fast. I don\'t even
>assume that a 100 T ship will survive longer than a 5 T jump torpedo (I do
>assume that they\'ll survive equally long). So the risk in both cases is 100%.

The point is, what if you don\'t know if the planet is heavily defended
or completely open?
Do you send in one ship to see, knowing that one ship is easy to pick
off?  Do you send in the whole fleet knowing that it can handle a lot
of situations, but if you made a mistake you\'ve lost a _lot_?  This
is just the sort of dilema that jump-torps eliminate.

>>B) There is nothing "just" about more expensive. We are talking about the
>>   resources you need to fight a war. Saving them can make all the
>>   difference.
>
>It will make _a_ difference, true, but _all_ the difference?

Communications are hard enough to justify all that money spent
and the X-boat network and expensive networks of jump-6 couriers.
Clearly cheaper is going to make a difference.

To put it another way, clearly they make communications a lot
cheaper, so they will have a big impact on communications (over
and beyond the issue of loosing men and stuff).  Since difficult
communiciations is a fundamental premise of the background,
they will change the background.

>You started out by claiming that jump torpedoes would allow
>this tactic, which, you further claimed, wasn\'t available at all without them.

No, I said it would mean you didn\'t have to loose men and ships
to check out systems.

>>and put jump-6 message capability that fits in a ship.
>
>Remember the heading. We\'re talking about the Rancke Jump Torpedo here. The
>RJT _does_ require a ship with a jump-X drive of its own to use J-X torpedoes.

But you still have made it so a jump-x ship can carry a jump-x device
that can send a message.  Otherwise that ship had to carry along a whole
\'nother ship.

>It\'s a matter of scale again. A Traveller fleet consists of ships worth
>trillions of credits. If sacrificing one 30 MCr ship will increase this
>fleet\'s chances of survival by as much as one thousandth of one percent,
>then sacrificing the scout ship is _comparatively_ cheap. If sacrificing
>it won\'t increase those chances by that much then making that tactic
>cheaper can\'t have that background-shattering influence on the historical
>battles that you claim.

Um, the cheapest j-6 ship I\'ve seen is at least 30 times that cost.
But, in any case, nations with battleships don\'t consider patrol
boats expendable.  Why do you think our navy is putting so much
into unmanned spotting plains when jeeps are so much cheaper
than tanks.

>>The fact is that tactical information and ships are _both_ important.
>
>Yes, but in what proportions? You seem to equate one 30 MCr ship with a
>whole 3+ TCr fleet.

NO, I\'m saying that just because you are big enough to afford
big ships makes little ships irrelavent.  If you look at history
it takes a lot of logisitics, including a lot of little ships,
to support a big ship.

The fact is that your diffences in cost are not new in historical
navies.  And they just don\'t have the attitude that the little
ships are so expendible that you can just ignore loosing them
when cheaper ways that don\'t involve loss of men are available.

>You persist in claiming that any ship that jumps into an enemy system is at
>a risk that can be expressed in significant numbers.

No, I persists in claiming that jumping into an unknown system exposes
you to an unknown risk.  That\'s just the problem.

>Not so. If you select
>a nice quiet spot off the beaten routes, the odds against accidentally being
>within reach of an enemy are literally astronomical.

You can\'t select a spot if you don\'t know what\'s in the system.
As to being off the beaten routes.  If you are going to be
close enough to detect the enemy, you have to be close
enough to be detected by them.

>Easy. You just select a likely spot somewhere.


You can\'t select a spot when you don\'t know where the enemy is
(which is the problem in the first place).

>Again you display a complete lack of any grasp of scale.

No, the problem is you apply that scale to only to combat
and not to detection.  If you are close enough to be
confident of detecting the enemy, you are close enough
to be in danger from energy weapons.

>Ship capacitors can retain a charge for a number of 20 minute combat turns.
