>>several years ago and used it in a TCS campaign run by Steve Higginbotham.
>>I called them \'jump projectors\'.
>
>But, this if course, is just the kind of thing that many of us are trying
>to avoid.

But how? By closing your eyes and hoping it will go away? There are
essentially three way to deal with discrepancies in rules and background:

1) Explain them away by introducing new (or rather, previously
   unpublishd ;-) facts or rules.
2) By changing thing retroactively.
3) By ignoring them.

I prefer the first. You appear to go for the third. Well, that\'s your
prerogative. And I won\'t pretend I haven\'t done it myslef, when I couldn\'t
come up with a plausible new fact or a retcon that didn\'t spoil more than
it saved. But I can\'t understand an attitude that essentially claims that
these discrepancies don\'t exist at all.

>>Now that discrepancy is a very good reason, IMO, to introduce some
>>arbitrary restriction of the technology that disallows this application.
>
>I don\'t consider the idea that an energy beam will cause as much disruption
>to a field as simply being to close to be "abitrary". I would say it follows
>quite logically.

Besides being totally irrelevant, because I never said anything about beaming
the energy over, it cartainly dosen\'t follow at all. It is stated quite
clearly that what screws up a jump drive is the proximity of a gravity
field. Energy dosen\'t generate a gravity field. Beaming energy to a ship
may screw up it\'s jump field, but if it does it is a previously unknown
(arbitrarily added) effect different from the gravity field effect.

>>I can\'t think of anything that would eliminate this application and still
>>retain the drop tanks (and I\'d like to retain the drop tanks; they\'re neat,
>>don\'t you think?)
>
>I haven\'t given drop tanks much thought.

You evidently haven\'t read the rules about them either.

>I would say that you should be required to bring them with you when you jump

Tsk, tsk. Naughty. That would run counter to numerous references in the
background history.

>(after all, if you drop them just before, then you will be within 100
>diameters of them).

No, that\'s what I\'ve tried to point out to you in my last four messages. I
apologize for not making it clearer from the start, but I made the mistake
of assuming that you knew the rules and background that you are defending
so vehemently. Pay attention this time: JUMP CAPACITORS CAN RETAIN THEIR
CHARGE LONG ENOUGH FOR THE SHIP TO MOVE AWAY FROM THE DROP TANKS. Therefor
they can retain their charge long enough to move away from a jump torpedo
or (more likely) thrust the torpedo away from it. The same goes for jump
projectors, unfortunately.

>>So does drop tanks, btw. It\'s always seemed strange to me that drop tanks
>>weren\'t used more, commercially.
>
>Drop tanks may not have been well thought out.

Oh, I think the tanks themselves were a good idea. Unfortunately later
background authors didn\'t fully work out the ramifications inherent in
their existence. (Which goes to show that working out the technology
beforehand is no guarantee of getting the background right). But they
are part of the background none the less.

>>No, the big difference comes if you assume that you can use the same drive
>>reactor more than once per week, which seems reasonable.
>
>It would be hard to see why you couldn\'t use them once a minute.

Well, it takes 20 minute to charge jump capacitors and you could plausibly
add a delay in getting the next ship hooked up. and then you might claim
that the special kind of reactor needs to cool off between uses.

>>I talked Steve into letting me use mine once per day. This was an arbitrary
>>restriction imposed in order to prevent the idea from completely
>>overwhelming the campaign.
>
>This is just the sort of problem with adding techologies to an existing
>background that many of us wish to avoid.

But as I\'m getting quite tired of pointing out, I\'m not adding a technology
here, I\'m just applying an existing one creatively.

>The point is, what if you don\'t know if the planet is heavily defended
>or completely open?

Simple. You assume it is heavily defended.

>Do you send in one ship to see, knowing that one ship is easy to pick off?

But it won\'t be easy to pick off. It will have to be in range of an enemy
ship. (A whole other thing is that I propably won\'t bother to send in a ship.
It will cost me two weeks waiting until it returns and by the time my fleet
arrives the data it gave me would be two weeks out of date).

>Do you send in the whole fleet knowing that it can handle a lot of
>situations, but if you made a mistake you\'ve lost a _lot_?

If you jump into a system where things get too hot you only need to stand one
combat round. It takes 20 minutes to charge the drive and bug out (No sane
admiral will jump into a system without fuel enough in his tanks to get out
again).

>This is just the sort of dilema that jump-torps eliminate.

How? The torpedo can\'t return to you on its own, and if it could the data
would still be two weeks old.

>To put it another way, clearly they make communications a lot cheaper,

They do not make communication a lot cheaper. Cheaper, possibly, unless we
assume a loss rate (which I do), but not a lot.

>so they will have a big impact on communications (over and beyond the issue
>of loosing men and stuff).  Since difficult communiciations is a fundamental
>premise of the background, they will change the background.

The fundamental premise of the background is the length of time it takes to
get messages from one place to another. Jump torpedoes does not change that
one little bit.

>>You started out by claiming that jump torpedoes would allow this tactic,
>>which, you further claimed, wasn\'t available at all without them.
>
>No, I said it would mean you didn\'t have to loose men and ships
>to check out systems.

That\'s not how I remember it, but I\'ll take your word for it that that was
what you meant. Well, that\'s wrong too. A torpedo can\'t check out a system
since it can\'t return on it\'s own.

>Um, the cheapest j-6 ship I\'ve seen is at least 30 times that cost.

The cheapest you\'ve heard about (just a few days ago, in one of my postings)
is 8.5 times that cost. But we were talking about sending an unmanned ship
into the thick of an enemy fleet. Why use a Fleet Courier for that? A
Scout Ship would do just as well. Hence the 30 MCr price tag. (Though if
that tactic was so all-fired useful, the Navy would build dedicated !00
T propes which would be a lot cheaper).

>But, in any case, nations with battleships don\'t consider patrol boats
>expendable.

Ever heard about screening units? The screening units are put in greater
risk in order to improve the screened unit(s)\' chances of survival.
Noone _wants_ to loose any of the screen units, but they are considered
expendable _if it will save the central unit_. Besides, an unmanned Scout
is not the equivalent of a patrol boat, it is the equivalent of a missile
(And that goes even more for dedicated drones).

>The fact is that your diffences in cost are not new in historical navies.
>And they just don\'t have the attitude that the little ships are so
>expendible that you can just ignore loosing them when cheaper ways that
>don\'t involve loss of men are available.

But what you were claiming was that the cheaper way didn\'t exist then the
more expensive way was so expensive that it would not be used. Maybe so.
But only if the benefit to be derived from it is enough to justify the
expenditure of 3 MCr but not enough to justify 30 MCr. And if this is
the case, the benefit is not big enough to change any of the established
background.

>No, I persists in claiming that jumping into an unknown system exposes
>you to an unknown risk.  That\'s just the problem.

But it is not a problem if the risk is minuscule in any possible case.

>You can\'t select a spot if you don\'t know what\'s in the system.

You\'d hardly be ignorant of the number of planets and their plane of
rotation, now would you? So if you select a spot away from the mainworld
and the gas giants and off the plane of rotation, the odds against
appearing within effective range of an enemy starship are astronimical.

>If you are close enough to be confident of detecting the enemy, you are
>close enough to be in danger from energy weapons.

Do you know the difference between a communicator and an energy weapon? Its
the strength of the beam they send out. You can detect a ship from at lot
farther out than you can harm it.

>>Ship capacitors can retain a charge for a number of 20 minute combat turns.
>>That means that you have time thrust the torpedo away from the ship between
>>charging the capacitors and the jump (That\'s why drop tanks don\'t interfere
>>with a ship\'s jump field either).
>
>To be honest, I\'ve not seen this and would have to see it before I believed
>it.

OK, I\'ll dig out the relevant quotes.

>If it were true, I would say that it is a mistake that opens as big a can
>of worms as torps and needs to be eliminated rather than compounded upon.

Change the well-established canonical background? Dear, dear. Won\'t that
ruin your willing suspension of disbelief?

>First of all, we were talking about courier networks.  In news of the
>emperor\'s death this is exactly the sort of thing you would want to do.

But there is absolutely no canonical evidence that any of the factions had
any breath of communication (and good reasons to assume that they didn\'t).
All we know is that they were able to get key messages a long way along
one or two straight lines. Nothing is mentioned about dispersing the info.
Indeed, we are told that Lucan\'s version didn\'t make it to Ileish until the
X-boats brought it, and that it was effectively suppressed in many places
there. Dosen\'t sound like many of the other factions had links to Ileish,
now does it?

>Also, even with X-boats, you still gain (in addition to other problems),
>the ability to send messages more than once a week.

Only if you are willing to pay for it. And only if you assume that there
are no losses involved in using jump torpedoes (which I assume there are).

>I wasn\'t talking about tracing ships in jump (which would cause a lot of
>problems to the background). I was talking about the emmisions that you
>put out entering and leaving jump space (and which can be used to tell
>that a ship has jumped in/out nearby).

Yes, nearby. What is \'nearby\' in a star system? How far out can you detect
an arriving or departing jump drive? And what was the original point? I\'ve
lost track.


