    'day' => '21',
    'body' => 'Mr. Summers,

I was strongly tempted to reply to your sneaky little attack on
me in the public forum where it was made, but since I really am going to
be personal this time, and since I firmly believe that one ought to go to
e-mail in such cases, I decided to forego that pleasure. You have the gall
to accuse me of being ignorant of the rules and to not think thing through
when you yourself have displayed abysmal ignorance of your own. One example:

>I don\'t know where you got your 20 minutes capactitor rule, but it isn\'t
in the original books.

_High Guard_, Starship Combat, Pre-combat decision step, 3rd paragraph:
"_Jumping_: A ship [...] must expend energy points equal to two turns output
from a power plant whose number is equal to the jump being attempted (EP
required =0.01MJn). If it can do this in two turns, it jumps at the end of
two turns. If it can do this in one turn or less, it jumps at the end of
one turn..."

It should be obvious, so I suppose i\'d better spell it out for you, that
any ship with jump-2 or better engines will be able to execute at least
a jump-1 in just one turn.

>>You evidently haven\'t read the rules about them either.
>
> OK, we can end here.  I have read them.

You then get upset over a little dig at the lack of knowledge you\'ve
displayed earlier. The above sentense is no more than the litteral truth.
>From the evidence available to me it certainly didn\'t appear as if you
had read them, since your previous remarks display a marked lack of
understanding of them. Nevertheless, the dig was friendly meant, since
I tend to regard fellow gamers as kindred spirits until the opposite has
been proven. And friends can chaff each other without taking offense.
Well, you\'re obviously not a kindred spirit. My mistake. And my gain,
since I\'d rather not associate, even by remote, with anyone who is
capable of such arrant, topsy-turvy nonsens as:

>Clearly my standards of thinking about things are higher than yours

Your standards are different, that much is clear.

>(I must say, I find that attacking your opponents credibility is a
>common tatic in threads when someone no longer finds themselves
>able to come up with cogent responses.

That would mean something only if I had been finding myself unable to come
up with cogent responses. Another tactic, let me add, is to take offense
at some remark of your opponent and cut off further discussion when one
finds oneself unable to come up with anything but stubborn reiterations
of already-refuted arguments.

>As is the use increased use, which you also show, of attempts to use smart
>cute remarks.

Here I suppose I must plead guilty. In retrospect I can see that as you
repeatedly displayed a failure to understand my arguments (as opposed to
understanding them, but disagreeing with them) I did become gradually more
exasperated at having to explain something that should have been obvious to
anyone who had a thorough familiarity with the rules and didn\'t stubbornly
refuse to even consider that he might be wrong. So I guess I did slip in
more digs as time went by, though, as I said, as a friendly way of blowing
off steam, since I still thought you were honestly trying to have a fruitful
argument rather than merely wanting to win.

Some of your ideas may have merit, sir, but your way of conducting an
argument does not. Good day to you, sir.



      Hans Rancke
University of Copenhagen
