On Thu, 22 Feb 1996, Robert Flammang wrote:

> Hi Charles,
>
> Regarding your question on neutrino background: No neutrino
> background has ever been observed, but that may have more to do with our
> inefficiency at detecting these things than with astrophysical reality.
> Almost all neutrinos we\'ve seen to date have come from 1) Fission
> reactors, 2) Particle accellerators, and 3) The sun.

More appropriately, three should be the process whereby stars such as the
Sun generate energy.  A neutrino is essentially a "garbage" particle that
is a by product of the fusion reaction going on in stellar cores emitted
as two protons squish together to form atom deuterium (hydrogen with a
neutron), a positron, and the neutrino.  Hypothetically, a type I
supernova (or a high solar mass late-stage supergiant) would be an extremely
powerful source of neutrinos, simply because it churns through the fusion
process at a ridiculuous rate.

> I\'m not aware of any other large neutrino sources in the
> universe, but that doesn\'t mean much. Very little is known about these
> particles.
>
> -Rob (the jump torp guy) Flammang

