    'day' => '22',
    'date' => 'Thu, 22 Feb 96 22:48:15 PST',
    'body' => 'Charles Collin <charles@hebb.psych.mcgill.ca> writes:

>I recently came across an interesting little quote in High Guard
>regarding invading fleets.  Under the discussion of black globes it is
>stated:
>
>"Invisibility: Since a black globe field absorbs all energy, a ship with
>its field completely on is, at any range over a few kilometers,
>effectively invisible.  In battle this will have no effect...However, the
>advantages to a fleet which has not yet been detected are immense.
>Suppose, for instance, that a fleet were to jump into a system with its
>black globes on and its velocity set upon a predetermined course.  It
>could drift unseen past any defending fleet and drop its screens at a
>preplanned moment..."
>
>This implies a couple of interesting things:
>
>1. Fleets of ships jumping in can arrive in roughly the same time-space
>(close enough that they will be able to coordinate their actions despite
>not being able to communicate).

Which folks had (mostly) conceded, but it\'s nice to have more
confirmation.

>2. Ships can jump into a system with a specific desired vector.

This has pretty much *had* to be the case. There are only a few
possibilities:

1. The ship emerges from jump with the same vector it entered jump
   with. This would be consistent with physical laws in that it
   wouldn\'t violate conservation of momentum. But it\'ll play *hell*
   with things, because the velocity difference between star systems
   often runs high enough to significantly affect fuel consumption!

2. The ship emerges at rest with respect to the local star (or whatever
   gravity well popped it out). This has problems too. First, where did
   the momentum go? Second, it affects mobility too, though not as
   drasticly. Plus, what about the case when you have aimed to come out
   of jump well away from anything? What are you at rest with respect
   to *then*?

3. Your exit vector is part of the calculations for the jump. Since
   jump plays hell with physics, this wouldn\'t be much worse, and there
   *are* arguments that can be used to justify "rotating" vectors when
   going through higher dimensions. Explaining how the vector\'s *size*
   changes is harder, but I wouldn\'t bet that it can\'t be justified.
   :-)

#3 does the least damage to canon and background. And if you use it,
you can claim that vector control isn\'t anymore precise than
*positional* control. Which solves a lot of the problems.

>3. Ships can turn their black globes on in jump space!  This is weird.
>What happens?  Do you absorb energy from jump space?  Spoooky...

The section you quote doesn\'t say thaty they rurned on the globe in
jump. Any reason they can\'t turn it on *before* jump? For simplicity,
I\'d say that there\'s nothing *for* it to absorb.

>4. Ships with their black globes on 100% are less visible than normal.
>This contradicts statements in "Grand Survey" (and "Worldtamers.." ?)
>that these ships would absorb too much of the background radiation and
>appear as below-baseline readings on sensor readouts.  Here\'s the quote on
>that one:
>
>"A TL 15 ship may be equipped with a black globe which hides its
>radiation and neutrinos.  The disadvantage to this technique is that the
>black globe also blanks natural neutrino sources behind it, so a "hole"
>in the starfield appears on the sensor.  A skilled operator will notice
>this "below background" reading..."
>
>I have a couple of questions about this: 1) Is there a "background
>neutrino level" or would you have to occlude a star?  2) Would the BG\'s
>absorption of other radiation types make it visible?

Sure, the globe would block out whatever is behind it. But detecting
*that* is going to be very difficult at any sort of range. Figure out
how small an arc that globe subtends at various distances. An *absence*
of radiation is *very* difficult to detect because of the way sensors
of any sort work. You can detect something emitting photons or
neutrinos even if the "image" on your sensor is so small that it only
covers one detector "element" (think of it like a pixel in reverse).
That\'s possible because the element just has to receive enough energy
to trigger it. It doesn\'t have to *resolve* it.

But trying to detect a *lack* of energy requires that the "image" be
large enough that the blank has a 100% probability of completely
covering a detector element. Otherwise, you pick up the signal from the
adjoining non-blank areas.

>Here\'s another interesting thing, this time regarding the High Guard
>quote.  If ships can have a predetermined vector towards the mainworld upon
>jumping in, what\'s to keep someone from sending in a ship with a really
>high velocity (or several such), and completely obliterating the planet?

Easy. Doing so requires that you come out of jump at a *precise* point
in space, with a *precise* vector. Getting the required precision gets
*harder* as the velocity goes up, because you\'ve got less time to make
course corrections *and* you need more thrust to make the same *angle*
change in the vector.

That\'s why my super-mass-driver is best located *way* the hell out
there. So there\'s *time* for small thrusters to make course
corrections.


Leonard Erickson (aka Shadow)
 shadow@<--preferred
leonard@<--last resort
