    'topic' => ' Invading Fleets (XBd#543)',
    'body' => 'shadow@ (Leonard Erickson) wrote:
> Charles Collin <charles@hebb.psych.mcgill.ca> writes:
> >2. Ships can jump into a system with a specific desired vector.
>
> possibilities:
>
> 1. The ship emerges from jump with the same vector it entered jump
>    with. This would be consistent with physical laws in that it
>    wouldn\'t violate conservation of momentum. But it\'ll play *hell*
>    with things, because the velocity difference between star systems
>    often runs high enough to significantly affect fuel consumption!

This is also the answer that Marc Miller used to give at CT question and
answer sessions.  As a rough, ballpark estimate the velocity difference
between two nearby star systems should be somewhere above 10 km/sec and
below 100 km/sec for nearby destinations, and increasing as the size of the
jump increases. (are there any astronomers out there who can give me
better figures?).

Given that Classic Traveller uses constant-accelleration drives,
establishing the correct vector before jump involves several hours of
accelleration.  A quick-and-dirty game mechanic might be:

Time spent establishing vector = (1d6 per Jump Number) * 3

The result being in High Guard turns; it hours, it would be (1d6 per Jump)/2
(anywhere from half an hour to eighteen hours).  In many cases, this vector
set-up is subsumed within the voyage from the starport to the jump point;
presumably there would ordinarily be "lanes" for each possible destination
out from the world in directions that help set up a reasonable entry vector
for ships going to those systems.

> #3 does the least damage to canon and background. And if you use it,
> you can claim that vector control isn\'t anymore precise than
> *positional* control. Which solves a lot of the problems.

Actually, #1 is canon, and #3 makes a mess of the idea, put forth in High
Guard, that a fleet can jump in with Black Globes up, and then drift past
the enemy\'s outer defences.  If vectors were randomized (even slightly) by
jumping, this tactic would not work.


