I\'m pretty sure that CT explicitly states that #1 (the ship
retains its original vector) is true. I don\'t have my books here, so I
can\'t quote chapter and verse at you, tho. This conservation-of-linear-
momentum rule was written into both CT\'s jump and teleport rules, as I
recall.

< #3 does the least damage to canon and background. And if you use it,
< you can claim that vector control isn\'t anymore precise than
< *positional* control. Which solves a lot of the problems.

I disagree with you here. If you\'re using CT rules, fuel cost is
neglegible for matching vectors between stars. I believe relative
stellar velocities are on the order of 10 km/s. A free trader could then
match velocities in less than a half-hour for most star systems. The
same thing is true of relative planetary velocity vectors.

If you\'re not using CT rules, then, of course, nothing I\'ve said
will apply. I don\'t know the new rules very well at all.

