    'body' => ' Sat, 24 Feb 96, shadow@ (Leonard Erickson)
>>A volume filled with locations that are all so far outside of your
>>sensor range as to be useless for scouting out a system.

>Out of the ranges given in the books for *active* sensors. Not out of
>real world active and passive sensor ranges. Note that for example, it
>is possible for *amateur* radio operators to not only bounce signals
>off the moon, but to do so well enough to use it for communications!

First of all, in Classic Traveller, detection ranges are explicitally
desribed as being in the light second range.  Even in MegaTraveller,
where there are passibe sensors with "interplanetary" range the ship
comat system give range modifiers that mean you aren\'t going to
detect a ship in much past the light-second range (presumably the
range on the sensor is how far you can detect "something" regardless
of whether ships are detecible.)

Ragarding the moon, that is a totally differnt situation.  The moon
is a _lot_ larger than a ship, it isn\'t actively designed to not
be detected, and we already know where it is.  Right now we can\'t
detect ships at the ranges proposed.  Now we can argue about the
effect of technology on the ability to detect vs remaining hidden,
but the fact is that, in Traveller, detection ranges are in the
light second range.

[this was moved because it touches on the subject just mentioned.]
>>But this is all beside the point
>>because Traveller detection ranges are given and they
>>are in only the light-second range (at least in the
>>original books).

>And they are patently *wrong*.

The main point is that jump-torps violate the Traveller background.
Having to agrue that that background is wrong (which I don\'t agree with,
see above and below) hardly supports the proposition that they are
compatible with the exisiting background.

>With larger gear (well within the size a medium sized ship could carry)

Assuming a larger portion of the ship is allocated to sensors than
the rules give.

>it is possible to *image* Venus! Believe me, detecting a 100 ton or
>better ship at interplanetary ranges *is* possible via radar if you
>don\'t have an atmosphere in the way.

Maybe is you launched a huge array of multiple radio telescopes into
orbit (though a ship could never carry that).  The fact is that
we aren\'t able to image Venus from the Earth with any radar
equipement currently avialable.  In any case, how far you can
detect planets has little bearing on detecting ships.

>And passive sensors have ranges just as good. Radio transmissions, IR
>signature, both light reflected off the hull, and light emitted by
>rockets are all detectable at interplanetary ranges with gear a ship
>can carry.

Not according to the rules and not possible today either.

>Depends on what you are detecting. The IR signature of a manned ship
>*will* be detectable at several AU or else the crew will be dead.
>Detecting a 300K object against the 3K background is *easy*.  And if the
>ship has any kind of powerplant or equipment running, it *must* have
>some way of dumping the waste heat.

Not true.  You don\'t need to dump heat isotropically.  You just
need to know _one_ direction the enemy isn\'t in and you can
dump the heat that direction.

Also, with active cooling, you can select the wavelength of the
energy you emit so that it is in the radio/micro waver region
that the univers emits (regardless of the actual black body
temp of the ship).

Also, it\'s not a 3K background either.  There are a lot of stars and the
amount of energy, at 1 AU distance, that you detect from a starship is
less than the nearby stars in your part of the galaxy (we had this
discussion in the GURPS list and I did the cacl).  What you are
trying to do is pick out one point buried in a mess of other ones
(sort of like picking out one grain of sand in a beach).

Furthermore, if you are trying to scout out a planet, you are going
to have to be able to detect ships against the background of the
planet (either a terrestial planet, which is likely reflecting energy
and emitting in the 300K+ range or, even worse, a jovian planet
that is generating and emitting it\'s own energy).

>While the Palomar scope isn\'t suited for mounting in a "scout" vessel,
>something along the lines of the Multiple Mirror Telescope *is*.
>(half a dozen 1 meter mirrors, computer synchronized). Get that outside
>the atmosphere, and float it on a tether, to isolate it from vibrations
>on the ship, and you\'ll be able to *image* ships.

First of all, what you are talking about in terms of space is something
that is so much more than what Traveller gives for ships as to
seriously weaken them.  Besides, you aren\'t going to be able to
detect something the size of a Traveller ship with the telescope
you describe at 1 AU (except, _maybe_ with a year or two of
observation), let along "image it".

[A lot of discussion about what we can do now, that I really don\'t have
time for.  The fact is that; a) I feel the poster is just dead wrong
in what he knows about currently sensor technology (for example, you
can\'t make inflatable radio dishes).  b) even disregarding"a" he
ignores concealment technology, c) this all of this only touches
on one of the problems that jump torps have.]

[A few selected points...]
>As for advances in concealment, you are up against the hard limits set
>by physics. Especially with regards to IR.

No you aren\'t.  See above.

>#2 requires either a black globe, or knowing in advance what
>frequencies you want to absorb (it\'s done with quarter wave coatings).
[and]
>But the best black coating known only absorb about 90% of the light.

Good examplse of ignoring advances in concealment technologies, you are only
willing to consider ways to absorb energy that we have now.


>>This is not a new tatic.  It\'s been used before in the "real world"
>>and it has the same risks that other approaches do (standard NATO
>>policy was to sink all those Russian "trawlers" if war broke
>>out and the russians detain, and sometimes even shoot down,
>>civilian aircraft in the wrong place).  The chances
>>of being disabled and captured or the enemy deciding that it\'s
>>just a ploy and blowing you away (esp. if you are making a habit
>>of this sort of thing, which you will be if this is your major
>>approach to intellegence gathering).
>
>On the other hand, even the Russians let ships from other countries
>into their ports.

They don\'t let them wander in and leave when they want.  If you
show up you better stop and get properly identified.  And that
is during peacetime.

>For what it is worth, there\'s even a fair chance that a single ship
>jumping in, not making any threatening moves and then jumping out will
>be "left alone" much of the time.  Consider that while the Germans and
>Japanese did shoot at the planes sent in to check the weather over
>tasrget areas, they didn\'t waste a lot of shells on them and almost
>*never* sent up fighters. It wasn\'t worth the effort. It made more
>sense to save fuel and ammunition to use against attacks.

OK, so jumping into a system is "safe" because they are only
going to "attack you some"?  (and that is for a ship that
is not going near important areas, not a situation a spy
ship is going to be in).

>I used to know a guy who\'d been navigator on a B-29 and his plane had
>been making weather flights over Japan at the end of the war. One
>interesting item is that it was pretty much a "milk run". Until August
>6th, 1945. After that they got everthing but the kitchen sink thrown at
>them.

And, on the other hand, planes that spied on military targets were
in real danger.


