    'body' => 'jbogan@pipeline.com (John H Bogan) wrote:
> Out of around 100 stars, the fastest moved at a speed of 15
> (only one star), the next at around 9 (again, one star).
> About 70-80% had a speed less than 4.

OK, that sounds like I need to (approximately) halve my results, and remove
some of the variation by distance.  How about does what\'s below look to
you?  It should produce results that average around BL Speed 4 to 6 (for
Jump-5+ trips), with a minimum of 2 and a maximum of 9.  This is still a
little high, but puts the top end better under control.  Did your figures
include the orbital velocities of the origin and destination planets, by the
way?

> I think your numbers are a little high, but more importantly you\'re not
> taking the ship\'s thrust rating into account.

You\'re right; I was trying to convert from BL to CT on the fly; those
numbers would be for a 1G ship; divide the result by the ship\'s maneuver
rating to find the actual figures (ie: divide the time by 6 for a maneuver-6
Rampart RF-128, or by 2 for a Azhanti High Lightning class cruiser).

Here\'s a different formula to use:
    Brilliant Lances Speed = (2d6 + Jump Number) / 2
    Hours Spent = Brilliant Lances Speed / (2 * M-Drive Rating)
    High Guard Turns Spent = Brilliant Lances Speed * 3 / M-Drive Rating

If you\'re computing the duration in High Guard Turns, remember to retain
fraction until the final computiation, but round the humber of turns to the
nearest whole number (that is, round 1/2 or more up, and less than 1/2 rounds
down).

Furthermore, I forgot to note that a ship can perform the vector matching on
the way INbound from the jump point in the destination system, as well as
OUTbound to the jump point in the originating system.  In actual practice,
ships probably perform part of the vector correction in both legs of the
journey before and after jump, so that (under normal operations), there\'s
little additional time that has to be spent matching vectors.

The main time it\'s important is when you _have_ to establish a certain (or
unusual) vector on entry - like for the jump-with-the-black-globe cloaking
trick.

> In most situations, GM\'s can ignore  this extra (or reduced) time.

Exactly.

