    'body' => 'shadow@ (Leonard Erickson) wrote:
> Derek Wildstar [that\'s me!] <wildstar@qrc.com> writes:
> > Actually, #1 is canon, and #3 makes a mess of the idea, put forth in High
> > Guard, that a fleet can jump in with Black Globes up, and then drift past
> > the enemy\'s outer defences.
>
> Better re-read what I said. In #3 I said that the emergence *vector*
> can be "chosen" to much the same sort of accuracy as the emergence
> *time* or the emergence *location*. Thus the same sort of "shared
> calculations" that allow a fleet to emerge at much the same time and
> position will also allow them to emerge with much the same vector.
>
> So it doesn\'t make a mess of that.

Yes, it does.  Here\'s why:

Even though the entire fleet emerges all together, if their vector has been
randomized (even if it has been randomized the same way for every ship in
the fleet), the fleet will not go where planned.

The tactic mentioned in High Guard was that a fleet would jump together,
emerge from jumpspace with black globes up, and drift past the enemy\'s outer
defences, to "uncloak" and engage the target.

If the fleet\'s vector is unpredictable on exit from jumpspace (even just a
little bit), the fleet may de-cloak to find itself considerably off course,
and nowhere near the target!  Think about it - if the fleet were planning to
attack an enemy\'s naval depot, they could very well collide with it, instead
of be in position to attack it, or instead of drifting past the enemy\'s
defenses, they may drift right into the thick of them.

Randomizing the exit vector makes the entire tactic pointless - you can\'t
tell where you\'re going, and you can\'t see out (because the globe screen
blocks your sensors as effectively as it does the enemy\'s).

> And in MT, #3 is probably more workable than #1. I don\'t wanna think
> about TNE... :-)

It\'s not much of a problem, even for T:TNE ships and their
limited-accelleration drives.  Even a "worst-case" scenario (two planets in
opposition, for a vector difference of +60km/sec, and differing stellar
speeds on the order of +40km/sec) gives us about 100km/sec speed difference,
or not quite 6 G-Turns of thrust (an hour and a half).  This is around 20%
of the maneuver fuel that even the most limited T:TNE design carries.

And this range of values is what my (updated, thanks to better numbers from
some other members of the XBOAT list - thank you, John!) formula provides.
The new formula (posted recently to the list) is BL speed = (2d6 + Jump) / 2

