<detected particles due to Supernova 1987A ?

Very true, I had forgetten about that. Obviously, I\'m a little rusty too
(especially when it comes to astrophysics, I mostly work on cyclotrons
these days.) Fortunately, I covered myself with the word "Almost!" 8^)

Actually, what I was thinking of when I stuck the word "almost" in front
of "all neutrinos" was the beta decay of many radio-isotopes. Neutrinos
were originally "invented" by E. Fermi who tried to explain beta decay
while maintaining conservation of energy.

I\'m not sure whether a neutrino as a natural decay product has ever been
observed in the laboratory. But it occurs to me that many planets (well,
the Earth anyway) have gigatons of radioactive ores in them, and that
such a planet will outshine any starship\'s powerplant in the neutrino
spectrum.

What do you suppose the angular resolution of a neutrino detector is? ...

Of course, most planets will outshine (or at least out-reflect) a
starship throughout the EM spectrum as well.

Food for thought.

-Rob

