    'day' => '27',
    'date' => 'Tue, 27 Feb 1996 09:54:12  0500 (EST)',
    'from' => 'Massimo Stiavelli mstiavel@stsci.edu',
    'year' => 1996,
    'index' => 'ac733',
    'body' => 'David still does not want to see them.

First of all we do not see current ships with HST because none of them
has power in excess of 500 MW.

Before attempting a rebuttal I would like to stress that already in
my message I had admitted that finding where to look is the real problem.
So at least on that David agrees with me..We also agree that if the
ship is not using its power is not detected.

My assumption on the presence of relatively warm/hot points derives partly
from the Starship Op. Manual (e.g. the pag. 3 blurb on the blue glow,
although not very convincing) but partly on some simple argument which
should apply also in the 57th century.

The heat you can radiate depends on the surface of the radiators and
their temperature. You cannot convert your excess heat into a laser beam
and point it somewhere because of the way thermodynamics works.

So take your 200 tons ship, it has a volume of 2700 m^3 and a surface of
at least about 1000 m^2 (if it is close to a sphere) or more.
Take 2000 m^2 as rough estimate.
An order of magnitude estimate tells you that the ship can radiate through
the whole surface at 100 K. If you reduce the radiator surface the
temperature has to go up (although only as 1 over the fourth root of the
surface). 100K would save it from  detection from the current HST
but may not save it from the NICMOS equipped one. Of course one
can avoid using power, and than of course is not detected. One can
also emit in some other direction, except that to know where not to emit
your ship has  to detect HST...if in a system there are a few HSTs at
various location not all of them will be looking away. In any case the
directionality of radiators is obviously an important factor
in spoiling a detection.

What about battleships? if you have a 2Mton battleship rather than
a 200 tons ship the power will go up at least by a factor 10,000 but
the surface (for a given geometry) will only go up by 10,000^(2/3)
ie roughly 220 times. Thus the temperature will have to raise by
roughly 2.5. Now 250 K is not a bad temperature for IR detectors.

It seems to me that the detectability of a battleship on, say,
Jupiter remains a possibility.

             Cheers,
                 Massimo


