    'index' => 'ac735',
    'topic' => 'NICMOS and more detection problems (3rd attempt, 1st/2nd returned)',
    'body' => 'David was commenting on my comments on NICMOS:

it is true that nicmos has not flown yet and therefore one does not
know for sure its sensitivity. However my argument was the following:
if the exhaust is cooler given that the energy to be radiated is the
same you emit more photons. This would produce more signal in an equivalent
IR detector with the same quantum efficiency of WFPC2. Since IR detectors
have a bit lower QE, I guess we just have to wait to see which way it goes.

Another effect that would spoil a detection (I do not remember David
mentioning it so I will confess before he catches me!) is that if the not
too well masked ship I had considered is moving at high transversal velocity
it is not detected since the  signal is spread along a long track and the
signal to noise ratio decreases.
At 1 AU the limiting transversal velocity I had assumed was 30 km/s.

            Cheers,
               Massimo

