    'from' => 'Stewart Eyres spe@astro.keele.ac.uk',
    'year' => 1996,
    'index' => 'ac739',
    'topic' => 'Cool it!',
    'body' => 'In the HST detection debate

>You can also "cool" the emmision to below the IR.

I assume you mean change the emission frequency to below that of IR,
which means radio.  It can still be detected; if you can build
technology to emit at a given frequency, you can build it to detect at
that wavelength.  The point then isn\'t if it is physically impossible
to detect a ship, but is it possible for that ship to direct it\'s
waste emission in a specific direction.  I think I saw a laser beam
thing suggested, or radiators "around the back".  Regardless, you need
to get x amount of energy out, so if you go to lower frequency (lower
energy photons) then you need more photons.  If enough energy is
emitted, won\'t this result in significant scatter?  Even in the
"vacuum" of space, there is sufficient hydrogen to cause scattering,
provided the scattered source is strong enough, and the detector
sensitive enough.  A laser (or maser in radio) would appear as a
straight line, pointing back to the source.  Also, a l/maser would
spread out over distance, increasing the posibility of "illuminating"
other objects in space (planet, moons, asteroids, other spaceships,
dust, gas...) which could be detected and picked up.  If it is
possible to detect a given energy flux, then all you can do is make it
harder to see.  I guess we could argue till the Doomsday Comet falls
on our head about ability to make detection difficult vs ability to
cope with detection-avoidance.  It all depends on who spends the most
resources in the right way.

