    'index' => 'ac742',
    'body' => 'Summers@Ethyl-the-Frog.ARC.NASA.gov (David P. Summers) writes:

> Tue, 27 Feb 1996 09:54:12, Massimo Stiavelli <mstiavel@stsci.edu>
>>First of all we do not see current ships with HST because none of them
>>has power in excess of 500 MW.
>
>Mmy point was that we can\'t use current equipement (HST) to detect current
>ships.  If you want to talk about Traveller ships, you have to talk about
>_all_ the technology they have.  We don\'t have currently ships with 500 MW
>powerplants, but they also don\'t have Traveller concealment technology.
>You can\'t have it both ways.

Unfortunately, the only Traveller technology that can help is black
globes. The laws of thermodynamics *require* that the energy leave in
certain ways *or* stay put. Staying put raises the temp of the ship,
thus requiring even *more* heat be gotten rid of.

>>The heat you can radiate depends on the surface of the radiators and
>>their temperature. You cannot convert your excess heat into a laser beam
>>and point it somewhere because of the way thermodynamics works.
>
>Um no, you can\'t do it without having to put more energy in.  But you can
>do it.  All that means is that your laser has to put out the energy you
>want to loose and more.

No. You misunderstand. The laser can pump out *energy*, but it can\'t
pump out *heat*. The laser energy is highly organized (very low
entropy). Heat is the exact opposite (high entropy). Any heat you
managed to get "into" the laser beam would be insignificant next to the
heat *generated* in the process. It\'s thermodynamically *impossible*.


>Furthermore, you can also take the approach
>of reducing wavelength (apparent temperature of you cooling) so that
>it lies in the cosmic background (or is at a wavelength were it
>will be absorbed) without having to add energy.

Again, no. You *can\'t* have a radiating surface at a temp lower than
cosmic background, because it is *also* an *absorbing* surface. And if
it is cooler than the 3K background, it will *absorb* heat rather than
radiate it.

Furthermore, if you *did* get it to 3k, that means that all the rest of
the ship would have to be at that temperature. People don\'yt work well
at thet temp.

The temperature of a radiating surface depends on the rate at which
energy is radiated, and upon the *area* of the surface. The watts/meter
is *directly* related to temperature. That sets the wavelength. Period.

The areas of the ship that have life support are going to be at 300k.
The engineering areas are going to be *hotter* unless you have a good
radiator system. And that means that the radiators are going to be
*hotter*.

If you want to get rid of 500 MW at 3k, you are going to need square
*kilometers* of radiating area. Maybe more.

The hard facts are that any reasonably efficient ship design is going
to radiate IR *strongly*. At 300k from the crew areas, and more from
the engineering spaces. Any attempts to keep them from radiating just
mean that you have to pump the heat to somewhere else. And that
somewhere else is going to be *much* hotter, and therefore stand out
even more.

And the lower the temperature of the radiating suraces, the less
efficiently they\'ll get rid of heat. At 3k, they *can\'t* get rid of
heat. At 300k, they\'ll get rid of it slowly.

It is possible to work out how many watts/meter^2 will be radiated at a
given temperature assuming that the radiator is perfect using the
Stefan-Boltzmann equation. Unfortunately, that book is in storage.
However, the formulas required should be in both book 6, and in World
Builder\'s handbook as part of the calcs for determining the equilibrium
temp of a planet.

Dig them out and work the calcs. You\'ll find that you have a choice
between a small *hot* radiator, and a very, very large cool one.

Don\'t forget that your ship will be absorbing light and heat from the
star, so if it uses *no* power (and has no living creatures onboard) it
will be at the "equilibrium temp" for its distance from the star (if
it\'s moving slowly enough to reach equilibrium).

If there are people or power systems aboard, the will be creating waste
heat, which means the ship will be warmer than a natural object. You
*cannot* prevent this. Period.

You *can* re-distribute it. But that means that to cool part of the
hull, you\'ll have to make the rest hotter. That\'s your radiator. You\'ll
run into two limits. First, your radiator *has* to be below the melting
temp. (unless you use a liquid drop radiator, but that doesn\'t work
well on ships that accelerate at more than a small fraction of a gee).
Second, the bigger the difference in temp between the radiator and the
rest of the ship, the *harder* it is to pump heat into it. There *will*
be a point of diminishing returns.

Even with Traveller tech, the point of diminishing returns is likely to
be such that you\'ll need a fairly large radaitor surface and it\'ll be
at a temp that\'ll stand out like a neon sign.

If you want a contemporary example, check out what Russian radar
satellites look like in the IR. They use a nuclear reactor and they
stick out like a sore thumb on even crude IR surveys.

To summarize:

1. The radiator surface *will* be above 300k.
2. The smaller the radiator, the hotter it\'ll have to be.
3. There\'s a limit to how hot it can be. And not all that high a limit.
4. It has to point *somewhere*, and you have no way of knowing in
   advance which direction a scout may be.


Leonard Erickson (aka Shadow)
