    'topic' => ' XBOAT digest 552',
    'body' => 'Hurray! The list is back! I\'ve got this message that\'s been sitting
around for a week; I\'ll post it now, in case anyone can remember what we
were talking about a week ago.

Hurray! Traveller is back! Or will be RSN. Thank you Susan Shock and
Kerry Harrison for your very interesting posts.

Now, back to our regularly scheduled debates:

Just a few comments on a conversation between Massimo Stiavelli and
David Summers:

<Date: Wed, 28 Feb 1996 12:13:05 -0800
<From: Summers@Ethyl-the-Frog.ARC.NASA.gov (David P. Summers)

>Tue, 27 Feb 1996 09:54:12, Massimo Stiavelli <mstiavel@stsci.edu>

Massimo:
>Before attempting a rebuttal I would like to stress that already in
>my message I had admitted that finding where to look is the real problem.
>So at least on that David agrees with me..We also agree that if the
>ship is not using its power is not detected.

David:
<Actually this cover the point that I was trying to make.  Someone
<coming into a system has to deal with both of these, making (for those
<reasons and others) jumping into a system to spy on it a risking venture.

Me:
It seems to me that these concerns make jumping into a system far less risky.
It\'s the sentinels guarding the mainworld who don\'t know where to look
for the spy ship. But the spy ship knows where the mainworld is, and the
fleets that protect the mainworld must be near it in order to watch over
it. So the spy ship will have an easier time finding the fleet than
the fleet will have finding the spy ship.

Massimo:
>My assumption on the presence of relatively warm/hot points derives partly
>from the Starship Op. Manual (e.g. the pag. 3 blurb on the blue glow,
>although not very convincing)

David:
<I don\'t have the book in question, but my understanding is that those
<things in back, that look like engines, are the exaust for the Power
<Plant.  That would say that, even on unconcealed ships, they energy
<is "in back".

Me:
Putting the radiators in back won\'t help you if the spy ship is in back
too. In fact, you\'d be better off with no radiators at all in that case.

Actually tho, there is a fairly effective way to shield a fleet from
view. Just keep it so close to a planet that the planet\'s EM and neutrino
emmissions swamp out the fleet\'s signature. Then a spy ship has to come in
close enough to actually RESOLVE a warship in order to see it. Even
then, the fleet may be able to be camouflaged.

This seems to jibe well with canon. In JTAS, articles used to mention
warships hidden in oceans and jovian atmospheres. Obviously such methods
of concealment are not fool-proof, but they do give some edge to the
defenders.

Also, (just to remember where this thread came from) a j-torp is no more
likely to see through such camouflage than a manned ship.(Oh no! Not
j-torps again! 8^) And since spy ships court so little danger in the
first place, j-torps will not make a big change in a spook\'s safety.

-Rob

