>It seems to me that these concerns make jumping into a system far less risky.
>It\'s the sentinels guarding the mainworld who don\'t know where to look
>for the spy ship. But the spy ship knows where the mainworld is, and the
>fleets that protect the mainworld must be near it in order to watch over
>it.

First of all, "the mainworld" is not that small an area.  Second, you
don\'t know that the ships are at the main world.  The could, in fact,
be positioned to catch a ship that is assuming that only people on
the main world are looking for him.

>Me:
>Putting the radiators in back won\'t help you if the spy ship is in back
>too. In fact, you\'d be better off with no radiators at all in that case.

Just putting them in back is a crude example of a more general issue.
The more you can direct the energy, the smaller of an area you "need
the enemy not to be in".   If you can only stick your radiators on
one side, then you pretty much need some reason to believe the bad
guys aren\'t behind you.  If you can do better (which I would say
military ships are going to be able to) your requirements are
better.  If you can restrict the emmision to a 30 degree cone
(say be resessing the radiator) then you only need to know
that there is a 30 degree arc free of enemy.  If you can put
out the energy in a specific direction (using a laser or some
yet-to-be-discovered method) then you just need do know
there isn\'t and enemy in the one direction (which is pretty
easy to do).

In anycase, this is, in fact, more a problem for a spy ship.  A defender
can have multiple ships vulnerable from different directions (assuming
they just don\'t dump the energy in the direction of a planet, moon,
asteroid, comet, the sun, etc.) so that any one ship will only
detect one of them.  A spy ships need to know he isn\'t detected
by anyone.

>Actually tho, there is a fairly effective way to shield a fleet from
>view. Just keep it so close to a planet that the planet\'s EM and neutrino
>emmissions swamp out the fleet\'s signature. Then a spy ship has to come in
>close enough to actually RESOLVE a warship in order to see it. Even
>then, the fleet may be able to be camouflaged.

Exactly.

>Also, (just to remember where this thread came from) a j-torp is no more
>likely to see through such camouflage than a manned ship.(Oh no! Not
>j-torps again! 8^) And since spy ships court so little danger in the
>first place, j-torps will not make a big change in a spook\'s safety.

But if you can detect the other ships, they can detect you.  I might
point out a smaller signature for jump-torp, but that is besides the
point.  If things go wrong, you don\'t loose men and ships when you
send in a jump torp.

