  {
    'date' => 'Sat, 9 Mar 1996 13:25:29  0800 (PST)',
    'day' => '09',
    'body' => 'Hi, I just signed up here, so forgive me if I end up going over old ground.

I use the MT rules, since I dislike almost everything about TNE.  I do have
one problem with tasks, running observational tasks.  In games from Ars
Magica to Call of Cthulhu there are simple rules for who notices what.
Does the PC hear the person sneaking up behind them or not...

TNE tried to solve this with the Observation skill, and that might work
well if everyone had the same sensory capacity.  However, between the
Vargr sense of smell, Vegan and Hiver IR vision, and the Aslan sense of
hearing things get confusing fast.  Has anyone found some simple way to
adjudicate these problems?   Working out a table of +s and -s for each
species, with each sense seems a bit extreme, but rolling every species
using the same task seems rather limiting.

My best thought would be a secondary characteristic which was species
specific: Senses:  For humans it would be 0, perhaps for +2 for Vargr and
+1 for Aslan, -1 (or -2) for Virushi...  You would then have perceptual
tasks written up as

Difficulty [Int, Senses] (uncertain),  or perhaps if looking for an Ambush
say Difficult [Int, Recon, Senses] (uncertain).

Tasks using sensors would remain Difficulty [Int, Sensor Ops]


Comments, other possibilities....


-John Snead jsnead@netcom.com

-Free-lance game designer/writer


