    'index' => 'ac765',
    'body' => 'Harley Grantham wrote:

>I have been giving some thought to what cities and other structures
>would look like in the Traveller Universe.
[...]
>The Imperial palace is a massive floating sphere. Dull. Dull, Dull, Dull!
>I would think once technology can free from the laws of physics, they
>would let there imaginations soar, not revert to simple shapes that are
>easy for non-artists to draw.  (Which seems to have been a major factor
>in Traveller descriptions.)

The description in TD#9 suggests that the architects decided to go with
a simple, massive design that served at least two purposes.  First, the
design was meant to be defensible.  No fancy platforms, clear fields of
fire for hidden surface weapons emplacements, strictly controlled and
visible access points.

The architect wanted to make a clear, stark statement about the solidity
of the Imperium.  A floating sphere a kilometer in diameter is a mighty
structure, simple, and stark.  It gets your attention.  And in 630, it
was probably an impressive technological achievement.  The building
displaces almost forty million tons in starship terms.

The previous palace, was designed by Martin II, and was supposed to be
splendid, and was also rather rococo -- it ended up being almost over
decorated.  Perhaps the practical Arbellatra wanted to make a statement
which expressed the might of Imperial power without the overdone fancy
architecture of previous, discredited Imperial administrations.

It\'s also elegantly surreal, as befits an emperor of the galaxy.  It seems
reminiscent of Magritte\'s painting "La voix des airs" to me.

Mark Seeman <mark@dk-online.dk> added:

>Well, the period in which the Imperial Palace was build was maybe a =
>\'functionalist\' or \'geometric\' one. Think of some of the arcitecture of =
>the twenties (Bauhaus but especially Funkis) or the sixties-seventies. =

Believe it or not, this fits with something I remember from _Signal GK_.
One of the liner\'s cabins was decorated in a post-Civil War style -- stark,
plain, with a lot of solid colors and translucent furniture.

  Steve Bonneville
  <bonn0015@itlabs.umn.edu>

