    'index' => 'ac775',
    'body' => 'On Wed, 13 Mar 1996, Jo Grant wrote:

>   I would imagine that most RC type campaigns could be
> lifted and insterted, without much change, into the
> new settings. Contrarywise new setting material could
> be just as easily grafted into ongoing RC type campaigns.

I cannot imagine "lifting" an existing campaign and "inserting" it into a
new setting, and having the campaign survive.  GDW made the same
suggestion about existing CT/MT campaigns when TNE came out, and I found
it equally repugnant.  Words fail to express, etc.

My CT campaign world is an integral part of the campaign.  Several
characters served in the Fifth Frontier War; one is considered a war
criminal by the Zhodani for his actions.  All have significant NPC
contacts outside their starship.  The PCs care what happens in the world,
and have political opinions.  One, for a trivial example, idolizes Norris,
and wants nothing more than to meet him.

Were I to "lift" my campaign out of its era and "insert" it into the Year
0 setting, as Ms. Grant blithely suggests, my players would lynch me.  I
could either (1) junk all of my existing NPCs, or (2) "lift and insert"
them into an alien setting.  The first would destroy a network of
contacts, connections, and attachments that are crucial to the
characters\' development.  The second would destroy suspension of disbelief.


>   Most Classic style campaigns are often set on the
> fringe anyway. The new setting just moves the fringe
> to a new location.

I cannot imagine what sort of campaign you run, if the setting is so
peripheral to the game that you can junk it.

Joe Saul
jmsaul@umich.edu

