    'from' => 'David P. Summers',
    'year' => 1996,
    'index' => 'ac798',
    'topic' => ' Terran Federation - How Large a Population?',
    'body' => '[Responding to few selected points.  I agree that the Solomani victory
has a few problems.  However, I disagree with where they are.  I don\'t
care for deciding that the history is all a lie, since that opens
a whole new set of issues and I don\'t really care for the approach,
but I won\'t really address it.]

Date: Mon, 18 Mar 1996 22:00:18 +1100 (EST), Phillip McGregor
<aspqrz@sydney.DIALix.oz.au>

>Then, consider this. What did the other planets (outside of Vland) *eat*? We
>are told that the plants and animals of Vland were largely inedible to the
>Vilani ... surely the chances of any planet having *any* food that is edible
>by humans or human descended/related lifeforms is so close to nil as to be
>pointless considering?!

You just can\'t make this statement.  We simply don\'t know enough about
why life evolved the way it did.  It can be argued that all life is going
to be based on the same sets of amino acids and nucleic acids.  It may
be that edible food is hard to come by for humans but it may also be
common.  [It should also be noted that things are easier for microbes
who will probably be able to live in any carbon based biosphere.]

>Moreover,
>it is made quite plain in a variety of sources that most animals that can be
>encountered are *edible*. Assuming that they are, then it seems to me that
>there is a very high chance (approaching 100%) that each such planet will
>haveat least one ... and probably several (tens, hundreds?) diseases that
>will find human beings quite palatable. So the Vilani *must* have had
>considerable
>experience with disease prior to contact with the Terrans.

The problem the Vilani had is that they were unable to develop a consitent
biology.  Since some of the species (including man, the one of most interest)
came from a completely seperate biosphere with a completely different universal
ancestory, the theories kept running into things they couldn\'t handle.  The
result is that Vilani medicine and biology had to treat every species and
disease as a unique case (and you can forget about genetics).  This leaves
them stuck back about where we were in the late 1800\'s/early 1900\'s.  Now
the Vilani were probly reasonably adept at treating microbial infections,
since microbes aren\'t so dependant on "high level" aspects of how biology
works, but viruses are another matter.

