I don\'t know *where* you\'re getting this sort of disinformation, but it is
patently untrue.  Women in Muslim countries certainly don\'t have the same
advantages or opportunities as women in the Western world do, but then
neither do women in Latin America--a primarily Catholic region.  Both
Pakistan and Turkey have had female prime ministers (which is certainly
better than the U.S. has done), and women attend universities and enter
professions such as medicine and academia alongside men.  In Algeria, women
participated in the struggle to kick the French out and in the West Bank and
Gaza, women have been involved in the intifada.  It is true that in most
Muslim countries, women are encouraged to stay at home and people try to
segregate of the sexes, but that doesn\'t justify sweeping generalizations
like yours.  (In fact, in the Gulf, efforts to segregate men and women have
resulted in *more* professional opportunities for women, since only a woman
doctor should examine a woman and separate banks have been set up with only
female customers and only female employees).

As a side note, I find it interesting that this subject came up right after
a call to squelch a racist group on usenet.  Over the past few years, it\'s
seemed to me that prejudice against Arabs and other Muslim peoples is one of
the few brands of racism that\'s still considered acceptable.

