    'index' => 'ac808',
    'topic' => ' XBOAT digest 564',
    'body' => '>>>>>>> Phil McGregor said:

> But the Solomani didn\'t have cloning! Its not available even for body parts
> until after TL12 (the highmark at the *end* of the Interstellar Wars!).
> Another strike for the five "p\'s" being ignored in Traveller ... and
> another gaping hole in the continuity!

  I never said anything about cloning - Rats & Cats says "artificial
wombs."  The implication is that the eggs and sperm were obtained from
human donors, were mixed, and then put in an artificial womb.  This is
not much of a stretch from current tech - it is already possible to
extract eggs from a human donor, fertilize them, and then implant them in
a human host.  Prenatal units can already handle premature babies of less
than a pound - I\'d have to say a fully artificial process is possible in
the near term.

> What exactly does it say in "Solomani & Aslan"? Does it *definitively*
> refer to the Nth Interstellar War period? Does it explain why a TL/16+
> tech is available at between TL/9 and TL/12?

  Yes, this refers to the Nth War period.  Again, it does not say
"cloning," so I suppose I was technically incorrect in saying that was
"canon" - what I really meant was that GenAssist developed tech that
bypassed normal childbirth.

  What is even more interesting is the potential this has for the
long-term social patterns of these "tuber" colonies - places where all
reproduction is done artificially and folks see natural childbirth as
"primitive" and "disgusting" - imagine the flak a pregnant PC might get!

----
