    'body' => 'Robert Flammang <FLAMMANG@vms.cis.pitt.edu> wrote:

> The real mystery to me is how did they conquer the Vilani? Two
>  possibilities present themselves:
>
>       1) The Vilani Population was unusually low. But why? I don\'t
>  find the plague argument very convincing either.
>
>        2) Many of the Vilani almost wanted to be conquered. The TC
> government just looked that much better to the Vilani "voters" who were
> fighting in the trenches.
>
> Other possibilities exist of course. I just happened to think of these
> two.
>
> Of course, this begs the question, did they really beat the Vilani?

Re: 1)

We know from Vilani and Vargr that Vilani have extra-long lifespans (say,
200 years for a pure-bred Vilani); I assume (and I\'ve no proof of this)
that this longevity is due to Ancient tinkering. It seems reasonable to
assume that the Ancients may also have taken action to reduce Vilani
breeding speed. In addition, since food was either scarce or very difficult
to prepare during early Vilani history, children would probably have been
far more widely spaced.

There is of course no canon backing for this assumption, but it would
provide an explanation for slow Vilani population growth.

Eric Evans

