>
> >Then, consider this. What did the other planets (outside of Vland) *eat*? We
> >are told that the plants and animals of Vland were largely inedible to the
> >Vilani ... surely the chances of any planet having *any* food that is edible
> >by humans or human descended/related lifeforms is so close to nil as to be
> >pointless considering?!
>
> You just can\'t make this statement.  We simply don\'t know enough about
> why life evolved the way it did.  It can be argued that all life is going
> to be based on the same sets of amino acids and nucleic acids.  It may
> be that edible food is hard to come by for humans but it may also be
> common.  [It should also be noted that things are easier for microbes
> who will probably be able to live in any carbon based biosphere.]

Why can\'t I make such a statement? What are the chances of life randomly
evolving on completely separate worlds being so close to that of other worlds
as to be edible? So astronomically large *against* it occurring *UNLESS* you
accept something like the Panspermia hypothesis that it is pointless even
considering any other evolutionary explanation. Or, perhaps, Grandfather wasn\'t
the *first* "Ancient"?

There is no evidence in any of the Traveller material that food is difficult to
find on most planets -- and the Animal Encounter rules (IIRC) assume that
larger animals can be hunted down and used for food. Not possible on Vland, but
possible *everywhere* else? Seems like you *have* to accept Panspermia - which
inevitably means that the argument about the Plague of Duskir (and nobody\'s
come up with a reliable reference to this *yet* ... was *IT* also from some
late term DGP nightmare?) is unlikely (and the Plague occurred *after* the war
in any case!).

> >Moreover,
> >it is made quite plain in a variety of sources that most animals that can be
> >encountered are *edible*. Assuming that they are, then it seems to me that
> >there is a very high chance (approaching 100%) that each such planet will
> >haveat least one ... and probably several (tens, hundreds?) diseases that
> >will find human beings quite palatable. So the Vilani *must* have had
> >considerable
> >experience with disease prior to contact with the Terrans.
>
> The problem the Vilani had is that they were unable to develop a consitent
> biology.  Since some of the species (including man, the one of most interest)
> came from a completely seperate biosphere with a completely different universa
> ancestory, the theories kept running into things they couldn\'t handle.  The
> result is that Vilani medicine and biology had to treat every species and
> disease as a unique case (and you can forget about genetics).  This leaves
> them stuck back about where we were in the late 1800\'s/early 1900\'s.  Now
> the Vilani were probly reasonably adept at treating microbial infections,
> since microbes aren\'t so dependant on "high level" aspects of how biology
> works, but viruses are another matter.

But you haven\'t dealt with the specific point! *IF*, as I contend *must* be the
case, the Vilani encounter hundreds of worlds where the local life forms are
edible by humans (and where local human races, major or minor, already exist),
then there is *no* justification whatsoever for the claim that the Plague of
Duskir would have had any real effect so late in their history. By then they
would have had so much disease experience from other worlds in their imperium
that any early false starts caused by lack of coherent biology on Vland would
be meaningless in the overall scheme of things. It\'s a *major* logical
inconsistency ... assuming that you accept the Plague of Duskir as canon, and
I\'m beginning to suspect that it should *not* be accepted as such as it seems
like it (just as Rats & Cats seems to be) was a late term DGP aberration
completely at odds with the basic rules/concepts of the background/game.

Phil McGregor

