> At 06:01 AM 18/03/96 -0500, you wrote:
>
> Also, Phil, in another post you asked why there was so little edible food on
> Vland when adventurers usually have a good chance of hunting down something
> edible.  Just because 80% (to pick a random figure; I don\'t recall what the
> rules say) of carbon-based animal and plant life in the galaxy is edible by
> humans doesn\'t mean that 80% of the animal and plant life on any given
> *planet* is edible.  The Vilani could very well have just gotten unlucky (or
> lucky; would they have gotten anywhere if they didn\'t have to cooperate?)
> and gotten stuck with a really rough planet.  There\'s pretty strong evidence
> scattered throughout _Traveller_ products that something like this is the
> case.  The Vargr didn\'t get quite as bad a deal.  There\'s plenty of edible
> food on Lair, but most of it just doesn\'t appeal to the Vargr palatte (which
> is why most Vargr food tastes like Cajun blackened vindaloo).

But the Panspermia theory is intended to deal with the ridiculously,
humungously, outrageously large chance *against* any given planet developing
any sort of food edible by organisms from any other such planet. The chance is
so infinitesimally small that there is, realistically, no chance at all of
Terrans finding edible food "on the hoof" (or even after a great deal of
processing) on *any* planet. So, the problem Vland has should be the problem
faced on *all* worlds ... but it isn\'t! *This* is the problem.

Sure, you can assume a much wider distribution of ancient transplanted *terran*
organisms, but this defeats the claims for the nastiness of the Plague of
Duskir, which has been the alleged "canonical" explanation for the succes of
the Terrans. However, this simply means that the Vilani would inevitably have
been exposed widely to Terran disease organisms ... or terran *compatible*
disease organisms *well* before they dealt with terra. And they would have had
to have developed the medical knowledge to deal with such diseases ... and
this means that any deficiency in Vilani medical science would have been
pre-Starflight.

> Consider that all carbon-based races can apparently eat the same food.
> Sometimes in race descriptions, it has said clearly that races can eat human
> food and vice versa, and when not stated explicitly, it\'s strongly implied.
> I can\'t think of any race for which a ship\'s captain would have to bring
> special food stores.  Of course, I don\'t think it\'s likely that a Vargr and
> a K\'Kree would swap lunches, but such dietary differences are far less
> radical than some among different animals on Earth.

Ergo, Panspermia *must* be right ... and, ergo, Vilani medical knowledge *must*
have been good enough to deal with the alleged Plague of Duskir!

