    'body' => 'At 07:02 AM 20/03/96 -0500, you wrote:

>I am assuming that Rats & Cats was *very* late DGP stuff ... I\'d never even
>heard of it before ...

"Rats & Cats" is the nickname for "Solomani & Aslan", in case that wasn\'t
clear.  It was the last (and only second) alien module they put out.

>... DGP didn\'t do their
>homework! Apart from there being no (even vague) intimation of anything like
>this elsewhere in the canon *and* it being impossible (MTrav Referees
>Compendium) to even clone *body parts* until TL13 (which occurs either right at
>the end of the Nth Interstellar war, in which case it isn\'t in time; or
>*after* it, in which case it also isn\'t possible) ... Genetic Engineering isn\'t
>available until TL14, and Partial Memory Transfer (Dupe) isn\'t available until
>TL18, it doesn\'t gel with anything else in anything we\'ve ever been told about
>the Terran Federation or even the Solomani. It seems like the last dying gasp
>of DGP more than anything else!

I think you\'re confused about what people mean by cloning.  By "full" clone,
we\'re talking about a complete *body* which will is born/decanted and then
will be raised and subject to the same stimuli that form all the other
individual personalities in the universe.  It is only "selective cloning of
replacement parts" that has to wait until TL13.  It makes a lot of sense for
body part cloning to be a much *later* development than full-body cloning.
First, serious ethical problems would arise from cloning an entire sentient
being just to lop off a limb for a replacement.  Also, you\'ve got to make
the clone growth much faster.  If not, you\'ll always be significantly older
than your replacement and it just won\'t do you any good.  You seem to think
that the "full clones" we\'re talking about are carbon copies--same bodies,
same memories, same personality as the original.

>But you then run into the problem that raising children takes time. Or, at
>least, assuming that you have (or wish to have) children *you* would want to
>spend some time with them? The more children you have, the more the woman is
>going to be tied down (or, let\'s not be sexist, the *man* just as likely)
>caring for them even if she doesn\'t have to carry them to term ... babies take
>a lot of looking after! So *this* interferes with her career *far* more than
>the actual 9 months of pregnancy ... and how much of this will they be prepared
>to put up with? I would suggest that the likely average family size is going to
>be around 2-3, and this is below replacement rate for a stable high level of
>population. And your claim that a colonial society would allow for more
>resources per child makes no sense on the above basis.

Remember that in *real* earth history, numerous solutions have been applied
to the problem of raising basket-loads of kids.  You get older children to
look after them, or hired professionals, or sit them in front of a video
screen for hours a day.
>
>Ergo, Panspermia *must* be right ... and, ergo, Vilani medical knowledge *must*
>have been good enough to deal with the alleged Plague of Duskir!

I have a professor who told me that whenever somebody says "it must have
been", that\'s a code for "I have no evidence" :) (not a dig--just a humorous
aside).  Like I say, the Vilani just got stuck with a bad planet.  I
understand your attacks on the innovations from DGP, but the idea of the
Vilani having poor medical knowledge has been tied up with their identity
for as long as I\'ve seen published material on them.  See Imperial
Encyclopedia, p.45.

This is an interesting exercise in future history, but why do we care?  It
won\'t matter a hill of beans in my campaign whether the Vilani lost because
of plagues, population, or superior Solomani ball bearings.


