> Because it depends on a level of knowledge that we just don\'t have.
> You are, of course, free to _presume_ that it is true for your own
> uses (it isn\'t contradicted by what we know), but to claim that
> other approaches aren\'t realistic can\'t be supported by our current
> level of understanding.

Well, everything I\'ve ever read on the subject in the way of *science* seems to
make the point I have been ... unless we assume something like "Panspermia"
then the chances of anything we ever discover being edible is unlikely in the
extreme. Just think of the "handedness" problems in proteins (?) where a mirror
image protein (?) is *eatable* (perhaps) but has no food value at all. And
that\'s just one of the possible (probable!) problems that random evolution
could throw up (and *will*, as far as we can figure) to make alien lifeforms
completely useless as food for terrans.

> >What are the chances of life randomly
> >evolving on completely separate worlds being so close to that of other worlds
> >as to be edible? So astronomically large *against* it occurring *UNLESS* you
> >accept something like the Panspermia hypothesis that it is pointless even
> >considering any other evolutionary explanation. Or, perhaps, Grandfather wasn
> >the *first* "Ancient"?
>
> Again, you can\'t make this statement.  There is no factual basis for
> either supporting it or denying the premise.  It may be that life
> is so ubiquitous that life exists in almost every system (if we
> were to find out that life once existed on Mars, that would go a
> long way toward supporting such a view) and it also may be
> that it is extremely rare.

I\'m sorry? There\'s no factual basis for it? There\'s a damn good *mathematical*
basis for it! The chances (probability theory here) of any random development
of life evolving in a form that will be edible to any other life-form that has
been developed in complete isolation is so close to zero, obviously, that it
needs no calculation. Only if something like "panspermia" is accepted is there
a realistic chance that any given life-bearing world will have edible food on
it for Terrans. Your saying that I can\'t make the statement is a complete
nonsense.

> That fact is that we know nothing about other biospheres.  It is quite
> possible that life has to follow a general plan that makes thing
> _generally_ edible, but on Vland most species use and enzyme that
> happens to be toxic to humans.

Yes, but probabilities are such that this is astronomically *unlikely*. So
unlikely that Vland is either weird because it\'s the exception, or everywhere
else has the same problem. Since the latter is *not* the case in Traveller,
then the problem is that Vland is weird ... and everywhere else has Terran
compatible lifeforms, ergo they will develop diseases capable of preying on
Terran descended life-forms ... and this makes a nonsense of the argument
that the Vilani were still suffering from any real medical lag when they met
the Terrans. It therefore makes the Plague of Duskir (which happened *after*
the collapse of the Empire anyway) a non-explanation for the Terran victory
despite the smaller Terran population and it makes the inability of the Vilani
to deal with it most likely to be a result of the sort of societal chaos that
inevitably results from the loss of a war such as the Interstellar wars.
In other words, GenAssist is a DGP fantasy, just like the "sparklers", and is
rightfully rejected as completely non-canon.

> >Seems like you *have* to accept Panspermia - which
> >inevitably means that the argument about the Plague of Duskir (and nobody\'s
> >come up with a reliable reference to this *yet* ... was *IT* also from some
> >late term DGP nightmare?) is unlikely (and the Plague occurred *after* the wa
> >in any case!).
>
> I don\'t see this.  Aside from the fact that you don\'t have to invoke panspermi
> I see nothing that precludes the Plague of Duskir in it.

Well, if you don\'t, I think we\'ll have to agree to disagree as I cannot see how
anyone can be so dense and lacking in basic scientific knowledge as to *not* see
that it *must* be the case ... and you obviously think much the same, but in
reverse. We have no basis for argument, so there\'s no point in carrying it
further.

> >But you haven\'t dealt with the specific point! *IF*, as I contend *must* be t
> >case, the Vilani encounter hundreds of worlds where the local life forms are
> >edible by humans (and where local human races, major or minor, already exist)
> >then there is *no* justification whatsoever for the claim that the Plague of
> >Duskir would have had any real effect so late in their history.  By then they
> >would have had so much disease experience from other worlds in their imperium
> >that any early false starts caused by lack of coherent biology on Vland would
> >be meaningless in the overall scheme of things.  It\'s a *major* logical
> >inconsistency
>
> I have delt with the point.  I\'ll try and be more clear.  What you
> are saying hold generally true for microbial infections (bacteria
> and the like) since that ability humans to eat food on other worlds
> does imply the ability to be infected by microbes that also "eat"
> in that biosphere.  However, it _doesn\'t_ apply to viral infections.
> It is quite possible that humans can only catch viruses from Terran
> species.

As I understand it, Viruses are based on incomplete RNA strands that have to
use human (or terran animal) cells to complete their "life" cycle. How can you
not see that such a development *must* be the logical corollary of Panspermia?
If all life has been spread evenly throughout the galaxy from a single source,
it cannot be other than that most (if not all) worlds where it has been spread
must have viruses as well. And, in any case, does it say that the Plague of
Duskir was only a virus?

> >... assuming that you accept the Plague of Duskir as canon

> I don\'t know if the Plague of Duskir is "canon".  It do think it should
> be (except that it should be, if my understanding is right, moved up
> to earlier than it presented).  It would go a long way toward explaining
> a Terran victory (especially if combined with simultaneous Vargr raid
> and various Rebelious fleet captains intent on seizing control of the
> First Imperium for themselves.).

Agreed, it *would* explain things - *EXCEPT* for the logical fallacy that GDW
has perpetrated in allowing/assuming all worlds except Vland to be home to
Terran edible organisms! For the reasons noted above. And, in any case, it
*isn\'t* canon, and it *didn\'t* occur earlier. Wishful thinking on your part is
just that, wishful thinking!

> >I\'m beginning to suspect that it should *not* be accepted as such as it seems
> >like it (just as Rats & Cats seems to be) was a late term DGP aberration
> >completely at odds with the basic rules/concepts of the background/game.
>
> Sort of like jump torps?  (sorry, I couldn\'t resist.  :-)

What\'s wrong with pointing out the flaws in the background? As the rules have
been written, and as they have been expanded, over the years, Jump Torps *are*
possible. Just as USL ships *are* capable of landing on worlds with an
atmosphere. The prohibitions against them are both contradicted in numerous
places. Sure. I\'ll even agree that the *intention* of GDW was to not allow
JTorps or USL landings on atmosphere planets ... unfortunately, they\'ve
put so many holes in their rules by trying to add what I regard as needless
chrome that they contradict their own prohibitions. It\'s called being too smart
for one\'s own good.

This *may* be another such case. However, since the only evidence that supports
*your* side of the story is DGP stuff that cannot be regarded as 100% canon,
then it is much more of a grey area.

Phil McGregor

