>
>   Based on Phil\'s comments, I should add that the children are raised by
> robots and a few human minders.  Education is by "subliminal tapes", not
> any sort of TL16 memory transfer.

What Robots? According to Book #8: Robots, it is only at TL/12 that the first
self-mobile computer brain with developed manipulative appendages (i.e. a
robot) finally becomes an economic and commercial reality. AI software can be
developed, but cost and size are limiting factors ... remember Aybee (?) from
the DGP Digests? He was, what, TL/16? And *he* was not AI in any real sense -
and this was made plain on a considerable number of occasions ... like every
issue! So, at TL/12-13 there *are* no Robots. Sorry to puncture your balloon!

Also, note that it is plainly stated that Memory transfer is not available
until TL/16 ... subliminal teaching is a crock that doesn\'t work here and now
and is not mentioned anywhere in Traveller ... certainly not in any of the
"official" GDW publications.

>   By the way, Rats & Cats provides some support for this position:
> "GenAssist first sought to genetically alter Terran and alien lifeforms
> so that food supply was not a problem."  p. 20.

Unfortunately this means, technically speaking, that they are unlikely to be of
the same species any more ... they will be Homo Sapiens *XXX* (name of specific
planet) rather than Homo Sapiens Sapiens (i.e. *us*) ... and it is likely that
they will be as capable of interbreeding as Horses and Donkeys, or Lions and
Tigers ... all they wil produce (if they\'re lucky) are *mules*. I do not see
that a society that eventually develops the Solomani Party on one side and the
Society for the Soveriegnty of Man over Machine (and then classes cyborgs as
machines) on the other could spawn such a movement ... we\'re talking Nazi level
nasties here, kiddo!

>   In Rats & Cats this is cited as a major reason behind the swift Terran
> victory.

And Rats and Cats is not certainly canon.

> > I am assuming that Rats & Cats was *very* late DGP stuff ... I\'d never even
> > heard of it before ... like the "Sparklers" I\'ve seen mentioned quite
> > negatively on this mailing list. I can understand why ... DGP didn\'t do thei
> > homework! Apart from there being no (even vague) intimation of anything like
> > this elsewhere in the canon *and* it being impossible (MTrav Referees
> > Compendium) to even clone *body parts* until TL13 (which occurs either right
> > the end of the Nth Interstellar war, in which case it isn\'t in time; or
> > available until TL14, and Partial Memory Transfer (Dupe) isn\'t available unt
> > TL18, it doesn\'t gel with anything else in anything we\'ve ever been told abo
> > the Terran Federation or even the Solomani. It seems like the last dying gas
> > of DGP more than anything else!
>
>   Come on, DGP _wrote_ MegaTraveller, for crying out loud.  Their stuff
> is cannon - frankly, it\'s better than a lot of GDW stuff as far as
> consistency goes (anyone want to go another round on jump torpedoes?  I
> didn\'t think so).  Again, as I point out above, the Solomani _did not use
> cloning_.  They used artificial wombs and robot nannies, well within the
> tech capability of the time.  If you do not agree with this fine - just
> stop talking about "cloning" and "memory transfer" - there is no
> reference to the Solomani using these technologies.

Well, yes and no. They wrote MTrav under the aegis of GDW, and Miller et al
seem to have their names prominently on the design credits as well! So, the
stuff that GDW published was *approved* by GDW ... and anything that DGP
