    'index' => 'ac834',
    'body' => 'Excerpts from Xboat-TML: 22-Mar-96 XBOAT digest 567 by xboat@MPGN.COM
> >Does anyone know of a good set of rules covering robots, their design
> >and their behaviour?  I know that there\'s the Robots supplement (which
> >I\'m searching for) but I\'m not sure if that book is applicable to
> >MegaTraveller rules.
>
> The Robot rules work quite well with MT.  In fact, a lot of what\'s included
> as robot design is identical to MT vehicle design.  The Robot supplement
> mainly adds rules for designing and programming the robot brain, and rating
> robots in terms of UPP\'s.  If you use some combination with the MT vehicle
> design rules, multiply all figures for "hit points" by a factor of ten, or
> you\'ll have robots that fall to pieces in front of body pistols (which
> isn\'t how they\'re supposed to work).

In fact, Book 8 "Robots" was written by the very people who founded DGP.
 No surprise that the design sequence resembles the MT craft design.  In
addition, "101 Vehicles" (also by DGP) provides an interesting twist.
They suggest allowing robot brains to replace computers (in small
vehicles anyway) and that robot brains have CP multipliers of 250(!) per
point of intelligence.  Even an Int 1, Edu 1 dumbot can reduce the
number of control panels in nearly all vehicles to a single panel, and
drive the thing too!

In my most recent campaign, robot brains became all the rage for
starships.  They allow a real "Star Trek" feel to ship operations where
you just talk to the ship and it does things for you.  Of course, I
wouldn\'t want a robot brain to be all that stands between me and hard
vacuum (or jumpspace) on a starship, though.  The robot brain at most
replaces one of the three computers normally required for a starship;
the regular computers prevent the robot brain from doing serious damage
if it malfunctions.  The CP requirements were used as listed in the
design sequence for purposes of installing panels and determining normal
crew requirements.  The robot brain\'s CP multiplier was used for
determining the absolute minimum number of crew in a pinch.  If I
remeber correctly, a robot brain with enough intelligence/education
and/or storage to be usable without Robot Ops skill, and have Pilot-2,
Nav-2, Engineer-2, Gunnery-1, ShipTactics-1 cost less than a model 3
computer.


--
