I\'m not sure what you have read so I can\'t comment on it.  I personally
happen to work in the field (disclaimer: I speak only for myself, not
for NASA or my employer!) and what you are say "has to be" is, in fact,
only one of several possiblities.

>Just think of the "handedness" problems in proteins (?) where a mirror
>image protein (?) is *eatable* (perhaps) but has no food value at all.

However, it is quite possible that one handedness works better.  The
fact is that we don\'t know where, or why, chirality arose.  Nobody
has made protiens of amino acids of the other isomer and we just
don\'t know if they form the requisite protiens.

Now I happen to agree that you would probably find biospheres randomly
distributed between the two isomers, but this is an _opinion_.  You
can\'t objectively claim it\'s right or wrong.

>And
>that\'s just one of the possible (probable!) problems that random evolution
>could throw up (and *will*, as far as we can figure) to make alien lifeforms
>completely useless as food for terrans.

Here you are talking about what is _possible_ and slip in a _will_ without
support.  What you say is indeed _possible_.  You can\'t say, based
on what we know, that is _will_ happen.

>I\'m sorry? There\'s no factual basis for it? There\'s a damn good *mathematical*
>basis for it! The chances (probability theory here) of any random development
>of life evolving in a form that will be edible to any other life-form that has
>been developed in complete isolation is so close to zero, obviously, that it
>needs no calculation.

I\'m sorry, this is just wrong.  You can\'t use probability theory when you
don\'t even know how probably the fundamental events are.  You have
_assume_ they are relatively unlikely and then used probability to
conclude that the probablility is "so close to zero".  The fact is
that, regardless of how much math you throw in, your conclusion
is no better than the base assumption.

>> That fact is that we know nothing about other biospheres.  It is quite
>> possible that life has to follow a general plan that makes thing
>> _generally_ edible, but on Vland most species use and enzyme that
>> happens to be toxic to humans.
>
>Yes, but probabilities are such that this is astronomically *unlikely*.  So
>unlikely that Vland is either weird because it\'s the exception, or everywhere
>else has the same problem. Since the latter is *not* the case in Traveller,
