    'body' => '> Date: Fri, 22 Mar 96 11:41:00 EST
> From: "Upton, Django" <DUpton@vtrnntov.telecom.com.au>
> To: xboat <xboat@MPGN.COM>
> Subject: On the Interstellar Wars.
> Message-ID: <31531F25@msmailv0.telecom.com.au>
>
> Terran industrial capacity:
>
>      One important aspect seems to have been left out here. I recall reading
> (in CT book 8 robots I think) that the TC made extensive use of robots and
> automated factories in their expansion, particularly for outposts. This
> becomes even more important at the end of the wars when the TC was at TL12.
>
>      Using robots etc expands your industrial capacity without the need for
> a corresponding increase in population. This is great in wartime but might
> not be so good in peacetime when it puts people out of work!

This is exaclt my argument. The Terrans didn\'t *need* a large population - they
were simply able to outproduce the Vilani who, I would propose, were still at
the manned factory stage of production because of their social conservatism
(remember that we are told that they did not introduce new inventions or ideas
willy nilly - as the Terrans did - but considered them, sometimes for several
hundreds of years, before deciding how/when/where to use them). They saw the
increased automation as a source of societal disruption in their static society
(and in one of the ImpEncyc article, IIRC, it is actually stated that the
freeing up of Vilani social controls led to, as an example, workers leaving
factories idle now that they were able to move around freely!) and did not
allow it ... the Terrans saw it as a new idea and simply applied it regardless
of any consequences.

So. Why are prices of anything so high in relation to wages in the Third
Imperium? An Air Raft costs around 40 years wages! With mass production, it
should cost no more (in *relative* terms) than a modern car. Sure, at TL/15
(say) you wouldn\'t be getting the latest "cutting edge" TL/15 model ... but
you\'d get a perfectly serviceable (say) TL/10 version for the same (relative)
price as a modern small car ... no more than half a year\'s wages, and probably
less. In *all* versions of Traveller, this is not allowed for ... and TL/10
Air/Rafts cost *in Imperial Credits* MORE than TL/15 ones, despite being less
capable!!!

My original suggestion was that the Terran Confederation won the war with the
Vilani by outproducing them with Robot factories and, just on winning, were
betrayed by plotters within their own military who dealt treasonously with the
Vilani Megacorps and Bureaus ... gaining their support for the coup in return
for minimising social disruption - to whit (as one thing), the decomissioning
of the robot factories and the use of the outdated, archaic, Vilani style
manned factories.

>      This "left over" industrial capacity would have kept going for a while
> after the wars at the same time that the Vilani economy was collapsing under
> the strain of the vast social changes brought about by Solomani insistence
> on "improving" things.

> This would have allowed the Solomani to gain substantial economic advantages
> and take over large amounts of Vilani industry. This situation seems to have
> persisted into the Third Imperium (and explains just _how_ the Solomani
> Nobility got control of such a large proportion of the Imperial economy).

No, I think you mean persisted into the *second* Imperium ... the Rule of Man.
There is no evidence that it exists in the Third Imperium. And, for the reasons
above, I would suggest that the Terran robotic factories must have been put out
of service relatively quickly to keep the treasonous deal that Estigaribbia
made with the Vilani for help in his coup against the democratically elected
Terran Confederation.

I mean, look at it from their point of view ... Estigaribbia and his friends
in the military, used to wielding great personal power during the course of
the wars are now, overnight, virtually un-needed. All that power gone! And
the Vilani Bureaus, well, they\'re even worse off ... and, as we\'ve been told,
some sections of Vilani society welcomed the overthrow of the upper classes
and bureaucrats; so why wouldn\'t the latter support Estigaribbia? They\'d end up
with almost everything they\'d had before ... sure the aftermath of the Terran
victory made things pretty chaotic, but it was the best that they could
salvage, and a reasonable deal, all things considered.

After all, do you *really* believe that garbage line of black propaganda that
Estigaribbia realised that the democratically elected government of the Terran
Confederation (and consider how a Confederacy is organised) wouldn\'t be able to
govern the now collapsing and conquered Vilani Imperium? But one man *could*!
It just happened to be the single man who had the most personal power to lose
in the Confederation! Sure, we\'re told that Norris\'s democratic reforms in the
DOmain of Deneb are stretched to the limits (at TL/15-16) in some of the last
TNE material ... but does this mean that the Confederation couldn\'t have done
exactly what a Confederacy is supposed to do ... provide a moderately strong
central government with limited powers (such as defence, protection of trade
etc.) and let the member states go their own way on their own planets? Who
would gain most from these sorts of reforms ... the ordinary people, especially
those of the collapsed and dictatorial Ziru Sirka ... and who desperately
wanted to protect their priviliged positions? The Confederate military and the
Vilani nobility!

>      The TC advance to TL 12 stuffed the Vilani because this was something
> completely new to which much of the "book" did not apply.

> This allowed the Terrans to break out and defeat the Vilani much more
> quickly and decisively than would otherwise have been the case.

And, coupled with the Terrans massive *materiel* advantage!

> Note on Vilani food supply and disease:

>      The Shulagii (sp?) who held the "secrets to food preparation" on Vland
> retained their hold on food production even when other sources were found.
> The widespread disruption to Vilani society and commerce during and after
> the Wars could have caused food shortages which lowered the Vilani immunity
> to disease and actual starvation on inhospitable worlds!

But only Vland is inhospitable in that way. Though you *are* essentially
correct, though not on an interstellar scale as much as on each planet. For
millennia, farmworkers have been forced to labour for a pittance and not
allowed to go to the "big city" where easier work and better money can be found
(or so they think). Now, the Terrans have destroyed (or damaged) the old social
strictures, and, suddenly, a hell of a lot of peasants do just that -- food
production plummets, and the excess new population in the cities finds that
things ain\'t so rosy. Disease and some starvation inevitably result.

Phil McGregor

> Date: Fri, 22 Mar 1996 18:26:14 +0900 (JST)
> From: ayersl@mibai.inforyukyu.or.jp
