> Why is life as we know it based on left-handed proteins and right-handed
> sugars?

<Interesting facts snipped for brevity>

> As you can see, I\'m not 100% up on the theory, but it seems there\'s a
> basis for assuming life will almost all be the right way round,
> chemically speaking. Thus, you don\'t *need* panspermia as a hypothesis
> for this to be true (although you might want panspermia to be correct
> anyway).

Interesting. But consider this, slight damage to a (Terran) organism\'s RNA/DNA
code can have tremendous consequences ... so, presumably, slight differences
between the chemical composition of left-handed proteins and right-handed
sugars could have similar differences? Also, there is the underlaying
assumption, is there not, that the path evolution has taken on earth is the
"best" path ... and this may not be the case. It may be *one* of a number of
equally viable "paths", may it not?

Obviously my reading is more general in nature than your specific knowledge, so
I will bow to your explanation for the rest of the First Imperium. However,
this leaves just as big a problem ... how did Vland come to be? If the tendency
is to have all life more or less compatible over a long enough period of time
(which is what I understand by the theory you are describing ... by all means
correct me if I am wrong!), then Vland is *mega* atypical. In fact, we could
say that it is probably close to unique ... and, thus, Vilani medical knowledge
becomes as per normal Terran standards once they get offplanet and find the
connections between organisms and diseases that, by the above theory, seems as
though must be the case everywhere else. See what I mean? It\'s a lose-lose
proposition for that particular argument about Vilani medicine no matter what
the outcome is (if I understand your theory description, as I noted).

Thus, the plague of Duskir is a nonsense as well. And GenAssist is a poorly
thought through DGP "last gasp". Like I said, lose-lose for the DGP
"explanation".

Phil McGregor

