Yes. Sure. Agreed. But it is as likely as not *based on current knowledge*. It
may, indeed, be wrong ... or right ... or *both* theories may be wrong. This is
all we can do when we are looking at Traveller ... base our arguments on what
the designers knew when they designed it. Would they make the same sort of
assumptions today? Would Vland type worlds be more common? Who knows? The point
is, based on what they have placed in canon so far, Vland type worlds are (as
far as we can tell) members of a class of *one* ... *unique*. And all other
worlds are basically terra type (as far as the nature of planetary life is
concerned), as long as they *are* basically Terra type. Ergo, either Vland is
a major anomaly that needs a *hell* of a lot more explanation, or the
assumption that all other worlds are like Terra is flawed.

Then, consider the reason for this particular thread of the argument. The
Vilani are *supposedly* backward in medical tech because of their lack of terra
style organisms back home. But what the rest of the Traveller materials seems
to make plain, and what you seem to be arguing is, is that Vland is *not*
going to be unique ... and that Terra-style worlds will be at least equally as
common. You will note that I originally accepted *both* possibilities, and
that, regardless of which one you accept, it is obvious that the Vilani must
have encountered terran style diseases as soon as they left the planet and
started exploring. Ergo, Vilani medical science was primitive *until they
started space exploration* ... *after* that it would have had to have kept
up pace in leaps and bounds. 2000 years down the track when the Terrans are
encountered, well, the Vilani medical tech is not significantly different from
that Terra possessed. If anything, because of the wider disease exposure that
they have inevitably had, *they* are more likely to be the ones who would
trash terran disease tech!

