had this to say:

>Subject: Wiseman on J-Torps
>
>       I don\'t know if anybody posted/mentioned this, but here\'s
>what I just found in my archive:  part of a reply by Loren Wiseman
>dating from Sept. 93 or so... (bundle 500?)
>
>" Scott KelloGG
> > we can now build Jump torpedoes again.
> It wasn\'t a misprint...we intended to allow smaller jump capable
>vessels.
>My guess would be that a jump capable ship could be built at about 15
>tons
>hull size (you need fuel, controls, power plant, etc, in addition to
>drives). Anybody done one already?
>"
>
>        He was referring to the FF&S book.
>
>        So it seems that J-Torps ARE canon (as far as TNE is canon
><snicker> :) from a design point of view.
..

  What I won\'t do now is give my opinion of people who snicker at the
demise of GDW or any other game company...


  Yes, FF&S brings down several old rules of ship-building. The two which
come to mind are the turrets-per-ton limit and the minimum displacement
to mount jump drives.  Both were done with two intentions: to bring more
concrete factors into play when designing (not enough room/power/crew for
the desired function) instead of some arbitrary limit, and to allow FF&S
to be used for non-Imperial settings.
  Despite the second reason, both limitations were also lifted from the
Third Imperium setting.  This was unstated until the Regency Sourcebook,
when designs appeared which made it clear that the 100 ton minimum was
gone.
  So be it.
  "How do you explain continuity with earlier editions?" you ask.
First, these were both _legal_ limits placed by the Ziru Sirka on all
shipbuilding, which became _traditional_ limits (the way the Vilani like
things to be...) during the long First Imperium, were re-affirmed by the
overly-legislative Solomani, and carried as law and tradition into the
Long Night and the Third Imperium.  No shipyard would build outside of these
limits for thousands of years.
  There is almost certainly an extensive body of medical and engineering
research which "proves" that starship hulls smaller than 100 tons are
a health/life risk to their crews.
  How does this explain the other races?  First, the Zhodani are a deeply
traditional people.  Somewhere back in antiquity they found a formula
which worked and have found no reason to ever exceed it.  The Vargr
shipbuilding credo was strongly influenced by first the Zhodani and then the
Vilani, waaay back when (read the old Vargr Module and the material on
the Julian Protectorate). The K\'kree and Aslan have to deal with immense
cultural restraints when designing ships: The K\'kree are gregarious
claustrophobes who wouldn\'t build a ship that small for any reason and have
trouble arming a ship even close to the limits because of space/power/crew
concerns, while the Aslan are creatures of Art, and arming a ship to the
teeth is not aesthetic.  The Hivers have some space concerns, but are ALWAYS
concerned with appearances: never appear more powerful than your neighbors
(unless they\'re K\'kree), as you might get a bad response that could disrupt
business and make you build warships.
  There is one other factor which cannot be completely ignored: perception.
The vast majority of the material available for Traveller is presented
through Imperial eyes, and the Imperium is not going to allow widespread
distribution of information which says "Our neighbors are breaking different
laws of nature than we are, and are building better ships than we are,
despite our technological edge." We didn\'t see such ships because we weren\'t
supposed to.

  AS for J-Torps, the above quote from Loren is indicative of the engineering
concerns.  Given the stated requirements for operating a jump drive, a J-Torp
is going to be huge. Design away.

