    'body' => '> From: Rob_Prior@nynet.nybe.north-york.on.ca (Rob Prior)
> Subject: Re: Babies
>
> If we assume a technology such as Bujold\'s \'uterine replicators\' (ie. a
> functional artificial womb) then having a child will not necessarily remove a
> woman from the work force.  Given that assumpion, and further linking that
> with cloning and a.i. means that _anyone_ can become a parent (in the sense
> of being a primary caregiver).

But such are not mentioned anywhere in Traveller material. Sure, you *can*
assume that they are available ... however, *if* they were of significance,
surely they would have been mentioned *somewhere* previously. Now, if Marc
Miller comes out with Trav4 and says, in the Interstellar Wars Milieu Book that
these *were* the reason for the Terran victory, well, I can accept this
justification after the fact. However, DGPs explanation smacks of the wild-eyed
ideas such as the Sparklers which, I presume, got them dumped by GDW at the end
(at least partly?). It is mentioned nowhere in the original *Solomani*, where,
surely, it should have been?

> Can robots help?  I have my doubts about robotic parents, but a robotic house
> would certainly help reduce the scutwork of parenting, leaving more time for
> other pursuits.  (Imagine: a machine that could pick up after your toddler!)

But, as a Teacher, I would suggest that this is the *least* part of raising
kids (well, not seriously ... I\'m sure any parents out there wouldn\'t agree
with mee). The problem is, regardless of how you look at it, how safe can
non-AI robots be around small children? I suggest that few (if any) parents
would allow them to do anything much re *raising* the kid ... and there are
already labour saving devices aplenty that reduce housework etc. *right now*.
No, robotic nannies are an expensive, and probably unnecessary, addition.

> Personally, I visualize a Terran colony as being a place where _everyone_
> (married or not) is socially expected to raise children.  Families are large,
> with the older children helping out.  Because there is a lot of automation,
> most workplaces are safe enough for children, and there is no social stigma
> attached to bringing a child to work; more importantly, there is no social
> stigma attached to devoting yourself full-time to childrearing.  Childrearing
> (in a couple) is a responsibility of both parents, not primarily the woman.
> Children are supported by the state; in fact, there are probably economic
> incentives that make childrearing \'profitable\' and penalize childless people.

But there is no justification for this. In fact, everything we have for
Traveller from the word go assumes male/female equality in all fields. And,
since robotic child-care is needlessly dangerous and (I suspect) excessively
expensive, that\'s not an option. It still boils down to how many children
people will want to have ... and more than 3 (*many* more for the growth rates
suggested by others) would be a minimum necessity. Assuming that present day
social trends continue, no-one is going to stand for that sort of time
consuming effort ... and even with day care and the like, kids still take a
hell of a lot of effort. That\'s the way the trend is now, and there is no
reasonable expectation that it will change ... and the fact that women can now
control their own fertility and have their own careers mean that being a
homemaker is increasingly *not* No 1 in their priorities ... at least, not in
Oz.

Is your suggestion possible? Yes? Likely? Not very, in my opinion (FWIW).

Phil McGregor


