    'body' => '>Date: Sun, 24 Mar 96 11:53:30 PST
>From: James Kundert <james@dumbcat.sf.ca.us>

>AS for J-Torps, the above quote from Loren is indicative of the engineering
>concerns.  Given the stated requirements for operating a jump drive, a J-Torp
>is going to be huge. Design away.

Actually, a J-torp doesn\'t need to be NEARLY that large.  That 15 ton figure 
includes fuel, controls, power plant, and just about everything needed to have a
  miniature little starship.  For not much more, you could add crew, a fixed 
mount weapon, and a little bunk: PRESTO you have a miniature little jump capable
  fighter craft.  Someone ought to design one of these, just for kicks. :) Sort 
of the Traveller version of the X-Wing fighter.

But a J-torp needn\'t be nearly this complex.

All you need is a little computer and a jump drive.  No power plant or fuel is 
needed.  The drive\'s capacitors are charged by the launching vessel, which
  also imparts inertia to the torp through its launching mechanism.  Once it 
reaches it comes in-system at the target location, it can sit around like a
  little Nav buoy and wait to be picked up by dedicated tender vessels.  The 
end result is a replacement of the generic X-boat courier line with unmanned
  J-torp message couriers.

A device like this would have tons of drawbacks.  For military courier use, its 
basically worthless since its unsecure and not tactical (bad idea to send one
  of these to communicate with someone hiding in an enemy system).  They\'d be 
nice for launching as a log buoy in the event of some catastrophic emergency on
  the starship.  The sheer size of one of these things (still in the 5-10 ton 
range) means that only larger vessels are likely to carry any at all,
  particularly since the launching mechanism has to be custom designed into the starship as well.  Only the larger ships of the line 
are likely to carry more than a small handful (2-4) of these things.  Like
  the X-boat, J-torps require dedicated tender vessels to care for them.  Just 
about anything with a cargo bay might concievably pick up one of the things,
  and maintenance could be done in the cargo bay, but getting the thing back 
into its launcher tube would be tricky, and best performed in port (unless 
you\'re
  a tender, cu! stom designed for the mission of launching and retrieving drone J-torps.

Without much extra work, a drone could be designed that has just enough of a 
robotic brain to fire some simple thrusters and home in on a target planet.
  Designed with an airfoil, some terminal guidance software, and a little 
turbine engine all you need is a warhead to create a J-Tomahawk cruise missile.
  Such nightmarish devices could (in sufficient numbers) be the scourge and 
plague of inhabited systems throughout the universe.  Of course the only reason
  those goofy Vampire Fleets don\'t just annihilate a
ll human life in the former Imperium is because they don\'t have the 
manufacturing capability to produce such weapons, since Imperial shipyards all 
conform to
  the 100ton limit.  Still, 100tons of automated Scout/Courier hell could carry 
one enormous fusion warhead (strip fuel, vehicle, and crew space, charge Jump
  capacitors externally, and fill all remaining space with one incredible bomb).

Hmm . . . does anyone remember Darkstar?  :)

Dave


