by referees, or material not mentioned in the basic rules but fleshed out in
widely-accepted "non-canon" magazine articles, etc.  Do we have to follow
Holy Writ from the Divine Miller or can we make reasonable assumptions based
on existing technology (this being, after, all, *science* fiction)?

For what it\'s worth, here is the actual material from Solomani & Aslan
(which you can argue about as "canon" all you want, Phillip -- the fact
remains that during the MegaTraveller years GDW largely abrogated
responsibility for Traveller development to DGP, concentrating instead on
T2K, Dark Conspiracy, and that dud Cadillacs & Dinosaurs).

S&A p.20 "GenAssist first sought to genetically alter Terran and alien
lifeforms so that food supply was not a problem.  Next, GenAssist sought
to increase the birth and growth rates of the colonists, expanding their
populations in record time.  Although our ancestors were eager colonists,
most sought to settle on habitable worlds.  Unfortunately, most worlds were
not suited for humans, but these same worlds often had the best resources
for a rapidly growing interstealler civilization.  Plus, we needed workers
to increase our productivity.

"Once again, GenAssist offered a solution.  Once established on a world
with a hostile environment, GenAssist set up \'artificial wombs\' producing
thousands of infants per year.  A staff of a few human and robot nurses
cared for these budding populations.  Others educated these new \'test-tube\'
colonists using tapes feeding the subconscious mind.  Using these techniques,
we could establish a fully productive, heavily populated colony world in
under twenty years."

Much of that has already been stated -- I just thought I\'d provide the
original text.  No copyright infringement is intended: this text is
reproduced purely for the purpose of example and debate.

On the same note, Phillip, I note that your much-vaunted MegaTraveller
Referee\'s Companion notes, on p. 28, that Medical Technology allows "limb
regeneration" at TL9, and "growth quickening" at TL10.  (Hell, along with
"nerve refusion" at TL11).  What more is needed for "artifical wombs" which
produce new infants rather than copies/clones of existing full-grown
individuals?

p. 35 of the same book mentions how "in -2389 the Terran Confederation Navy
commissioned a line of mass-produced tech level 12 robots as support staff
for military personnel.  These were not warbots as we know them today.  A
few of the robots were expert medical robots or served as administrative
support, but most were heavy-duty, hard-working construction robots, used
to build temporary installations for advanced bases."  Sounds like they
were a bit more capable than you give them credit for.

You are welcome, Phillip, to build your own Interstellar Wars campaign any
way you like.  Just don\'t be so cock-sure of yourself that you try to make
everyone else play the same way.

