    'topic' => 'Population Matters',
    'body' => '> From: jlockett@hanszen.rice.edu (Joseph L Lockett)
> Subject: The Ongoing Population Debate
>
> Phillip, I have to start off by saying that I\'m finding your arguments, in
> general, tiresome and offensive.  I think much of this trouble may be
> explained by your assertion a few digests back that:
>
> Phillip McGregor <aspqrz@sydney.DIALix.oz.au> writes:
> > I think the intellectual exercise of the argument is more fun than the
> > topic itself, in general!
>
> And, sure enough, you seem to revel more in the argument, quoting reams of
> unnecessary text and longwindedly repeating the same arguments from a position
> of utter and complete certitude (rather than the much more friendly, and
> "scientific," aura of doubting interest), than in actually listening to
> other\'s points and objections.  You seem to care far more about showing off
> yourself rather than actually trying to find a reasonable, let alone
> compromise, position.  I think that\'s unfortunate (and would love to be
> wrong), since you have indeed brought up a fascinating topic.

If that\'s the way I come across, I must apologise. It is not intentional -
probably too many years teaching, I spose. That said, however, I do not
necessarily agree with your summation (of course!), as I do not see that I
should agree with something that seems to me to have been sloppily dealt with
(whether that is by GDW or whoever) or contradictory or ambiguous. Sure, I may
well be wrong on a wide variety of issues, and I am more than happy to admit
it when someone can show that it is the case (as I provisionally did some
months ago with the Plague of Duskir ... until I found the source and the
exact details, which did *not* support the contention{s} of the person{s} who
had used it!). Anyway, I\'ll try to be more brief in argument, at least.

> > ...it is obvious that the Vilani must have encountered Terran-style
> > diseases as soon as they left the planet and started exploring. Ergo,
> > Vilani medical science was primitive *until they started space exploration*:
> > *after* that it would have had to have kept up pace in leaps and bounds.
> > ...If anything, because of the wider disease exposure that they have
> > inevitably had, *they* are more likely to be the ones who would trash
> > Terran disease tech!
>
> Well, you\'re glossing over (intentionally or unintentionally, I can\'t tell)
> the difference between bacteria and viruses.  It is, indeed, more than likely
> that, for example, Vilani medicine had to deal with, say, intestinal parasites
> (like tapeworms) and simple bacteria, particularly when they got off-planet.
> However, given that the genetic code (not the _existence_ of DNA/RNA, which
> seem very practical and natural methods, but the _cipher_ of combinations of
> adenine, tyrosine, etc. that correspond to specific amino acids) is probably
> completely different on all other worlds, the Vilani would have no experience
> with viruses -- extraterrestrial viruses invading human cells would produce
> useless gibberish and not reproduce, assuming they ever managed the invasion
> in the first place through completely different cell membranes and defenses.

I am not intentionally (or unintentionally) glossing over the difference
between viruses and bacteria. I am assuming that, whether you assume Panspermia
or simply convergent evolution (or whethever), analogues of *both* are likely
to be present off Vland. This may be incorrect ... but what I understand of the
arguments presented by some others re developments in Oxford (?) that seem to
show that certain types of proteins and sugars (?) are more likely to occur in
life (even extraterrestrial life) than not. If you disagree with this, and I
am bowing to superior knowledge here, then you don\'t have an argument with me.
If you assume Panspermia, which was *my* original position, then all life -
except that on Vland, for some reason, is massively more likely than not to be
related ... and in that case, then the Viruses and Bacteria will be compatible
to some considerable degree. Since this seems to be supported by the fact that
Traveller has made provisions for animal encounters to be *edible* without
special preparation in the past, I have assumed that Vland is unique and the
rest of the planets are populated via Panspermia. This may well be a big ask,
but no more than assuming that animals on widely separated planets are edible
by humans! See what I\'m getting at here?

> To put that more simply, if Terran organisms code asparagine as, say, TGA,
> but Vilani organisms signify it by CTG, then viruses, which reproduce by
> hijacking the host cell\'s genetic machinery, are unlikely to work.
>
> The absence of viable animal models -- ones which have the same biochemical
> cycles and internal workings on a fine scale -- would handicap Vilani medicine
> as has been described.  They\'d learn how to deal with parasites, sure, but
> imagine their horror on meeting the Solomani and encountering diseases which
> hijacked their own genetic machinery in order to reproduce!  They would never
> have encountered such a thing, and have no countermeasures against it.

Yes, but given my proposition, based on what Traveller seems to be implying,
this would *not* be the first time they would have found something like it. In
any case, even if my position is flawed by being too big a jump, then have you
considered that, just like the proto-Vilani in effect brought their own
bacterial diseases *with* them (and they then mutated to be diseases or not),
they probably also brought viruses that may originally have been relatively
benign (or controllable by Ancient tech). And there were, I believe, something
in excess of 40 offplanet "plantings" of humans by the Ancients *that
survived*. All the more chance for this to happen ... and none of whom had the
food problems facing the Vilani, when, if you assume *no* Panspermia, they
would have more likely than not have faced very similar ones. And that doesn\'t
include those planets where the *humans* didn\'t survive, but other Terran
animals did ... and there was at least one world that was identified as an
Ancient Zoological preserve known to the Ziru Sirka before contact with the
Solomani. It looks to *me* that the current "canon" handles the matter with
*considerable* ambiguity that seems to support my side more than yours, though
indirectly, of course.

> > Note that the Terrans only reached TL/12 *at the end* of the wars, *not*
> > at the beginning where the population growth would have had to have been.
>
> Phillip, this is balderdash.  Do you actually read your sources, or just
> argue about them?  Supplement 10 (The Solomani Rim) states rather clearly,
> as I recall, that jump-3 was invented during the 8th or 9th Interstellar
> War, and was what allowed a breakout around the Vilani defenses.  This still
> leaves quite a bit of time until the end of the Nth Interstellar War.  And
> we know that technology can lag or run ahead of a society\'s nominal "tech
> level" (I think it\'s been stated that the Solomani, despite being TL9,
> lacked gravitics until after Vilani contact).  So I see no problem with
> the Vilani having TL12 _medical_ technology well before the 8th or 9th War.

Well, *is* it balderdash? According to Alien Module #6: Solomani (page #5),
indicates that the invention occurred after the end of the 8th Interstellar
War, and the 9th as the time of said invention. In MTrav Ref\'s Companion (page
#34) Terran invention of J3 is dated at -2210. In MTrav ImpEncyc (page #6) the
beginning of the Nth Interstellar War is -2235 and end at 2219. However, it
does not indicate when the 8th or 9th Wars were ... or whether they were part
of the "Nth" war or not. However, it is *implied* that they were ... and the
invention of J3 is only 9 years before the end of the Nth Interstellar war.
So, think about it from the point of the original thrust of the post ... that
the Terrans must have been able to *outproduce* the Vilani as they certainly
did not outnumber them. Remember construction times for Traveller Ships (a
large vessel takes a minimum of 12 months and up to 60 months for the larger
ones) ... in nine years, how many j3 ships would the Terrans have been able to
produce? Most of their fleet must (unless you assume the sort of massive
productivity disparity that I have suggested) still have been J2. It smacks of
the German situation at the end of WW2, in some ways ... a handful of hi-tech
weapons against the massive lower tech weapons of the enemy. There *has* to be
more to it than *just* J3 units. Does that sound more reasonable?

> I acknowledge and approve of your conspiratorial view of the changeover from
> Terran Confederation to Rule of Man, but wish you\'d be slightly less sure of
> yourself in argument, and more willing to listen and respond to others.

I hope that the above is more reasoned and to your liking. I\'m trying, anyway!

Phil McGregor

