    'body' => '> From: Summers@Ethyl-the-Frog.ARC.NASA.gov (David P. Summers)
> Subject: Re: Terran Federation: How Large a Pop?
>
> Um, first of all, the problem with Vland is not (as you imply, I don\'t
> know if that is intentional) is bacause the biosphere is based on
> the wrong amino acids, because that would make everything inedible.

Well, as you will note, the problem with amino acids wasn\'t something I came up
with, it was suggested in another post as (as I understood it) a proposition
that Vland style worlds were not terribly likely. I was simply following on
from that ... based (IIRC) on the research of an Oxford Biochemist.

> I don\'t know anything in "canon" that says that Vland worlds are
> unique.  All you can say is that, of the human races important enough
<snip>

No, they don\'t. However, the Animals system allows for animal encounters to be
edible ... and in all of the adventures I can remember offhand (not all by any
means, I stand happy to be corrected) that are on worlds with an inhabitable
biosphere (i.e. not like "Across the Bright Face" ??) the assumption, often
quite implicitly, is that the local food is edible with no special preparation.
Also, for example, Aslan are not said to have any special food requirements and
can exist (co-exist) quite happily on the same worlds as Terrans ... also
implying that they can eat the same foods we do. Sure. it doesn\'t say
*specifically* that Vland is unique, it just seems to be the way everything
else is described shows that it either is, or very close to.

<snip>

> >You will note that I originally accepted *both* possibilities, and
> >that, regardless of which one you accept, it is obvious that the Vilani must
> >have encountered terran style diseases as soon as they left the planet and
> >started exploring.
>
> No here too.  The reason the above is not important is that the edibility
> of local organisms need not have anything to do with the problem
> of viral contagion.  As we both have mentions, you virus are very
> dependend on the detail of an organisms genetics and it is possible
> that the Vilani didn\'t find an ecosystem that posed a threat of
> viral disease until Terra.

Yes, OK. I accept that. I think you\'re not necessarily right. Remember, I am
assuming that Panspermia is the reason for all this. I may well be wrong, but
I think the evidence supports me (admittedly in a negative kind of way) at
least as much as the science you present supports you. And, though you won\'t
accept it, it still boils down to the fact that this wasn\'t the main point of
the original post.

Also, consider this, there were 42 (IIRC) other human groups transplanted by
the Ancients, and (IIRC) these were only the ones that survived. There was also
at least one world that was a major zoological facility (Dinorb? I don\'t
remember offhand) where many terran organisms were found ... well before the
Terrans were encountered. Every time they encountered one of these worlds, even
the ones where the Terrans didn\'t survive, there is a chance that bacteria and
viruses that had mutated there would be dangerous to the Vilani, so there is
a good chance that the Vilani would have overcome their initial difficulties
- though not certain, of course (happy?).

> You can waffle and back-track all you want, but you were attempting to
> score cheap points by attempting a personal attack on my personal
> knowledge.  (Had I not found your arrogance and close mindedness so
> ammusing I would have been offended)  Not only do I not lack a "basic
> scientific knowledge", but I have specific experience in the field of
> exobiology.  I presume now that you are abandoning such tatics (I knew an
> apology was too much too expect).

I apologise of you think I was intending to score points (cheap or not) off
you. I was not. If you took it that way, it was not intended. However, on the
substantive matters - I assumed from you arguments that you lacked a knowledge
that you had *at that point* made no claim to possess. I am quite happy to
acknowledge that you possess it. Does that make your arguments right
automatically any more than mine are?

> You really need to review the difference between "opinion" and "fact".
> Just because you believe something doesn\'t make it logically true.

No, but almost all of this argument has to be based on opinion. We have found
no alien worlds to check the *opinions* of either of us or of the designers of
Traveller out against.

> >As you have just yourself said, it is just as possible (or you can\'t
> >say it *isn\'t* just as possible, because we don\'t know) that terran style
> >organisms will be common everywhere ... so the Vilani get exposed to terran
> >style diseases and have to come up with the same sort of solutions.
>
> It is possible that you are right.  But your claim is that the Traveller
> background is wrong.  You are quick to talk about logic, lets review
> it.  You can\'t prove that something (in this case the Traveller background)
> is wrong buy showing how something else _might_ be right.

And that works as much against your position as mine. Think of this more as
being "balance of probabilities" than "observable scientific fact".

> >Is it arrogance to point out flaws in GDW\'s background?
>
> Nope.  But it is arrogant to attack someones background and abilities
> because they disagree with you.

And I have not done so since you pointed out that you possessed them. I am not
a Zhodani ... I can\'t read your mine.

> >Remember, we are not substantially arguing chemisty (or biochemistry) here, w
> >are arguing how it affects a very specific matter ... Vilani medical knowledg
> >at the time they contact Terra.
>
> Well, no.  You are trying to change the arguement because your cheap little
> tatic has back fired.  The fact is that the lack abilty of Vilani to
> fit themselves into a rational theory of biology (based on how different
> life on other planets might be) and the fact that they might, when they
> came in contact with Terra, encounter diseases they weren\'t prepared for
> were main issues, both of which are fundamentally issue in Exobiology.

And both of which I have offered plausible alternatives too ... more plausible,
as far as I am concerned, than the one offered by GDW, FWIW. That doesn\'t mean
that I\'m right and they\'re wrong ... not at all. However, I believe that the
flaws arise from the knowledge that was available at the time when the original
design was done and that the arguments we\'re using to attack (or defend) the
matter are based on facts that have since come to light ... or, to be more
correct (since there are no exobiospheres to compare them against) the latest
scientific *opinions*.

<snip>

> >What I said above was that Panspermia means that all life is related ... ther
> >*are* no "alien biospheres" ... and so the Vilani, with their unique and
> >atypical biosphere, are exposed to diseases that *are* related to terran ones
> >as soon as they leave their own planet.
>
> But nothing you have said require panspermia.  And without panspermia,
> it is easy to believe that the Vilani, when they came in contact with
> Terra, encounter diseases they weren\'t prepared for

Well, this is where we differ, for some of the reasons I\'ve mentioned above. I
guess we\'ll have to agree to disagree.

> >Don\'t take this as a personal attack on your professional qualifications.
>
> Fine, don\'t define lacking in "basic scientific knowledge" as "he happens
> to disagree with me".

And don\'t whinge if you get called out on something because you haven\'t noted
that you possess it, if we\'re getting down to tin-tacks.

Phil McGregor

