    'topic' => 'Vilani Doctors',
    'body' => '> From: "Edgar W. Francis, IV" <gar@ucla.edu>
> Subject: Re: Vilani medical tech
>
> At 05:29 AM 24/03/96 -0500, you wrote:

> First of all, every indication is that Vilani medical science is *still*
> lagging behind, and it\'s not that hard to explain:  the Vilani just don\'t
> value doctors.  As the culture evolved on Vland, food preparers held the
> real keys to power, and any sort of doctor was just a technician to take
> care of bleeding, broken bones, etc.  As they encountered other worlds, the
> anmount of technical knowledge they had to acquire was greater, but that
> doensn\'t necessarily mean that their status increased any.  Imagine how many
> people would go to medical school in the U.S. if, after you got out, you got
> about the same pay and societal status as a high school teacher.  Not too
> many, I\'d wager.

Actually, though I\'m not sure that you\'re right about the "present" (i.e. c
1100, Imperial, say), you *are* right, come to think of it (or more likely than
not) ... there is a statement *somewhere* to the effect that the Vilani always
considered the potential effects of tech (esp., IIRC, *medical* tech) before
they release it ... sometimes, it is implied, for generations, perhaps even
hundreds of years. This is actually a good explanation ... though it needs a
little more work. You could, for example, also assume that the Vilani *had* the
tech to deal with Terran diseases ... back in hi-security labs back on Vland or
some of the interior sectors, and didn\'t (or were slow to) release it when it
was needed. This may well explain the evident fact that some of the Vilani
dominated worlds more or less went over to the Solomani ... perhaps the failure
of the Vilani to "give a damn" meant that they welcomed the terrans because
*they* seemed to?

Phil McGregor

> From: Rob_Prior@nynet.nybe.north-york.on.ca (Rob Prior)
> Subject: Re: Babies (again)
>
> >as a Teacher, I do not believe that I would want to have anything to do
> >with any society where children are substantially raised and educated by
> >robots. Think of the long term socialisation problems alone!
>
> But as a teacher, imagine a school where robots handle all the routine
> gruntwork, leaving you free to concentrate on your students.  I know I spend
> nearly half of my time dealing with non-kid issues (in spite of what the
> Ontario Minister of Education thinks).

Yep, I can sympathise with that. Of course, tho you have a *definite* point,
just consider this ... some damn bureacrat somewhere is going to figure, "Well,
those lazy so-and-so\'s have all this extra time on their hands that they\'re
probably wasting, so lets demand that they fill in these extra forms ..." ...
and, bang goes all the "extra" time you had, for all of five seconds, no doubt!

Phil

