> Summary:
>
> Phil and I disagree about Terran population growth.  I argue that
> reproductive technology is not inconsistent with existing Traveller canon,
> indeed can even be considered as being implied.  I also argue that the
> primary factors in a rapidly expanding population would be cultural not
> technological.
>
> ----
>
> Well, major mills aren\'t mentioned in Roman literature and inscriptions, but
> they existed and ground a large proportion of the grain.  And for a long time
> very few civilian vehicles were published in Traveller, most equipment was
> military, etc.  The absence of something just indicates that no one wrote
> about it.  Hey, look at cargo containers.  Not mentioned at all until MTJ 3,
> when they became \'canon\'.  (I wrote that one, along with grashfalt and quite
> a few others.)

True, and fair enough. I\'ll go along with that.

I even agree about cloning. I *still* think that the limitation is the lack of
a memory transfer facility (and we disagree with this, too) ... *and* the
economic limitations, which hasn\'t been considered fully (cost of robots and
all that).

> Why use a robotic nanny?  Playing with your kids is the fun part.  Use the
> robot to do the boring jobs.  Housework takes a tremendous amount of time,
> when you add it up, even with labour-saving devices.  Cooking, cleaning, etc
> take me many hours a week, anyway, and I don\'t have any kids living with me
