> historically, been used for power tools, spin driers, and many other
> labour-saving appliances.  Design in good safeguards (eg. robot doesn\'t clean
> while living creature is in room).

Cost is still a problem.

> Nor reason against it.  There is simply nothing written on daily life in the
> Terran Confederation.  This is my view.  (OK, one of my views - I figure the
> Terran Confederation had a _lot_ of different cultures.)

Aha! But a little bird informs me that there *will* be, for Trav4! We\'ll see
how it turns out, shall we?

> >It still boils down to how many children people will want to have ...
>
> True.  I\'m trying to come up with a culture/society that will make them want
> to have lots of kids, and make it easy for them to have lots.

And that\'s where the problem is. Not impossible ... and, perhaps, it *will* be
the case in the above project (and *official* Trav4 one, but don\'t ask me
details of who and what!) ... but, FWIW, I suspect that it would take some
*real* mental contortions to do so.

As for the rest <snipped> re reasons for small families at present. I accept
and understand what you\'re getting at, I just am not convinced that you\'re on
the right track. We\'ll have to wait 50 years or so and see, I spose (if the Mad
Cow disease doesn\'t get us first!).

Phil

