    'topic' => 're: Babies in xboat 570',
    'body' => 'While I have generally skipped these historical arguments about the
canon-challenged explanation for Terran/Vilani population levels at and
immediately following the fall of the Vilani Empire, the following struck me:

> However, DGPs explanation smacks of the wild-eyed
>ideas such as the Sparklers which, I presume, got them dumped by GDW at the end

Um, no. DGP wanted to move onto other projects, was taking too much money
away from GDW (from GDW\'s viewpoint), and the Traveller:TNE project turned
their stomachs. AFAIK.

>> Can robots help?  I have my doubts about robotic parents, but a robotic house
>> would certainly help reduce the scutwork of parenting,

>But, as a Teacher, I would suggest that this is the *least* part of raising
>kids
> The problem is, regardless of how you look at it, how safe can
>non-AI robots be around small children? I suggest that few (if any) parents
>would allow them to do anything much re *raising* the kid...

You miss the goal here.  To mass-produce (mass-raise) children
produced by artificial wombs, you are dealing with products rather than
individual children.  Robotic houses/barracks/schools with labor-saving
devices and monitors would allow a few overseer/parents to take care of
many more kids than a traditional household.  Less "human," perhaps, but
it should turn out adequate soldiers and workers easily enough.

Consider reading CJ Cherryh\'s books that deal with AZI (_Cyteen_ series and
_40,000 in Gehenna_) for an interesting view of artificially raised populations.

>> Personally, I visualize a Terran colony as being a place where _everyone_
>> (married or not) is socially expected to raise children.  Families are large,

>But there is no justification for this. In fact, everything we have for
>Traveller from the word go assumes male/female equality in all fields.

No, but then all the Traveller culture we have seen has occurred some 3000
years after this time.

>since robotic child-care is needlessly dangerous and (I suspect) excessively
>expensive, that\'s not an option.

Certainly robotic child-care is less expensive than being overwhelmed by the
Vilani!  I also disbelieve that it would be "needlessly" dangerous.
Semi-intelligent
design at TL12 need not be particularly dangerous.

>Assuming that present day social trends continue,
A bad assumption.  Less than 100 years ago (heck, less than 50 years ago), large
families were a goal (actually, it was being able to afford a large
family...).  In 1970,
the average family in the US had 3.2 kids - down from earlier times.  That
has dropped
to less than 2 currently in the US.  But it had also been lower (than 3.2)
at other
low points in US economic history (1880s, 1930s)! The number fluctuates - it is
neither constant nor moving in a single direction.

>no-one is going to stand for that sort of time consuming effort
But they did!  And if you go back futher (1400s-1900s), you had as large a
family
as your farm could support - because that provided you with labor!

Let\'s a make a canon assumption - fusion power.  Vast amounts of cheap power
will drop the price of most of anything - allowing one to afford more children.
Particularly when coupled with a dispersion to the stars, would not raising
large
families begin to make sense if only in order to provide a population to
carry on
your particular (sub)culture?

I am not saying this is what occurred.  I am saying that "this could not happen"
is not the case.  Unless you plan to set a campaign IN that time period, I don\'t
see that it matters a lot.

mitch


